text: I'm amazed at this discovery - it's incredible how often I've overlooked this spot... Already, I've visited thrice in just a fortnight. The portions are ideal for a midday meal (a single slice suffices) - they offer excellent salad and pizza pairings for lunch, among other things... Soon, I plan to stop by for an evening meal and order a whole pizza for myself.

The task was completed efficiently without excessive promotion of additional sales. They conducted a comprehensive examination of nearly all components, including air pressure, water, hoses, filters, wipers, tires, and more. The cost for one air filter and synthetic oil totaled approximately $120.

While it doesn't quite capture the allure of the Tempe venue, it remains a pleasant establishment nonetheless. The employees tend to be overly trendy, yet they are generally amiable and skilled. We visited primarily for the cuisine, and it certainly did not let us down. I particularly enjoy their versions of the Cheese Steak and the Royale with Cheese. The fries topped with jalapeÃ±os are simply enchanting.

A good spot to spend the weekend with some pals... Weekdays tend to be quiet. The patrons generally skew younger.

The vibe is nice, and there's a big outside area for smokers with direct access to the bartender (no need to re-enter the building). The patio is pleasant when it's not too hot...

Wouldn't be surprised to find Wile E. Coyote here, drowning his sorrows...

An excellent choice for morning or midday meals in central Mesa. The cuisine is notably better than typical, with prices that are quite fair. I frequent this establishment roughly weekly due to its proximity to my workplace. I prefer this local eatery to chain restaurants such as Denny's or Coco's on any given day. They present distinctive specials not listed on the menu, including dishes like grandma's meatloaf, spinach quiche, and blueberry pancakes, available nearly daily.

There's no need to wait; the space is fairly expansive and usually not overly packed. It has the ambiance and appearance of a traditional mid-western diner.

The employees are exceptionally courteous and attentive, quickly remembering patrons' names.

Establishments serving drinks close at 2am, yet this venue offers delivery up until 3am... What a bargain!

I'm quite fond of their broccoli cheese soup, the economical 99-cent side salad, and the "Georgetown" sandwich.

The food is reliably tasty and available for delivery well into the night - truly a godsend. Consider trying them out if they provide service to your location. Their prices are also unexpectedly affordable.
Fantastic Tacos with an excellent selection of salsa... Quick, affordable, tasty, and located in the heart of downtown. An ideal spot for lunch when you're in the city center.

I had the luxury of residing adjacent to the Chapparal Dog Park for many years. Now, this has become my nearest location, and fortunately, it remains a nicely kept area equipped with water, shade, and cleaning tools. However, it provides just one expansive area for all dogs.

Saddle Ranch has been a delightful new presence in the historic district. Since its recent opening, the establishment has seen a steady influx of patrons. Although I haven't had the chance to eat there yet, visiting in the late hours offers a lively experience as you can enjoy a few drinks and observe others being thrown from the mechanical bull. The decor is inspired by cowboy aesthetics, yet the playlist deviates significantly from traditional country tunes (much to my relief), attracting a trendy bar clientele.

No dance floor - a definite plus!

The ambiance doesn't really evoke Ireland, and it's somewhat rundown, but it's a satisfactory, low-key bar for savoring inexpensive beverages with close friends. There's a small exterior area available for smoking. Consider starting your night here. Additionally, it's a laid-back place during weekdays for those seeking a very casual environment to unwind.

The music selection is entirely up to the customers via the jukebox (which can be a gamble).

Significantly improved compared to Mulligans! Excellent work in revitalizing this establishment - its position is outstanding, and the atmosphere is relaxed and cozy. There are two pleasant outdoor terraces that accommodate both smokers and those who enjoy observing passersby.

The cuisine is excellent, especially considering it's a budget-friendly Mexican option. This beloved spot, a local favorite, is conveniently located in my area and I often visit. I choose not to dine in due to the unappealing fluorescent lighting and worn-out decor. Instead, I prefer enjoying my Favoritos at home. It's rumored that some patrons prefer to take their meals to the adjacent Tally Ho (a local dive bar) to savor their tacos alongside a chilled Corona. How bizarre!

For just $2, you can get nachos smothered in cheese and jalapeÃ±os. The tacos and tostadas are simply sublime. Additionally, there's a small salsa bar offering a variety of spice levels and flavors.

Visited J Alexander's for lunch today. Just so you know, El Toritio next door is shut (unclear if it's just for plaza renovations or permanently).

They boast an appealing lunch menu! Available dishes included a New York strip, club sandwich, chicken fried chicken, sea bass, and diver scallops.

The restaurant was quite vacant around noon, evoking the ambiance of a brightly lit Houston's (though caps are allowed here). It must be stunning in the evening.

In summary, the service, food, ambiance, and pricing were all satisfactory. I plan to return.

I must say, this is the least impressive Whole Foods location I've encountered. It resembles a warehouse more than it does a high-end grocery store, and it appears to have a poorer selection compared to other branches I have shopped at before. Should you reside in this area, I recommend visiting AJ's instead.

I had the good fortune of receiving an invitation to attend the Phoenix Suns versus Houston Rockets basketball match on a Saturday evening, where I enjoyed the luxury of watching from a private suite (indeed, a very plush suite).

The game was spectacular, especially with Shaq playing for the Suns, who decisively defeated the Rockets.

Moreover, the US Airways Center proves to be an ideal location, encircled by numerous appealing bar/restaurants that are perfect for gathering before and after the game. We enjoyed a beer at Alice Cooperstown before making our way to the match.

Our car was conveniently parked in a nearby garage, allowing us to walk straight from our vehicle into the stadium with ease.

My sole grievance concerns the overly harsh treatment of smokers, akin to treating us as criminals. I found myself walking half a mile to a designated outdoor area for a smoke several times (a frequent necessity when drinking). While I get that non-smokers prefer not to inhale smoke, it baffles me that such a large venue lacks designated smoking areas. Despite the strong anti-smoking sentiment, it's important to note that smoking remains legal and arguably less harmful than consuming spirits, which are readily available at the venue's bars.

In general, this local bar is quite pleasant.

The establishment boasts an extensive array of bottled beers, showcased in large, chilled display cases that are sure to catch your eye. The cuisine surpasses the typical offerings of a pub. It features a laid-back environment (neat, though unremarkable). Locating it within a vast shopping center can prove to be a bit tricky.

If you're a resident nearby, it's certainly worth stopping by. Otherwise, it might be wise to conserve your fuel.

Complimentary vehicle service ensures your safe arrival and return. Absolutely!

Dukes, characterized by its dive bar ambiance, is expansive and sports-oriented, featuring countless screens, satisfactory cuisine, and very affordable beverages.

Nightly deals include $2 burgers on Mondays, with Karaoke sessions on Wednesday and Saturday. Additionally, there are pool tables, shuffleboard, and a misted patio for those who smoke, among other amenities.

Situated near the old town, it's an ideal spot to kick off your festivities!

Truly a hidden gem :)

I generally have a low opinion of Walmart, but they slightly changed my mind when they offered a prescription for $4 that CVS had priced at $80. Naturally, while waiting for it to be prepared, I ended up spending the $76 I "saved"...

Elegant bar located at the heart of Scottsdale's Old Town. The cuisine is excellent and surprisingly inexpensive given the refined setting. Premium drinks available. I consistently take visitors from out of town to this spot.

This area is also part of my neighborhood...

I've visited on several occasions (for key duplication and purchasing paint). The staff is quite informed and approachable, and both the variety and prices are fair.

It seems we've all grown accustomed to the convenience of big box stores like Home Depot, yet I often find myself favoring the local hardware store :)

It seems possible that Korina confused this location with another, or maybe an ex-boyfriend of hers is employed there...

In my experience, Community Tire ranks as one of the most professional organizations I've dealt with, always fully backing their work.

I've patronized two different Community Tire sites, experiencing impeccable service each time. They are quick, reasonable, and amiable! Additionally, they contribute significantly to the local community.

Undoubtedly, this is the top buffet in Arizona. Truly!

I sampled the sirloin, roast beef, shrimp, mussels, mahi, and pork. Each dish was freshly made and delicious. Additionally, I noticed crab legs, various salads, pasta dishes, pizza, and calamari on offer. Their dessert selection is impressively vast! The setting is contemporary and spacious, featuring a choice of an outdoor patio.

It's advantageous that this place is located within the newly established Talking Stick Resort & Casino, home to a variety of other high-end dining options. *Do visit the bar on the 15th floor during your stay.

In terms of quality, this zoo ranks among the top. Naturally, it's challenging to appreciate any zoo once you've visited the one in San Diego!

This past week, during their spring break, I brought my daughters here and they thoroughly enjoyed it. We decided to try out the paddle boats for the first time. A heads-up: 30 minutes is quite sufficient (no need to opt for an hour unless you're akin to Lance Armstrong). The children were particularly fond of the petting zoo, which essentially is just goats, in my opinion.

The cost to enter the Phoenix Zoo was reasonable: $26 covered entry for all three of us, with an additional $12 for the paddle boats, and about $20 for refreshments and water. We wisely chose to eat lunch prior to our arrival.

Despite it being a Thursday afternoon, the place was unexpectedly busy. We spent several hours there, managed to see most of the animals, and all for under $60.

Terroir presents itself as a charming, small venue for enjoying wine and beer. Tucked away at the rear of the plaza located at Indian Bend and Scottsdale Road, it offers a cozy retreat. Although my date was less than successful, I did discover a delightful new spot that merits another visit.

This area offers a high-end open-air shopping environment, complete with dining options, bars, and cinemas. It is situated right opposite Kierland Commons. Spanning Scottsdale Quarter, Kierland, and the Promenade (all within walking distance), one could swiftly spend all their Powerball earnings.

My experience here has been limited to midday meals, which were delightful. The seafood, particularly the Halibut Cheeks, is superb.

Regarded as one of the top dining spots in the city center, it boasts a refined ambiance, an ideal setting, and exceptionally distinctive dishes. Dining here during the day is genuinely a pleasure.

I plan to visit again soon for an evening meal...

Ideal spot for an affordable, laid-back lunch. It boasts a straightforward cafÃ© ambiance. The chicken teriyaki bowl was delightful, though the egg rolls were somewhat soggy. I plan to return to sample their sushi rolls, which appear popular among other customers.

John's expertise is truly remarkable; he is a highly knowledgeable and passionate optometrist, dedicated to the care of his patients. For those residing on the West side, I strongly suggest consulting John for your yearly eye examinations.

This team surpasses the national chains significantly in terms of service, quality, and expertise.

However, their range of eyewear is somewhat limited. (Therefore, consider purchasing your stylish frames from another location, but let this team handle the fitting of your prescription lenses - and save money in the process).

I really enjoy it here - but I suggest skipping the deep-fried deviled eggs presented to each table. They didn't meet my expectations (despite my fondness for deviled eggs). The remainder of our meal, from the buttery salad to her stuffed chicken and my pork chop with baked beans, was indulgent. The coconut cake dessert was a highlight of my life. Beckett's offers a luxurious dining experience at moderate prices.

Last evening marked my initial visit to Comedor Guadalajara, a vast dining establishment situated in the southern part of Phoenix.

**Positives**: The menu boasts a wide variety of options. The accompanying salsa served with chips is both spicy and tasty. I opted for the "three meat plate" (intended for two), which arrived sizzling on a metal skillet equipped with its own burner, overflowing with generous portions of steak, chicken, pork, jalapenos, and onions. It easily served four people. The taste was outstanding.

**Negatives**: The interior design lacks excitement, and the illumination is excessively bright.

**Neutral Points**: There was nothing displeasing about the venue. Both the staff and other customers were exceptionally welcoming. The restrooms were maintained clean, and the atmosphere around the establishment felt secure even late at night, thanks to a security officer stationed at the entrance.

I've never actually visited the location.

However, I've frequently utilized their offerings through their user-friendly online platform. Phoenix Flower Shops offers a superior service compared to those internet options where flowers are delivered in a box, requiring the receiver to arrange them. My girlfriend really values their expert delivery service.

They are a local business with a fantastic range of products, fair pricing, and punctual delivery.

Visit their website at http://www.phoenixflowershops.com/

Although my favorite is the two-level Tempe site at 101 & University, this place is quite decent too. It's clear from the initial taste that the ingredients they utilize are of high quality. Despite the staff here lacking in professionalism, their sandwiches are exceptionally difficult to surpass.

I've frequented this establishment on several occasions previously, as my office was located nearby.

The venue boasts a welcoming atmosphere with amenities such as a pool table and complimentary wine or beer as you wait, complemented by skilled stylists. They also accept walk-ins.

It's certainly a worthwhile visit when you're in the area. (you might also enjoy visiting Seamus McCaffrey's Irish Pub just across the street afterward)
Among the top quick-service burgers available, the jalapeÃ±o bacon double Whataburger with cheese is a must-try. Absolutely astonishing!

Explore this impressive array of light bulbs suitable for nearly every requirement. The majority are readily available, affordably priced, and prepared for immediate purchase. I've personally presented numerous unmarked, peculiar bulbs for replacement â they consistently deliver outstanding results.

Heed my suggestion and switch your outdated bulbs to LED. For me, the investment is justified simply by the reduction in the frequency of replacements â especially since some of my fixtures are extremely difficult to access, and Halogens generate excessive heat!

Recently launched, this establishment appears to be on the right track. Today, I tried some of their pork ribs and was impressed by the delicious sauce. It's clear that this family-operated business deeply values their ancestral recipes, potentially passed through many generations. I would recommend a bit of enhancement in their decoration, although it's quite minimal since they are newly opened - Wishing them all the best!

"Corny," whose real name is Cornelius, excels as a master electrician and consistently demonstrates immense pride in all his work. I've employed his services multiple times for both residential and commercial projects, and his skill, punctuality, and fair pricing have consistently impressed me. He is truly a reliable professional.

The ambiance is impeccable. A blend of red and dark hues creates a sophisticated vibe. It's typically not overly packed, which suits my preferences perfectlyâno hassle entering, and it's an excellent spot for drinks and conversation. The cocktails are outstanding!

Soon, they plan to expand with a dance floor and a DJ on the upper level...

*UPDATE

I revisited this place not long ago and had a fantastic time. Roughly 20 people were relaxing there on a Thursday evening, making for a lively atmosphere. Additionally, they've reintroduced some food options, featuring an array of appealing appetizers to enjoy.

Fantastic beverages in a TIKI theme! Imagine something akin to Trader Vics, yet situated in a quaint, locally-owned establishment. The cuisine is outstanding, and the beverages are exceptional! It's a wonderful spot to spend the night. Additionally, there's a very pleasant outdoor seating area.

Was this location previously known as the Miracle Mile Deli? It seems so. Now operating as the Park Central Deli, the establishment retains much of its original charm.

Regarded as one of the most frequented spots in downtown Phoenix, it boasts considerable size for a deli. My experience included a delightful pastrami sandwich topped with "straw" (a mix of sauerkraut and cheese). A lighter option featuring turkey is also available. Additionally, the menu includes enchiladas, salads, and a variety of other choices.

For those who enjoy al fresco dining, there's a pleasant patio space available.

The products crafted by this company are of global standard, and it fills me with pride to have such a facility nearby. I'm acquainted with several workers there; they are genuinely humble and exceptionally friendly.

It's unfortunate that Mistress J encountered problems with the Marketing team - maybe a consultation with the Legal team would have been beneficial?

Personally, I play a Gretsch guitar, which Fender distributes, and I absolutely adore it. Previously, I was a staunch supporter of Les Paul, but the Gretsch has won me over.

Cheers to Fender!

If you find yourself at Scottsdale Fashion Square Mall and need a speedy bite, this spot surpasses the mall's food court options. While I wouldn't make a special trip solely for their burgers, they do evoke memories of White Castle from years past.

Does anyone know if there's a White Castle close to the valley?

Absolutely astonishing! This establishment ranks as one of the top venues for Chinese cuisine throughout Scottsdale. I've consistently adored Flo's (located on Frank Lloyd Wright Boulevard); however, this place may have surpassed it. The "house special salad" is simply phenomenal, the shrimp spring rolls brim with shrimp, the egg drop soup surpasses any I've tasted before (abundant with vegetables), and the shrimp fried rice rivals that of Flo's. The couple seated opposite us opted for Kung Pao beef and string beans, which I plan to try on my next visit. George personally expressed his gratitude for our patronage.

Definitely give this place a go if you're a Scottsdale resident - they offer delivery service too!

This could be among the finest Asian dishes you'll ever have the pleasure of tasting. Remarkably, the prices are quite low for lunch as well. Both the house fried rice and the wonton soup achieve absolute perfection. While the Lincoln site is more visually appealing, the culinary quality remains consistent across locations.

Today, I had the pleasure of dining at this charming, quaint restaurant.

The Fettuccine Alfredo reached the pinnacle of culinary excellence, accompanied by a superb salad and exquisite bread. The service was flawless, and the ambiance was exceptionally inviting. My companion chose the Halibut, which appeared to be a special, and it was visually stunning.

I am eagerly looking forward to returning for an evening meal in the near future.

You can find L'amore situated on the South West corner of 32nd and Lincoln.

Simply great BBQ.

The ambiance isn't particularly remarkable (ideal for a lunch outing), yet the BBQ is exceptionally delicious and offers great value. Be sure to sample the pulled pork sandwich and the corn on the cob.

Charming family-operated establishment.

In general, I appreciate this shop and its range of products. However, it frustrates me when large retailers advertise items on their site without clearly stating that these items may not be available in-store (a classic bait-and-switch tactic).

I was interested in purchasing a bicycle and some exercise gear after viewing them online. I decided to visit the store to see them firsthand, only to discover that the specific models I was interested in were "out of stock," and the only similar products available were double the cost. Despite assurances that the items would be in stock soon, a return visit weeks later revealed they were still "en route" - likely from China, I suspect...

So frustrating!

Fantastic meal for a fantastic value!

Eddie attended, accompanied by no fewer than twelve waitstaff.

The cuisine is truly exceptional - genuinely so - Eddie disregards numerous gastronomic norms for our advantage! The service was flawless, the prices reasonable, and the dishes were tasty. Happy to know Cook and Jacks was put to good use.

Cheer for Eddie!

This establishment is a high-end burger venue. Initially, they serve you homemade kettle chips, followed by a "design your own burger" form. The location is excellent, the service is top-notch, the ambiance is contemporary, the food quality is exceptional, and the prices are quite reasonable.

*Their happy hour appears to be quite a deal as well - I plan to go back...

UPDATE - I've returned numerous times since, and their weekend BREAKFAST has become a favorite of mine! They offer a Bloody Mary bar! It's definitely worth trying!

This complex is a behemoth. Several of my acquaintances reside in this overly expansive facility. Yet, its position is ideal, situated right in the heart of the old town. The parking situation is troublesome, featuring a five-story gated garage. It's difficult to have visitors over or even to get a pizza delivery. The pool area has undergone recent renovations.

Generally, I'm not overly fond of chain eateries - however, Sweet Tomatoes genuinely provides good value in the realm of "fast food." Although the salad bar vibe from the 1980s isn't particularly noteworthy, the extensive variety, high quality, and freshness they offer are remarkable, especially considering the cost.

Fantastic spot to pick up a burger alongside a personalized beer...

Definitely sample the Peach beer. Trying out the beer samplers is also enjoyable.

Additionally, there's the option to carry away a "growler" (large bottle) of your preferred drink.

This present is bestowed upon Scottsdale. Despite its modest size, it's astonishing how much personality it exudes. The ambiance, the team, and the cuisine all possess a magical quality. I recommend taking a seat at the bar where you can observe the chefs' meticulous techniques. The pork shank I had was luxurious, as were the leeks. The menu frequently updates and includes ingredients that are organic and sourced from local areas. Additional Advice: Should you find yourself waiting for a seat, Kazimierz is conveniently located adjacent, offering a swift option for a glass of wine.

This certainly isn't Spain. It resembles more a scene where country folks dash away from bulls in a rodeo, whose horns have been blunted. Across the road, there was a modest festival which I enjoyed more. I foresee that this event will expand and evolve, eventually becoming something worth experiencing. Best of luck!

Probably among the best delicatessens throughout the valley. Rumors of its stellar reputation had reached me, and indeed, they did not disappoint.

Both the pastrami and the ruben sandwiches are exceptional, and even the fries impress. Additionally, their black and white cookies are a must-try (though I was too stuffed and had to take one to go). The service is quick, the prices are fair, and the ambiance has a charming, retro feel.

It's a blessing to have such treasures endure in the chain-dominated landscapes of "Tempe Marketplace" and "Mesa Riverview".

A respectable dive bar located in Mesa, near the Mesa/Tempe boundary along the 101.

The appeal of this venue largely hinges on the band's performance. The primary draw here is the music, which means that post-8pm, conversation becomes challenging due to the high noise levels.

Thus, the experience can be great if the band performs well; otherwise, it remains a typical, unremarkable dive bar.

I don't particularly enjoy the dinner offerings at this location, yet it's an excellent spot for a lunch outing. The menu offers a wide variety and the servings are ample. Steve's offers reasonable prices for a dining establishment situated in the central part of the city.

Observe the charming quotes adorning the walls.

Earlier today, I sampled the Tuna Salad Salad, and it was absolutely flawless! Additionally, the accompanying bread was exceptionally delicious. Over the years, my visits here have been frequent, and the establishment has maintained a high standard of excellence in their offerings - Well done!

Excellent, reliable deli offerings. I've sampled multiple sandwiches, each of which has left me content. It would be beneficial for them to enhance the ambiance for those who choose to eat on-site (though perhaps that's not their goal).

An excellent spot to visit for drinks and celebrations following a victory in a game -- that's exactly what we did earlier this week after the D-backs triumphed over the Braves with a score of 5-2.

The crowd was quite captivating, featuring numerous beer tub girls dressed in revealing attire... it took the bouncer about 10 minutes to extract my girlfriend's ID from her wallet for a thorough check (it was really wedged in there); he could have just let her through... she looks young, but she's not under 20!

I can't see myself ever coming here for anything but drinks after a game... and for that purpose, it's perfectly adequate.

Exceptionally tasty Mexican cuisine at an affordable rate. It features a cozy, cafe-like ambiance, which is significantly more appealing than many local taco establishments.

The provided salsa with the free chips is outstanding! Both the taco and tostada were flawless, and the rice and beans were spot on.

An ideal spot for lunch located in the southern part of Tempe.

Scottsdale's Old Town was in dire need of a BBQ spot! I popped in to visit a friend, had a quick beverage, and sampled a spicy sausage... the costs for starters, sandwiches, and beverages appeared quite fair. The remainder of the menu also looked enticing, especially the pork-based treats that are likely to excite culinary enthusiasts. It baffles me why someone would give this a one-star rating - perhaps due to a personal grudge. The team was extremely welcoming, the service swift, and my meal was excellently prepared. Wishing you all the best!

*UPDATE - Gave it another go and it truly is a fantastic spot for a drink as well - any draft beer plus a whiskey shot for just $3, available ALL DAY, EVERY DAY! They offer incredible happy hour deals and a cozy bar space for relaxing.

Do try the pulled pork sandwich and cornbread for only $7!!!

This was my initial visit to an EB, and I found the experience quite pleasant overall, particularly the lunch. I opted for a shrimp platter, which was generously portioned and offered good value for money. The interior design of the place reminds one of a grown-up rainforest-themed restaurant, while the menu, extensive and eclectic much like that of a Cheesecake Factory, unfortunately, features offerings of lesser quality. Rumor has it that their happy hour is not to be missed.

Pete's equals amazing!

Spend ten dollars to purchase as much shrimp and hot sauce as possible â that's the essential info...

Primarily a drive-thru establishment, grab your food, enjoy it at home, and you'll be grateful afterwards...

A fantastic spot for enjoying a drink following an evening meal in the historic district, though I steer clear on Fridays and Saturdays due to the overwhelming crowds.

The beverages are of the highest caliber (and command premium prices), the ambiance is undoubtedly captivating for virtually all, and the patrons are quite fascinating (primarily aged 25 and above), including numerous visitors from out of town who are guests at the Mondrian and frequent this venue.

This BBQ establishment is enormous, possibly covering 8000 square feet. Surprisingly, I've enjoyed nearly every dish I've tried at this large franchise. The employees are always alert, and the quality of the meals exceeds expectations. There aren't many alternative BBQ places in Tempe.

My goodness, give this place a fresh coat of paint already... It's astounding how many establishments lack ambiance... I have no desire to dine at K-mart (nor am I inclined to shop there). What's the cost of a few gallons of paint and proper lighting, really? Also, it's time to revamp the bar! It's disheartening to see a business owner lose their enthusiasm.

Took some medication... feeling calmer now...

The cuisine is decent - not outstanding - but offers a veritable feast of options for vegetarians (there are about 100 choices on the menu). The prices are exceptionally low (perhaps they could increase each item by 10 cents to cover new paint). Initially, the menu is confusing, as it lists items like chicken, beef, shrimp, etc., but a note at the front clarifies that these are all meat alternatives.

Would anyone else be willing to volunteer some time to help enhance this place (yes, it bothers me that much).
Incredible ambiance - the identity becomes clear post-visit. There's a fantastic terrace, though it's completely overshadowed by the harsh summer temperatures. I plan to go back when winter arrives.

At last, I made it down here to catch up with my girlfriend and a few of her friends (they're regulars)... The beverage prices appeared fair. I didn't partake in any food personally, but I noticed an assortment of dishes on our table: salads, shepherd's pie, pretzels with dip. All seemed quite appetizing. Additionally, there are several pool tables, a jukebox, an extended bar, and numerous tables.

In summary, it's a pleasant, dimly lit, dive bar with tasty food.

In general, it's a satisfactory establishment. The best feature of Networks might be its prime location and extended operating hours compared to other local spots.

I've experienced a number of effective business lunches at this venue, and the cuisine is fairly good. The evening atmosphere tends to be somewhat subdued, with the service lagging even more. The interior design is appealing and contemporary, giving it an upscale appearance.

If you're considering eating out, this might not be the best choice. However, for a beverage prior to a sports event or after a day at the office, it's a wise decision...

The atmosphere here exudes a 1960s retro charm. I'm fond of the architecture and the sign outside. Rip's, originally an old house, has been transformed into a vintage bar, radiating a classic vibe. It attracts an eclectic mix of individuals, making it a unique spot. For those who appreciate observing diverse crowds (akin to enjoying a circus), visiting during the weekend is a must. My experience was pleasant, though it won't become my regular spot.

Initially, the concept of Maria Maria appeared intriguing. However, enduring over ninety minutes of exclusively Santana tunes might become somewhat irritating.

The establishment was roughly half occupied, yet we faced a 20-minute delay for seating. The interior design was appealing and the service was friendly. The chips and salsa exceeded expectations, offering three varieties as standard. We opted for the chicken fajitas and a Mexican salad. Both dishes were satisfactory, though not particularly exceptional.

To me, Maria Maria felt more like it was all show and no real depth.

Why do people bring small children to such venues? The ambiance alone should signal that this isn't a place for kids like a McDonald's playground. A rule I once learned and found memorable is that "the price on the menu should correspond to the child's age." For instance, at McDonald's, a child's meal costs less than $3, suitable for children aged three and older. At Denny's, a meal costs around $10, while at Maria Maria, even the most frugal can expect to spend about $15. This provides a straightforward and refined guideline for parents to consider... (This does not apply to exceptionally well-mannered children).
The initial impressions I get are professionalism and friendliness. Additionally, they contribute significantly to the local community. I strongly endorse the wonderful team at American Chiropractic.

Here, convenience reigns supreme; the selection isn't vast, yet the availability of small servings and ready-made meals secures its popularity. Additionally, this place offers fresher, healthier options compared to the average supermarket.

A great spot to bring children; they really enjoy the woman dressed as a pig who wanders the area. The staff is amiable and quick, and the barbecue food is quite satisfactory. Either the Pork Ribs or the Jalapeno Burger stand out as the top choices on the menu.

This chain restaurant isn't particularly extraordinary.

I made my initial visit on a Sunday afternoon to partake in their "Chili Cookoff" event. Participation was a mere $2, allowing us to sample 20 unique chili recipes. The venue boasted an excellent outdoor area equipped with volleyball, cornhole, various other games, live bands, and facilities to grill your own meals. Additionally, the chili that received our votes emerged as the contest winner!

Given its vibrant atmosphere, despite being a 30-minute drive from Scottsdale, this place could likely become a frequent spot for us.
No item exceeds a price of $1.99... wonderful staff, excellent service!

This venue has certainly seen improvements since my previous visit. The entire place, including the bar and restrooms, underwent renovations roughly a year back.

I joined a group of friends for beers and bowling last Saturday evening. We enjoyed ourselves immensely and managed to secure a few lanes without difficulty. The place became more crowded as the night progressed - arriving before 10pm is advisable.

The venue offers "polar pitchers" that ensure your beer remains chilled to the last sip :)

On weekends, each game costs $5 per person. With eight of us, the total came to $120 after playing three games...

Superb Mexican cuisine featuring a creative flair. It has been some time since my last visit, yet I recall having a delightful time and noting that the service exceeded expectations. The ambiance is also perfect for a sophisticated date.

In terms of quick-service burgers, this establishment performs admirably. Although I prefer visiting places like Indulge Burger, David's, or Deluxe when I'm not rushed, this spot is my go-to when I need something speedy, definitely over the typical Mc-King-Taco-Box franchises. The aspect I appreciate most is their straightforward approach: "You want a burger and fries, or a burger and fries?"

The establishment has such a traditional vibe that it practically requires reconstruction. There may be evenings when the atmosphere is lively and enjoyable, yet the venue's condition is overly dilapidated. Our visit on a Sunday evening left us underwhelmed, especially given the numerous favorable critiques I had encountered. This Bikini is grimy, aged, and foul-smelling.

Should you locate it, your enjoyment is guaranteed - Nestled in a quaint spot on the extreme left of the plaza at the northeast intersection of Hardy and University in Tempe.

I learned that the Pasty originates from an old English mining custom, essentially a British version of a burrito. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limey

Our Sunday lunch experience included trying these dishes - Her cheese steak pasty was exceptional, and my chicken pot pie pasty was equally scrumptious. The pastry was exceptionally flaky, and the "oven chips" topped with jalapeÃ±os were unparalleled. Remember, this establishment does not serve fast food, so patience is advised during your visit.

PupTent represents a fresh and thrilling substitute for traditional pet boarding services. Karri has been an acquaintance of mine for a while, and she is a reliable expert. It's hard to envision allowing my dog to stay at a conventional boarding place when, for a reduced cost, he could be with a caring family instead. This service is greatly beneficial for individuals who often travel for extended periods or need prolonged medical care.

Located in the heart of Old Town Scottsdale, this spot is ideal for a cozy date or a casual hangout with friends to chat. It's the perfect venue to either kick off or wrap up your night...

Enchanting and cozy, it features a host of friendly regulars (including myself), outdoor seating with a charming fireplace, a smoker-friendly terrace, and a secluded patio on the upper level.

The Martinis and assorted cocktails are top-notch! Should you encounter "Kevin" behind the bar: mentioning his "excellent roller blading prowess" might just snag you a discount... :)

(situated slightly to the east of Main and Brown along the pavement)

*UPDATE* 2009 - now renamed Brackin's Bar, it remains exceptionally trendy!!!

This establishment is among the rare chain eateries that I enjoy...

I visited their new spot on a recent Saturday evening (they've just relocated to a larger facility right next door).

The Melting Pot offers a unique culinary adventure, characterized by an extended dining duration that spans several hours. I'm a big fan of fondue, and The Melting Pot excels in this area!

We began with a starter of cheese, apples, breads, and vegetables, accompanied by a blend of cheddar cheese and beer. We then proceeded to enjoy lobster, shrimp, steak, pork, and chicken, all cooked in a vegetable broth. We concluded our dining experience with a dessert of chocolate and peanut butter served with cheesecake, strawberries, and rice crispy treats.

The service was outstanding, as was the food and the selection of wines. A truly memorable experience!

Visited this spot for the first time yesterday evening.

I really enjoyed it â the atmosphere was relaxed, the interior design appealing, the staff welcoming, the outdoor seating delightful, the beverages outstanding, the music soothing, and it's superbly located (southwest of Don and Charlie's - just search for the blue-light-pillars outside). It's advisable to arrive before 9pm during weekends (to ensure you find a seat).

A friend introduced me to this venue, and I'm grateful for the introduction to yet another laid-back spot for socializing and drinking in Old Town. It tends to become quite crowded on weekends.

***UPDATE*** Just so you know - Monday nights here are exceptionally busy!!!

Should you find yourself in need of some pampering while in Cave Creek, Salon Mila is unquestionably the spot to visit. Our visit was serendipitous, coinciding with a festival taking place within the shopping complex. The facility stands out as an architectural wonder, conceived and constructed by the proprietors who also own the premises. The owners are exceptionally involved and enthusiastic. Available services include haircuts, manicures, pedicures, facials, massages, among various other spa treatments. Indulge at Salon Mila!

Zur Kate offers a delightful experience, reminiscent of a classic German tavern setting. The team is exceptionally welcoming to those new to German cuisine. Every morsel was enjoyed, and we ate roughly half of our large servings. As we exited close to 7:30 pm, an accordionist began to perform. There's genuine historical significance to the venue, as detailed in the menu's narrative. We're excited to go back!

This spot ranks among the top local venues for purchasing alcoholic beverages!

It surpasses BevMo in terms of charm, historical significance, and the variety of spirits it offers! While I'm generally not a fan of most beers or wines (though they offer a wide array), I prefer to try the more unusual types of Vodka, Rum, and Tequila.

Sportsmans offers great value for money, though it's not exactly a discount store - the superior experience makes it worthwhile, however. It's the kind of shop where you can leisurely browse, engage in conversations, and thoroughly explore.

Try visiting Sportsmans - you'll soon be saying, "No more BevMo!"

I've learned that Legends has recently shut down, changed ownership, and is currently undergoing renovations to open again shortly. Here's hoping, because North Scottsdale could really use a charming local spot.

During my time residing in Tempe, occasionally, I indulged in a late-night snack accompanied by a cocktail at this establishment.

The venue strikes a balance between a dive bar and a sports bar, featuring expansive spaces and multiple rooms for dining and drinking. On several late evenings, I witnessed live band performances here. Both the beverages and meals are reasonably priced and of satisfactory quality.

Both the frequent patrons and the bartenders showed great friendliness.

A good spot, especially on Sunday evenings if you're into Metalhead. Yelling along with hair bands occasionally is quite enjoyable. I've been told the 80's tribute band playing on Saturdays is also commendable, though I haven't had the chance to see them myself.

The venue is spacious, featuring multiple rooms and an expansive outdoor patio.

UPDATE - Recently attended a birthday celebration here and checked out the dance club located upstairs at the back - encountered many friendly folks, enjoyed tasty beverages, and had a great time... May09'

Of all the Manuel's locations I've visited in the valley, this one tops the list. The establishment is tidy and welcoming, staffed by amiable personnel, and is situated ideally. The Mexican cuisine offered is quite satisfactory. Here, the dishes are conservative in flavorânothing too spicy or off-putting. The meals are cooked to perfection, with the rice and beans being notably exceptional. The Margaritas appeared tempting, although we decided to refrain this time. For a different experience, consider trying "Ajo Al's," located just down the road.
Metro Phoenix's biggest Comedy Club. A close friend performed, and I thoroughly enjoyed it. While the beverages might be somewhat expensive and the cuisine just average, the comedy is top-notch!
I occasionally had this for lunch - Regrettably, it shut down a few months back... I believe "Julio's Too" remains open.

Excellent cuisine, reasonable rates, and commendable customer service.

Extreme Pita offers nothing overly "radical," aside from being a refreshing change from the usual burger and fries.

Additionally, the excessively bright, nondescript, quick-service restaurant ambiance can interfere with digestion.

The food's superior quality, coupled with the welcoming personnel and a stylish, modern setting, provides an excellent beginning to the day. I chose a classic breakfast featuring bacon, eggs, potatoes, and toast, and found it very satisfying.
In terms of quick dining choices, this one stands out as quite satisfactory. I really enjoy the classic roast beef sandwich topped with Arby's sauce!

The primary descriptor here is 'downhill' - it's baffling how this place remains operational. The quality of the crab cakes is extremely poor, and nearly all other offerings barely reach mediocrity. Do yourself a favor and choose a different location.

I had a meal here yesterday evening accompanied by several cocktails. It's advisable to arrive early to dodge the late-night crowd, particularly after 10pm on weekends.

Geisha offers a contemporary setting with the option of renting private Karaoke rooms for gatherings with friends.

The chicken stir fry for dinner and the beverages were thoroughly enjoyable. The pricing is reasonable for the Scottsdale region. I concur that it's a "nice place" deserving of dressing up for. If casual attire is more your style, like wearing flip flops and skipping the shower, Loco Patron might be a better choice.

Individuals either adore or despise this location... "destined disdain"?

Regardless, my preference is affection, as it's a delightful, repurposed residence situated directly in the city center. The culinary expert is brilliant, offering dishes that are both distinctive and unforgettable. Make sure to book ahead or hope for the best!

The sole gripe I have is that it becomes somewhat oppressive during the warmer months.
Visited DD on Saturday evening for Doggtoberfest; they extended into the parking area with a live band. Enjoyed the lively scene and excellent crowd. The atmosphere was consistently laid-back.
Pleasant location with amiable Italian proprietors.

Scottsdale Quarter is a great enhancement to the local area. I enjoy dining at True Food Kitchen, Narcisse, and Parc Central. Primebar also offers a decent happy hour.

While I don't shop much, the shopping options at SQ appear somewhat limited. However, the Apple store is appealing. Recently, I've frequented SQ more often than Kierland Commons across the way.

Definitely an enjoyable spot for relaxing and observing others. Last night, I stopped by for some wine and pizza late in the evening. The prosciutto pizza, with its extremely thin crust, was quite tasty. Many Comicon attendees were coming and going in their outfits. Quite amusing!

Scottsdale's top spot for Italian beef is here. When in Chicago, I typically visit Al's or Portillo's for this delicacy, but having Al's locally eliminates the need to travel to the Windy City.

The interior features an interesting display of several motorcycles. It's tidy, clean, and staffed by numerous attentive workers who ensure service is swift.

I opted for the standard Al's beef with sweet peppers. I avoid ordering my sandwiches "wet" as they're already quite juicy. The flavor was satisfying and the portion was perfect. The fries, though thick, were somewhat too greasy for me.

Overall, it was a satisfying lunch and a reminder of Chicago's culinary offerings to consider for future cravings.
Grateful to Shannon M. for recommending this spot. The meatball sandwich was superb. Appreciated the family-run service.

Amidst the plethora of trendy eateries popping up, it's easy to overlook an established gem like T-Cook's at the Royal Palms Resort, where the ambiance, service, and cuisine remain top-notch.

Chef Lee Hillson, a former Iron Chef America contestant, consistently delivers exceptional fare, putting a unique twist on traditional recipes that tantalize the taste buds.

During the Scottsdale Culinary Festival in April, I indulged in a multi-course meal at T-Cook's. Chef Hillson showcased his culinary prowess, especially with a remarkable lamb dish.

Recently, I had lunch there with a client, opting for the Fruit de Marâa mix of fried calamari, shrimp, and scallops. While the seafood was tasty, the breading was slightly overwhelming for me. The Turkey club sandwich, however, was excellent, loaded with succulent slices of roasted turkey, enough to have leftovers.

T-Cook's is truly a delightful dining spot, one I find myself frequently revisiting.
Big outdoor shopping center featuring typical franchise shops. Many restaurant units are currently empty.
Arizona's top mall features numerous upscale stores and fine dining options, with ample covered parking available except during holiday seasons.

I'm quite fond of this location. Many have commented on the building's appealing exposed brick and open design. The staff are consistently friendly, and the menu is robust. I believe a large menu isn't necessary if a few items are done exceptionally well.

I visited for lunch and chose a seat at the outdoor bar. The weather was pleasant, making it an ideal spot. I opted for the sweet carrot soup, which was superb. The portion was generous, and I enjoyed every bite.

I also tried the burger and fries, both of which were delicious. The burger was served with bacon, gruyere cheese, and crispy onions, and even the ketchup was unique, enhanced with pepper and other spices for a distinct flavor.

I appreciate the offerings here and am eager to return for another meal, be it lunch or dinner.
I've visited multiple PBs in the Valley; they're consistently good. I enjoyed a mandarin orange muffin last Sunday morning. I hope they'll soon adopt the trend of providing a green iced tea option.

My friend and I chose this spot for an outdoor lunch on the patio, securing a prime table near the entrance, ideal for observing passersby, with comfy couch seating.

I opted for the Pub Burger, served with bacon, Havarti cheese, and fries, remarking to my friend about its dubious nutritional value. Shortly after, an old acquaintance appeared, revealing his recent heart attack, eyeing my meal enviously since he's now restricted from such foods, prompting me to consider healthier choices.

Despite its health implications, the burger was delicious, large, and well-prepared, with crispy bacon and ample cheese.

It was a pleasant venue for a relaxed meal. I plan to choose something healthier next time.
This spot is fantastic! The carne asada burrito accompanied by guacamole and various homemade salsas is absolute perfection. Additionally, the service is extremely welcoming.

I entered around 6 PM on Friday to find the venue bustling. I managed to grab a seat at the bar's end near the TV, ready to settle in.

I began with an Irish Red beer, which was quite tasty, slightly more so than the cream ale I tried subsequently.

I opted for the capicola pizza, which was notably spicy and rich in flavor. Although I'm not entirely convinced about the crust, I generally liked the meal.

It seems Fate is set for success!
Sunday afternoons are best spent here with live music, delicious food, and drinks on the rear patioâit truly doesn't improve beyond this!

I recently visited this spot for the first time and loved its modern design. The bar space is ample and offers a nice dining experience. The staff was both friendly and good-looking!

The chicken tikka masala tasted wonderful, and I plan to return!
If you're nearby, it's a solid choice for Mexican cuisine. I opted for carne asada tacos with rice and black beans at the bar. The spices and spiciness were satisfactory. Service was amiable.

This contemporary Italian eatery is quite pleasant.

Last week, we dined here and liked it. The burrata caponata starter tasted great, with its creamy, rich burrata pairing well with the bread.

Staff were consistently attentive, and proactively provided an ice bucket for our Sonoma Cutrer wine.

I chose bucatini amatriciana while my friend opted for shrimp risotto. Both dishes were satisfactory, though not extraordinary.

In summary, the meal was enjoyable, and I plan to return.

On Sunday, we planned to visit Switch but ended up at Fez instead, playfully altering our plans.

Fez offered a welcoming vibe and courteous staff. We both enjoyed a Sam Adams and a shared hummus plate, which was delicious, especially with olive slices and flavorful flatbread.

I chose the lemon caper chicken while my girlfriend opted for the shrimp kisra. The chicken was satisfactory, featuring two portions, allowing me to take a good amount home.

The shrimp kisra resembled a pizza but was somewhat soggy and only mediocre.

The meal was enjoyable, though the prices seemed a bit steep.

We plan to revisit Switch next time.
The Bananas Foster waffle at this place is astonishing. What other breakfast spot serves it with a scoop of vanilla ice cream? Adding bacon on the side makes it a morning must-have.

Returned from the grand openingâthis spot's set to be popular. Great having a sushi joint at the Biltmore post-Ayako.

Menu matches the Scottsdale site. The Biltmore features a superb indoor/outdoor bar and a distinct back dining space.

All sushi rolls tasted excellent, spicy and rich.

Typically, I opt for beer or sake at Japanese spots, but the Tokyo Wall Street cocktail with vodka and ginger was outstanding.

I'd rate this venue at 3.5 stars. It's best appreciated as a lively spot for those around their 40s, give or take a few years.

They offer decent discounts during happy hour on both beverages and meals. The vibe picks up in the evening, especially with the live music.

I visited NOCA for the third time last week.

It being Thursday, I opted for the wagyu pastrami sliders, which were excellentâsubstantial meat cuts on well-toasted bread, accompanied by superb homemade chips.

The service was commendable, and the restaurant maintains high standards throughout.
Nice spot. The food's good. Visited during the Super Bowl; very crowded. Would think about returning to catch a game.

Alright, we've often come here at night for bruschetta and wine.

This time, I tried their lunch menu since I was nearby.

The nine iron panini was excellent. Served on ciabatta with chicken, bacon, burrata, lettuce, and tomato, it was truly delightful.

It felt odd to be here in daylight without wine, yet I'm sure to return soon for another lunchtime panini.

This spot is excellent. Its owner was just honored as an exceptional pastry chef and welcomed into the Arizona Culinary Hall of Fame. My buddy and I opted to visit.

I chose the quiche Lorraine accompanied by fruit. The eggy core and flawless crust were superb.

I also had to try the chocolate croissantâa truly tasty, airy, and flaky masterpiece.

DeliciousâI'd love to live nearer!
This place offers an excellent happy hour. The popovers are fantastic, and the jalapeno burger is a bargain for $8. The escargot is tasty, though not as much as when the recipe was different.
I truly enjoy their chocolate chip sconeâit's delicious and surprisingly big. Plus, the availability of various newspapers to peruse during your visit is a pleasant addition.

Yesterday, I joined a charming Yelp acquaintance for lunch at Liberty Market, a place I've been eager to visit after hearing about it for years.

Finding parking might be tricky, but once you're inside, the ambiance is inviting with its raw brick, steel, and wood aesthetics, offering a modern and open vibe.

The menu offers a wide selection. I opted for the Rancher sandwich, a pressed creation similar to a panini, featuring roast beef, caramelized onions, blue cheese, arugula, and horseradish for a flavorful kickâa truly delicious choice. The accompanying caprese pasta salad was also superb.

I'm keen to return and sample more of their sandwiches, salads, and pizzas, which all seem appealing.

A heartfelt thanks to Liberty Market for a delightful meal!

Post-trekking Pinnacle Peak, my friends and I visited this spot for a Sunday breakfast. The weather was pleasant, making the patio an ideal choice.

I opted for corned beef hash with two eggs and hash browns. Service lagged somewhat, yet the meal was delicious upon its arrival.

I've visited multiple Miracle Mile Deli spots over time. This spot is ideal for comfort food.

Today, I stopped by for lunch. Their Thursday special includes meatloaf, which I chose. The portion was generous, accompanied by mashed potatoes and gravy. Truly a delicious, hearty meal!

The servers frequently checked on me, offering more iced tea, which was appreciated.

I can't wait to return!

Kelly's, which launched this week, is already thriving. Its prime corner spot boasts one of Scottsdale's top front patios. I enjoyed drinks both at the bar and on the patio during my visits. The menu is appealing, the drinks are satisfying, and the service is exceptionally friendly.
I recently had spare time and visited this place to pass it. As a member who has frequented here often, I particularly enjoy the Philip Curtis paintings.

Visited this spot on Saturday evening. Prefer the Scottsdale location, but both the food and service were dependable. My buddy praised his New Planet gluten-free beer, claiming it was the finest he's ever had.

Visited this spot a few days back. Happy I came mid-afternoon; parking seems challenging when it's busy.

Tried the butter pecan and strawberry. Loved the butter pecanârich, smooth, and creamy. The strawberry, however, was overly sweet for me.

Will remember this place for great ice cream when I'm nearby.

I attended a Scottsdale League for the Arts gathering here last evening with roughly 150 attendees. The venue was lively and everything was excellent!

The drinks and bubbly selection were impressive. The decor was stylish, the music enjoyable, the crowd attractive, and the service welcoming.

I've visited this spot several times and really enjoy it. Yesterday, I chose a seat at the rear of the dining area close to the pizza oven. The appeal was enhanced by the chilly, rainy weather, allowing me to view the wood-fired oven, evoking the warmth of sitting by a cozy fireplace.

I sampled the egg pizza topped with prosciutto and mozzarella. It's now my top pick at Humble Pie. The ingredients blend superbly, and the leftovers made an excellent breakfast the following day.

I also observed their attractive happy hour offerings and half-priced wine bottles on Mondays, which I plan to explore soon.

Craving red meat, my friend and I opted for The Grind.

The dim, contemporary interior surprised me; I found the elongated, narrow space quite exclusive, reminiscent of a secretive club or speakeasy.

At the bar, I chose an Anchor Steam beer on tap, a nod to my San Francisco roots. The mason jar glasses weren't to my liking, causing me to spill some beer.

I went for the steakhouse BLT burger and herbed fries. The burger's size stood out in comparison to local offerings, affirming that size does matter. It was cooked to perfection, with the bun and charred onions also impressing.

In the Phoenix gourmet burger scene, this juicy, tasty burger takes the top spot.

Visited today for lunch.

This restaurant is often crowded due to its tasty cuisine and amiable staff. I chose the chicken tikka masala. The portion is generous, including ample chicken and rice. The flavors and spices are delightful. There's enough to bring home for another meal.

Take advantage of the outdoor seating if the weather allows.

I attended an outdoor concert here last Friday night. Jesse Cook performed, and the weather, acoustics, and hillside seating were ideal. It's an excellent venue for events such as the Scottsdale Culinary Festival or simply to stroll and appreciate the gardens, blooms, and water elements.

In 2010, my top dining experiences were at Quiessence and FnB, both deserving 4.5 stars.

Upon entering the Farm, we spotted a wedding reception to our left in a grassy area. No need to wed just to enjoy a superb meal here!

We began with a platter of the chef's cured meats and salumi, each uniquely delicious.

The pork loin I had was excellent, and my girlfriend's scallops were exceptionally tender. The freshness and natural quality of the food here enhance the genuine taste present in each morsel.

Both the service and the picturesque surroundings were charming.

This destination merits a visit for an extraordinary culinary adventure, regardless of your proximity.

I recently dined with my mother and we thoroughly enjoyed our meal.

We began with the Maust Khiar yogurt appetizer, a delightful mix of mint and cucumber, which was both light and refreshing, perfect for pairing with warm pita bread.

For our main dishes, we chose stews. I opted for the Gheimeh Bademjan, essentially a beef stew, accompanied by a side of riceâtruly tasty.

My mother selected the Fessenjan, a unique chicken stew seasoned with walnuts and pomegranate, offering a distinct and pleasing taste.

I'm eager to return soon to explore more of their intriguing dishes.

Ate lunch at the bar, enjoying sports on TV and chatting with the bartender for amusement.

Opting for the factory burger and fries is always wise, especially since the fries are notably superior.

This spot ensures you won't go hungry!

I've eaten Chinese cuisine thrice in the past fortnight, consistently choosing beef with broccoli among various dishes. Pei Wei made it best, perfectly seasoning it. It's fast, affordable, and comes with numerous fortune cookies. What's there not to enjoy?

After reading Lindsey F's review about the dessert poker chip at Durant's, I quickly made my way there, having not visited in some time.

I indulged fully in the meal, sitting at the bar, enjoying Monday Night Football, and chatting with the bartender.

My dinner began with a glass of cabernet and a Caesar salad, which was both large and tasty.

Next, I had the filet medium rare with garlic mashed potatoes. With 60 years of experience, they really know their steaks!

I chose the Chocolate Fudge Brownie pie for dessert. It was scrumptious, but I barely managed to eat half.

I earned my black poker chip for lifetime desserts and left feeling overjoyed and satisfied.
Great cuisine, welcoming staff, and consistently tidy.

I visited this place earlier in the week for dinner with friends. I adore the modern decor, especially how the west side facing Scottsdale Rd opens, which is perfect in good weather. The food was mediocre; we had egg drop soup, house fried rice, beef with broccoli, and a shrimp dish. I would return for the ambiance and try different menu items hoping to find something more to my liking.

This location is unlike what I expected. It has a laid-back atmosphere where you order at the counter and use paper cups for beverages.

The cheesesteak sandwich was tasty, and the green iced tea was outstanding.

Turf Paradise offers an enjoyable experience for those who appreciate gambling. There, you can enjoy live races, sip on beer, wager some cash, have more beer, and perhaps eat something in the process.

In my opinion, it's an exciting option for a Saturday outing, providing a change from the usual routine (at least that's the hope). The venue is also quite roomy and well-maintained. Why not give it a try?

Are you a fan of golf and looking to save some money? Paradise Valley Park Golf Course might be the perfect spot for you! I rate it three stars due to its affordability and the opportunity it provides for a relaxed round of golf without spending a lot.

However, remember that the quality matches the price, and it's certainly not Pebble Beach. While it may not be the best 18-hole course, it still offers a good time.

For those who simply want to practice their swing, it's possible to do so at a minimal cost. As a community golf course, no membership is necessary, and it's open to everyone, kids included. Why not bring the family along for some budget-friendly fun when the weather is nice?

Many regard Mickey's merely as a place to sober up after a night out, yet it's genuinely a lively spot to spend the evening. I'm aware of several individuals who visit Mickey's for lunch, and even more who indulge in the spinach dip post-nightlifeâit's top-notch! They often offer drink deals, and I can attest that on Wednesdays, drinks are just $3 each. Occasionally, there's a $5 entry fee, but there's no need for fancy dress, hats are okay, and there's no fuss about footwear. Also, make sure not to miss their happy hour, which features half-price food and beverages. The venue boasts pool tables and a unique mix of decor that spans from charming and quirky to vintage and eerie. Previously, they had a DJ on weekends, but now they play a varied playlist and provide a jukebox for personal music choices.

Looking for a perfect present for the special woman in your life? Check out Bath and Body Works! This store offers an extensive range of beautifully scented body lotions, oils, massage creams, sprays, skincare products, bath essentials, perfumes, and home fragrances, among other items. It's a treasure trove for anyone who adores feminine products.

Frequent promotions like buy two, get one free are common, and if you time it right to hit their yearly sale, you can snag all their top-notch items at a steal.

Their standout offerings include their aromatic lotions, which are unbeatable. The warm vanilla sugar and cucumber melon scents are my top picks; they're not only delightful but also have lasting power. I consistently receive compliments on these scents long after application.

If I were fascinated by mechanical animals or were a child of five, this location might appeal to me.

In my view, the Rainforest Cafe is somewhat overpriced. It's a themed dining establishment where small mechanical animals periodically move around as you dine. Periodically, sounds of thunder and rain are played, and mist sprays over the guests.

This venue is ideal for children, particularly for hosting birthday celebrations. If I had children, I would certainly consider organizing a party here. However, since I do not have children, I do not plan on revisiting the Rainforest Cafe with its animated gorillas and enigmatic fog in the near future.

I recently visited this place and it took me back to my college years, which I remembered as carefree until I recalled all the homework, exams, and jobs I had.

It's always nostalgic revisiting places from my youth, though I didn't frequent this particular Dos location as much as the one on Mill. Despite its larger size now, it doesn't feel the same.

The place still attracts a lot of students, with beers and tacos being enjoyed in abundance, yet I find myself missing the old, less polished Dos. Skipping class to hang out and enjoy a day at Dos had its own charm.

However, one visit was enough for me this time around. I observed fraternity members chugging beers, young women in short skirts, and older men at the bar taking in the scene. I think I'll stick to Scottsdale from now on.

If you're in the mood for a unique spot to enjoy a burger and beer, consider visiting Greasewood Flat. The setting is laid-back, featuring picnic benches as seating and a distinctly Western vibe. A stroll around the vicinity might give you the impression of a scrapyard, with various old cars and parts scattered about. Although I haven't visited recently, this was the scene during my last visit a year ago.

In the past, Greasewood was home to an exceptionally large pig, enclosed by a fence. You could only converse with him, as coaxing him to move was quite the challengeâI can attest to that.

Remember to bring cash, as Greasewood does not take credit cards, and the selection of food is quite sparse.

The place is known for hosting live music, and on chilly nights, patrons huddle around fire pits for warmth.

It's certainly a bar worth visiting if you've never been before!

During my final year at university, our student union had a Jamba Juice outlet, and I oddly decided to sample every flavor they offered before my graduation. I even maintained a notebook to track each flavor, ensuring I remembered which ones I had already tasted.

A slight obsession? Quite likely.

Eventually, my intense fascination with Jamba Juice diminished after several months, but not without me having enjoyed many of their delicious offerings.

I'm not a fan of blueberries, yet they taste great in Blutopia. Raspberries are not my preference either, but I can still enjoy a full cup of Raspberry Rage.

Believe me, there's nothing poor in quality at Jamba Juice. As someone who considers themselves quite knowledgeable about their menu, I recommend trying Aloha Pineapple, Mango-a-go-go, Banana Berry, and Strawberries Wild.

A piece of advice: avoid the pretzels. They lack flavor and excitement.

The Dirty Drummer offers a laid-back, sports bar-like atmosphere perfect for relaxing with friends, enjoying a good meal, having a few drinks, or playing pool.

The prices are quite reasonable as well. During my visit, drinks were priced below $6, which is an excellent deal for a bar in Scottsdale.

The pool tables are often occupied, so there could be a wait for a game. However, visiting on less busy weekday evenings usually means no wait.

There's no cover charge, and the dress code is entirely casual. Give it a try!

Pizza Picazzo didn't impress me much. Everything was mediocre: the food, the beverages, and the service.

During my visit, the pizza was average at best. It was passable, yet not memorable. However, the service was particularly disappointing.

It took forever for our server to initially approach our table, and then she delivered incorrect drinks and vanished for lengthy periods. The overall experience at Pizza Picazzo was quite irritating.

They offer some good lunch deals, but I prefer to dine elsewhere.

This art gallery and music venue is quite impressive. I've visited only during First Friday, which wasn't the best idea. It's essential to revisit at a time when the outdoor temperature isn't soaring to 115 degrees at night.

Modified Arts tends to fill up quickly, leading to discomfort in the heat. The crowd adds to the indoor warmth, ensuring you'll sweat if you haven't started already.

Aside from the heat issue, the venue offers an intriguing concept that I'm eager to explore again under more temperate conditions.

My feelings about Salt River are ambivalent. On one side, the water is disgustingly tainted with urine, yet on the flip side, it offers a delightful and soothing experience as you drift along. 

Like many locals, I've visited numerous times, more often than I'd like to acknowledge. It didn't take long, just a couple of visits, to understand that my mother's advice about sunscreen was serious.

After suffering from several sunburns, I now diligently apply SPF 45 all over whenever I'm near Salt River, and I recommend you do the same. If you're planning a day there, remember to bring your sunscreen. It's easy to carry it with you since many people have coolers and various items floating in tubes alongside them.

Although it's a great spot for family outings, be aware that it tends to attract a rowdy crowd. It's popular among teenagers and young adults, and I've even encountered two men, completely unclothed, floating by in a tube on separate occasions.

Expect the unexpected, pack plenty of sunscreen and water, and you're set for an enjoyable time. Just make sure to scrub off in a hot shower afterwards to cleanse any lingering bacteria.

It's unlikely that patrons frequent Pink Taco solely for its culinary offerings.

In my opinion, the establishment's notoriety and unique name draw the crowds. Pink Taco enjoys a prominent reputation and is quite celebrated.

Visitors might also be drawn by fond memories of a great time at the Pink Taco in Las Vegas. They may even recall the food being exceptional, though this perception is likely enhanced by the numerous margaritas consumed alongside their dishes.

However, dining at Pink Taco without the influence of alcohol reveals a less impressive reality. I find the food to be mediocre at best.

Pink Taco is an ideal spot for enjoying a few drinks and an appetizer before a night out, especially if you're looking to mingle with attractive people. However, for those seeking an authentic Mexican meal, this restaurant might not meet your expectations.

Although I don't typically eat steak, I find Durant's an appealing spot for a drink or meal occasionally.

Their desserts are particularly impressive. For those who enjoy steak, chicken, or similar dishes, this establishment is likely to be a favorite. It has been around for over 50 years, establishing itself as a notable landmark in Arizona. It is reputed to be the first steakhouse in the state.

I would characterize it as a blend of upscale and traditionalâa new niche I believe I've coined in the dining scene, if I may say so myself.

The ambiance of the restaurant is pleasant, albeit slightly dated, evoking memories of visits with my Grandma Mary. She would dress up in a sequin dress and a long fur coat, and we would go to Durant's for a meal. Yes, Grandma Mary was quite the fashion icon.

Martini Ranch offers a laid-back vibe compared to other local venues. Guests can enjoy a live band on the lower level or venture to the upstairs "shaker room" where a DJ plays hip hop, rap, and occasionally techno. It's convenient to have both choices, allowing visitors to select based on their mood each visit. The drink prices are reasonable, though sometimes there's a lengthy wait at the bar. The shaker room can become quite warm with the crowd it attracts, to the point where if we dance for over ten minutes, we end up sweating profusely. Despite this, Martini Ranch remains an excellent choice for an evening out in Scottsdale, conveniently located near other popular spots like Mickey's, Six, DJ's, and Maloney's.

Regardless of effort, no one seems to surpass Victoria's Secret. They excel in offering top-quality lingerie, underwear, bras, lotions, pajamas, and candles.

I appreciate that even the most provocative thongs and bras at Victoria's Secret retain an element of elegance. For those seeking something more risquÃ©, Frederick's is likely just around the corner.

Taking advantage of their sales can lead to some great bargains, especially during their major annual sale. However, arriving early is crucial to avoid the less desirable items that remain after many have shopped.

I have no criticisms of Victoria's Secret, though I do wish their prices were somewhat more affordable, a sentiment many share.

Curse you, Quizno's, for making such irresistibly tasty sandwiches that are also quite rich in fat.

I find myself unable to resist the veggie sandwich. It's far from a healthy option, yet it's incredibly flavorful. Packed with cheese and a type of oil-based dressing, it likely contains around 20 grams of fat per serving.

Additionally, I invariably end up adding chips and a soda to my order, which sends my daily caloric intake soaring into the thousands. Jared would never consider choosing the veggie sandwich, yet I frequently do. For low-fat veggie sandwiches, Subway is my go-to. However, when my cravings lean towards a scrumptious veggie sandwich that fulfills my daily fat and calorie requirements, Quizno's is the place I head to.

I'm quite fond of Souper Salad.

Whenever I plan a visit, I aim to arrive just as they open to be among the first to serve myself. I'm a bit particular about cleanliness at buffets, and getting there early alleviates my concerns.

The salad bar is top-notch, offering an extensive array of toppings, including a wide variety of dressings. Additionally, they provide pasta salads, fruit salads, pudding, and other tasty items in this section of SS.

Moving on to the hot dishes, the menu varies daily, yet staples like breadsticks and pizza are constants. Occasionally, they introduce different pastas or a taco bar, and there are always a few soups available.

For those with a sweet tooth, there's a frozen ice cream dispenser with several candy toppings. They also offer everything needed to assemble an excellent strawberry shortcake.

Service includes a waiter who handles drink orders and clears plates. While the cost per person is quite reasonable, leaving a tip is customary. If you enjoy using coupons, you might find one in the Sunday newspaper for a small discount.

If you're feeling under the weather or simply want to indulge, Red Robin is an excellent choice. The establishment offers a plethora of greasy, fried delights that you can imagine, plus more!

They also serve large burgers and fries, including a veggie burger option, which is quite tasty.

Additionally, the menu features a variety of desserts, among them a particularly scrumptious Oreo shake. Delicious!

The food is decent, though not exceptional. Our server appeared more engaged in recounting her unsuccessful date from the previous evening with a colleague than in attending to us. However, we were treated to all the cringe-worthy and regrettable details of her fleeting romance, which certainly added a layer of amusement to our dining experience.

This is a fantastic spot. If there are any aspiring cowboys or cowgirls among your loved ones, consider taking them to the Mining Camp restaurant for a meal. The atmosphere is welcoming to families, and the servings are generous. Located near the Superstition Mountains, the restaurant has an enigmatic aura, and the staff eagerly shares intriguing stories from the area while you dine.

The Mining Camp restaurant opened its doors in 1961 and was constructed using Ponderosa Pine sourced directly from Payson. The interior design mimics an old mining shack positioned at the foot of Superstition Springs Mountain. Meals are served in a communal style, with ample portions of chicken, ham, and ribs that could satisfy a large group.

I brought my grandparents to this restaurant for their anniversary, and they were thrilled with it.

The restaurant's ambiance is quite unique, as you eat in an underground cellar. This setting can feel a bit chilly, yet it adds to the unforgettable atmosphere.

It's said that the crab legs are exceptional, though I have tried the crab cakes and fried shrimp myself, and both were tasty.

The desserts and drinks were excellent, with the drinks being particularly potent. The prices are fair, considering the quality and quantity of food served.

I absolutely adore Bloom. Their menu blends traditional American dishes with creative touches from Italian, Asian, and French cuisines. The ambiance is sophisticated, and the service is outstanding.

The raviolis are my top pick, so I definitely suggest trying them. The peanut-crusted prawns are also fantastic. Bloom ranks high on my list of dinner spots, so give it a try!

P.S. - Their martinis are exceptional; don't hesitate to order one or two!

This shop caters primarily to affluent women and their cherished dogs. I still rate it four stars because it's quite charming. However, be ready to encounter an unprecedented number of botox-treated faces when you visit.

The store is a haven for all things canine. It offers miniature dresses for dogs, orthopedic dog beds with cooling features, and an assortment of treats, collars, and bowls, among other items. Additionally, there are unique gifts for dog enthusiasts, such as canine-shaped wine holders and various stationery items.

During my visit, I saw a patron strolling around with an adorable dog nestled in a Gucci carrier. The dog's name? Valentino, naturally.

If you're a dog lover or simply want to pamper your pet with the finest products, this is the place to go. It may be expensive, but the quality of the merchandise is unparalleled.

I'm not much of a beer enthusiast, so I'm not the best to comment on their extensive beer selection, but their martinis are something I can discuss.
