They offer a wide array of specialty martinis and cocktails, all of which are quite delicious in my opinion. A friend of mine was particularly fond of a chocolate-flavored martini, while I enjoyed a pear-flavored one, and another friend was impressed with the pomegranate press.

The food was quite satisfying, or perhaps it was the drinks enhancing the experience. Maybe it was a bit of both. We enjoyed a cheese pizza and a towering stack of onion rings, both discounted during happy hour, which really does feature an impressive tower of onion rings. Additionally, the server surprised me with a complimentary cheesecake for my birthday, making it a memorable celebration.

However, the prime feature of Yard House is its location. Positioned near Kona and Z Tejas, you can start at 3pm and catch the happy hour specials at each spot, then continue the evening with a free trolley ride to Giligin's. I did just that last Friday, and it was incredibly enjoyable. I highly recommend giving it a try.

Although the prices at Bed, Bath and Beyond are somewhat inflated, it remains an appealing store. It offers uniquely designed shower curtains and other charming items that are hard to find elsewhere.

Additionally, it's an excellent spot for purchasing picture frames. There's a dedicated area for frames, and they also offer a variety of framed art and pictures suitable for decorating your walls.

The selection of bedding is impressive as well; however, it's advisable to avoid buying memory foam here due to the excessive cost. You can find much more affordable options on Overstock.com.

For smaller items for your bathroom or bedroom, this store is definitely worth a visit.

I appreciate Big O Tires. I've consistently had positive experiences with their service, as the technicians are quick and approachable. Purchasing tires from them is beneficial because they often cover blowouts or flats under warranty. Additionally, they have never attempted to sell me unnecessary items or overcharge me. They are certainly a reliable choice for acquiring new tires.

Indeed, that's quite a strong assertion.

I was aware of this establishment but only recently visited for the first time. The cake is indeed excellent, though it doesn't completely justify its reputation.

During a visit to their cafe, my friend and I had lunch where I opted for the grilled vegetable sandwich. The menu also includes pizza, salad, and soup.

However, the main highlight is undoubtedly the cake. I selected the classico (chocolate, caramel, and whipped cream) which was delicious. My friend tried a cake featuring pineapple and peanut brittle and thoroughly enjoyed it, though she still maintains that sex is superior.

The Breakfast Club, nestled in the heart of Old Town Scottsdale, is an ideal spot for breakfast, brunch, or lunch. Keep in mind that it's not the kind of place to show up disheveled from just waking up. Expect a lengthy wait, particularly during weekends. However, the crowd of people around can be quite interesting to watch, which might make the time pass more quickly while you wait for a table.

I've tried both the breakfast burrito and the veggie omelette; each was scrumptious. They come accompanied by potatoes and fruit, though it's often hard to eat it all given the generous serving sizes.

In a single word: Margaritas.

The margaritas at Los Olivos are my favorite. My experience with the food is limited to a cheese crisp and a bean burrito, both of which were tasty, but the real stars are the chips, salsa, and undoubtedly, the margaritas.

The atmosphere during happy hour is enjoyable, as it's lively without being overcrowded, and the service is quite satisfactory. For anyone who appreciates budget-friendly beverages and delicious Mexican cuisine, this spot is worth a visit.

Who can resist live mariachi music? La Parrilla Suiza features a roaming mariachi band on weekends, which definitely earns it an extra star from me. The ambiance and decor make you feel as though you're dining in Mexico itself.

The cuisine is also quite deliciousâmy top picks include cheese enchiladas, chimichangas, and fajitas. Plus, if you love to dip, the chips are served with three distinct salsas!

Amsterdam is truly remarkable. They offer the finest and most potent martinis, accompanied by excellent music.

The majority of the patrons are men, though a good number of women are also present. The bartenders work swiftly, which is crucial, and the ambiance is sophisticated.

I haven't visited Burn yet, but prior to its opening, Amsterdam was arguably the best alternative bar available. It might still hold that title, although I've heard a lot about Burn and it seems all my gay friends are heading there enthusiastically, so it might have surpassed Amsterdam. Regardless, it remains an excellent choice for an enjoyable evening out, no matter your sexual orientation.

Lowe's is the one home improvement store that I somewhat enjoy visiting. What's great about Lowe's is its comprehensive inventory, ranging from tools to outdoor furniture, all offered at fair prices.

The customer service is excellent, and it's generally easy to locate assistance on the sales floor. If you've never visited and are planning any home improvements or modifications, Lowe's is certainly a recommended destination.

If you feel like swinging at some pitches, head over to Casey at the Bat. There, you can strike as many balls as you can imagine and even select the pitching speed.

For those who enjoy hockey, there's an option to play roller hockey in their arena, and they also offer video games on-site.

My rating is three stars because, personally, I find it somewhat lacking in excitement. Continuously hitting balls can become monotonous, don't you think? It certainly does for me.

Moreover, the maintenance of the facility could be better; it appears somewhat worn. However, if you're in the mood for something slightly unconventional, Casey's might be a decent option. The balls are ready for you.

**Warning**: this place is a popular spot among high school students!

Shoe haven. Numerous rows of footwear suitable for any event. This store stocks both obscure and designer brands, often at excellent prices. However, shopping here can be inconsistent. At times, you might depart with five pairs, while at other times, you struggle to find even one appealing pair. For the best discounts, explore the clearance shelves at the back, but be ready to sift through unattractive shoes adorned with gold sequins and similar embellishments to find the gems.

Great food, enjoyable drinks, lively bar. The valley hosts numerous Buffalo Wild Wings locations, offering a vibrant spot for a swift meal while enjoying a sports match. Their garden burger is commendable, and their buffalo chips, akin to French fries, are quite tasty. For fans of Bloody Marys, theirs is top-notch, notably spicy and brimming with celery and olives. However, be mindful of your timing, especially during game days, as arriving early is essential to secure seating.

I stumbled upon an undiscovered sushi spot that hasn't been reviewed online yet! It's tucked away in a nondescript strip mall, so it's easy to miss if you're just passing by. Despite its unassuming exterior, the interior houses a charming sushi restaurant with quite tasty offerings.

They offer unique sushi rolls wrapped in colorful soybean paper in shades of pink, yellow, and blue, which was a new sight for me. Even though I usually stick to the basics with sushi, I ventured to try several varieties. The Jazz roll was a favorite, featuring shrimp, asparagus, among other ingredients, and was quite delicious. The Crazy roll, with its spicy tuna, avocado, fried shrimp, and more, was alright, but not outstanding. The Arizona roll, containing asparagus, cucumber, and scallops, was also enjoyable.

If you're a fan of sushi, this place is worth a visit. It's exciting to explore new dining options, and their prices are reasonable compared to other sushi joints I've frequented. However, please don't hold it against me if it doesn't meet your expectations â I'm no sushi expert!

This location is great for a date as it offers ample opportunity for conversation in a cozy, dimly lit setting. However, I find it overly cheesy and you have to prepare your own food, which can get somewhat untidy and it's quite expensive.

Despite these drawbacks, the quality of the food is commendable, so I have no real complaints there. It simply isn't to my taste.

The desserts are also delicious, but be prepared to depart with the sensation of having overindulged, probably because you have!

Could it be my imagination, or is this Bath and Body Works superior to the one at Fashion Square? It's hard to say, but I know I could easily spend a lot of money here if I allowed myself.

Originally, they were known primarily for their lotions, but now BBW has expanded their range to include everything you might need for your bathroom cabinet. Their inventory now includes aromatherapy products, cleansers, toners, anti-aging creams, makeup, and much more.

My top picks for lotions are warm sugar vanilla, classic cucumber melon, and strawberry something or other. However, you really can't make a mistake with any of their lotions or body butters, as they all have wonderfully long-lasting scents.

Are you in the mood for crafting? This location offers a vast array of supplies for virtually any project you can imagine.

This specific Jo-Ann's store is quite large, which might feel overwhelming at first if you're not used to it. However, if you leisurely explore each aisle, you're likely to discover all that's available and even gather some excellent ideas for upcoming crafts.

I also find that their prices tend to be slightly lower than those at Michael's, and they have an impressive selection in their painting department.

Greetings, Baskin Robbins. Whenever the weather turns warm, my cravings for ice cream inevitably lead me to your store, especially given your impressive selection of 31 flavors. Making a choice is always a challenge because each flavor is tempting, yet I usually settle on cookies and cream or mint cookies and cream. It might seem mundane, but I prefer the timeless favorites.

Baskin Robbins also offers a variety of sundaes and shakes, though I've never explored those options. I tend to stick to the familiar, and what I know is exceptionally good.

I don't possess any pieces from Parnian Furniture, yet I admire them. Is that significant? It's clear that this family-run business has achieved considerable success.

Their furniture is exclusively upscale and modern. It often features bold hues, which are balanced by the absence of patterns, maintaining a minimalist yet contemporary aesthetic.

You should visit their showroom, and they've also opened a new location in the Scottsdale Fashion Square mall.

Streets of New York is undoubtedly a classic. How could anyone criticize this charming pizza spot? Throughout my high school and college years, I frequently enjoyed lunches and dinners here, and even now, I occasionally indulge in a slice of pizza, a salad, and some garlic bread. The only issue is that I can never persuade my friends to join me. What exactly do they have against Streets? It's a mystery to me. Therefore, if you happen to visit and spot a brunette dining solo in a booth, please say hello. I'd greatly appreciate the company of fellow Streets of New York enthusiasts.

Is it possible to attend ASU without visiting the Vine and indulging a few times? It seems unlikely. It might as well be an unofficial requirement.

The appeal of the Vine lies in its status as a beloved dive bar among college students. The beer is affordable, the food is tasty, and it's conveniently close to numerous apartment complexes.

Their fish and chips are quite impressive, assuming my memory serves me correctly, and the beer specials often offer pints at just $2 for an entire evening. It's no surprise that my recollections of the food are a bit hazy.

Eliminate it from my sight. I despise Electric Ladyland immensely.

Every aspect of it, including its glittering shirts and extensive hat collection, makes Electric Ladyland a shop I will absolutely avoid.

Additionally, the staff are unpleasant. Seriously, if there are customers in Electric Ladyland ready to spend their money, they deserve courteous treatment.

I used to steer clear of this place as if it were highly contagious, and when I did venture inside, I acknowledged that they carry some reputable designer brands like Frankie B. and Juicy. For this reason, they earn an additional star, but the majority of their merchandise is excessively adorned with counterfeit gems, which is unnecessary in my opinion.

Fox Sports Grill transcends the typical venue for game-watching. It's not only equipped with large TVs throughout, but it also functions as a social hotspot. Women typically arrive in chic outfits and towering heels, while men sport snug t-shirts and styled, spiky hair.

As evening sets in, the ambiance shifts to resemble a nightclub more than a sports bar, complete with lively music and a bustling crowd.

The dining area of the restaurant offers a pleasant setting with tables set apart from the bar area, and the cuisine, such as the linguini I enjoyed, is quite satisfying.

The beverages might be pricey, but the cost is justified by the sophisticated environment.

For those aiming to dress up, socialize, and catch a major sports event, this place is ideal. However, if you're after a laid-back spot to enjoy beers with friends, you might want to look elsewhere.

Ocean Club is undoubtedly a high-end dining spot, perfect for an enjoyable meal and a lively evening. The bar section is consistently bustling, so anticipate a delay and a challenge in securing a table even if you're just dropping by for drinks. Dining service can be inconsistent; at times the waitstaff may be too intrusive, while at other times they might be scarcely noticeable. The seafood, particularly the fish, is excellent, and the crab legs are reportedly superior. The setting is appealing, as after dining, you have the option to stroll through Kierland and explore the various shops.

This store features an unparalleled selection of pipes, ranging from large to small, stylish to animal-themed, and everything in between.

If there's someone in your life who enjoys smoking "tobacco," this is the place to visit. The glassware is crafted by hand, and visitors have the opportunity to observe the artisans as they work on creating unique pipes. You even have the chance to design and make your own pipe, tailoring it to your personal taste.

Beyond pipes, the shop also offers clothing, incense, candles, jewelry, and more, though the pipes are the primary attraction.

It's an impressive shop worth exploring!

Why isn't there a similar spot nearer to my home? I absolutely adore this venue! While I haven't sampled the dining area, I've experienced the dancing and it's tremendously enjoyable. The restaurant offers a view over the dance floor, which features live music nightly.

The place has a somewhat upscale and lounge-like atmosphere. In my opinion, it has significantly boosted Peoria's nightlife scene, and although nobody asked, that's the purpose of sharing on Yelp, isn't it?

Meh.

I wouldn't choose to spend my money on this hotel again. The exterior and common areas of the hotel are quite appealing. It boasts a large, airy structure with an impressive bar near the lobby.

However, the rooms leave much to be desired. They seem quite ordinary, and the so-called heavenly beds fell short of my expectations.

Equally disappointing was the pool service. The management seems clueless, and staffing at the pool fluctuates between being overrun with indifferent high school students to barely managed by one or two servers covering the whole area.

Considering the cost, I would rather stay at the Four Seasons, where they truly understand the essence of excellent customer service.

I first learned of Tammie, the renowned cake artist, at a friend's wedding. The wedding cake was stunningly beautiful and seemed almost too perfect to consume. However, we did indulge, and every bit of it was delicious.

When it came time to organize a baby shower for another friend, I recalled Tammie Coe and her exceptional skills. She crafted an exquisite cake adorned with flowers that became the highlight of the event, much to the delight of the expectant mother.

Tammie appears capable of designing cakes in virtually any shape or style you might envision; you simply need to make your request. Naturally, you also get to pick your preferred flavors.

While these cakes may come with a higher price tag, they are truly worth the expense. Not only do they serve as stunning centerpieces due to their elaborate and attractive designs, but they also taste exceptional.

Three margaritas? Absolutely!

During my time in Tempe, my roommate and I often frequented 3 Margaritas for casual dining experiences where appearance wasn't a priority (unlike at Macayo's Depot Cantina).

The handsome crowd usually gathered at Macayo's on Ash, allowing us to enjoy our meals at 3 Margaritas without worry. Occasionally, we'd indulge in more than three margaritas. Why not, when a taxi was merely a short, inexpensive ride away? Oh, those were the days.

The cuisine here is passable. It's not the pinnacle of Mexican cuisine, but it's decent enough. If you're feeling self-conscious about your appearance, this is the place to be. You can dine in peace, free from the anxiety of bumping into acquaintances.

I had almost forgotten the delight of eating donuts until my visit to Rainbow Donut. Despite its unassuming appearance, the quality of their donuts remains unaffected.

I typically opt for traditional donut varieties and am convinced that a simple glazed donut is unbeatable. Accordingly, I selected one along with a chocolate sprinkled donut. Indeed, I indulged in two.

My boyfriend sampled a cream-filled donut which he enjoyed, as well as a chocolate long john, another staple.

The coffee was passable, but the real highlight is the donuts. They're certainly worth a visit, just remember to carry cash!

JoAnn's should be your top choice for supplies for your upcoming art or craft project. Although Michael's isn't terrible, JoAnn's simply outshines it. Significantly so. They offer a wider variety of products, generally more competitive pricing, and superior organization.

My feelings about Fate are ambivalent. The cuisine is quite delicious, and the setting is trendy, nestled within a bustling urban area. However, the prices are steep and the serving sizes leave something to be desired. It's a wonderful spot if you're there for the vibe. Yet, for those watching their wallet or in search of hearty Asian fare, it might be wise to look elsewhere.

Despite these drawbacks, my visit to Fate was enjoyable, though locating it proved challenging. Situated in a residential area, it's tricky to distinguish the homes from the restaurant. The interior boasts a vibrant ambiance with local artwork adorning the walls and lively music in the background.

The wait for a table was around 40 minutes, which felt extensive in such a compact venue. Once seated, the service was prompt and efficient. The dishes were tasty; we chose vegetarian spring rolls, pad thai, broccoli island, and chow fun, all featuring crispy tofu, though there are options for chicken, beef, or shrimp. They offer a wide selection of wines, but we opted for herbal tea instead. For those late-night diners, they remain open until 3am on weekends.

This charming spot is slightly west of where Happy Valley Road meets Pima. At the General Store, you'll discover a variety of essentials whether you're beginning or wrapping up your day.

Here, not only can you refuel your vehicle and pick up typical convenience items, but there's also a post office and a quaint cafe offering a comprehensive menu. It's an ideal place for a fast snack or a relaxed dining experience.

The coffee here is quite satisfying, and the selection of snacks, meals, beverages, and personal care items surpasses what's typically available at other service stations.

Chompies is fantastic. They boast an extensive menu, and their breakfast offerings are so delightful that I've never managed to try their lunch options. Typically, I opt for the veggie omelette, minus mushrooms and scallions, accompanied by a bagel slathered in jalapeno cream cheese. Upon seating, the server promptly presents a plate of cucumbers and pickles, and they are generally quick to take your order and serve your meal. Don't miss the mural on the wall during your visit; it features a man wielding a knife, and if a guest sits precisely below it, it appears as though they are about to be stabbed. A tip for the early birds: expect to wait around 30 minutes if you visit on a weekend morning.

Whenever I visit this place, I'm reminded of the syrup container shaped like a lady, possibly named Mrs. Butterworth.

This eatery is a fantastic choice for breakfast, offering all the beloved morning staples such as pancakes, Belgian waffles, eggs, and omelets, often enhanced with fresh fruit.

The servings are generous, often resulting in extra food to take home. The restaurant tends to be crowded on weekends, and you may find yourself waiting around 20 minutes.

If you're in the mood to explore a new spot for breakfast, this should definitely be on your list!

If you're looking for quick bites, this spot is ideal. It offers speedy, affordable Mexican fare.

The menu features typical selections like tostadas, burritos, quesadillas, chips, and more, all customizable to your preferences, which is a pleasant touch.

The service is quick, so you won't spend much time waiting, especially beneficial during a busy lunch break when you need time both to grab and eat your meal.

I would suggest this establishment for a quick, delicious lunch that is easy on the budget.

Kohl's Department Store is enormous, offering a wide range of products including jewelry, clothing, picture frames, and shower curtains. This variety makes Kohl's an ideal shopping destination when you need to purchase multiple gifts for different individuals, as you can often find everything you need in a single visit.

At Kohl's, there are often great bargains to be had, but it's important to monitor the checkout process carefully. There have been instances where the sale prices were not applied correctly, which could have resulted in less favorable prices had I not noticed the error.

Don't forget to explore the shoe section as well. There, you might discover some stylish footwear at reasonable prices, especially if you visit on the right day. They've also added a makeup department, though I have yet to try any products from there.

Kohl's resembles a slightly more upscale version of TJ Max. It's worth a visit.

The Victoria's Secret at this location doesn't compare to the one at Scottsdale Fashion Square. They consistently lack a variety of sizes, and it's almost guaranteed they won't have mine whenever I visit. This issue isn't unique to me; several of my friends have experienced the same problem.

For a better selection and a larger store, I recommend visiting the Victoria's Secret at Fashion Square.

Is there any connection to Fox and Hound?

This establishment offers some fantastic drink deals! A friend and I decided to drop by unexpectedly and were quite impressed. Despite the bar's slightly shabby appearance, it's an excellent venue for enjoying fried snacks and indulging in drinks without breaking the bank.

During happy hour, their well drinks are only $2. Just imagine, two dollars! I was thrilled about that. All you need is a ten-dollar bill and a little extra for a tip, and you're all set. The drinks are potent, and the bar attracts a good number of attractive guys as well.

There are plenty of TVs around, making it an ideal spot to catch a game. No matter where you sit, you're guaranteed a good view of the ongoing sports due to the abundance of screens.

Incredible Mexican cuisine at unbeatable prices considering the quality offered. I've never paid more than $5, and the meals are consistently tasty. It's true that the area isn't the best, and there have been instances where cars were broken into during my visits, yet I continue to frequent the place. I'm willing to take the risk.

During lunch hours, Carolina's is bustling with local professionals, making it hard to secure a seat. It might be wiser to order takeout, so you don't have to worry about your vehicle and can still savor Carolina's delightful offerings.

Last time, I noticed a few bullet holes in the vicinity, but that seems common for the area, doesn't it?

Don't be put off by these details. If you're a fan of Mexican cuisine, it's definitely worth visitingâjust try to avoid nighttime visits.

The Rosson House Museum, a beautifully restored dwelling from 1895, is ideally situated next to the Teeter House Tea Room and opposite Pizzeria Bianco.

For less than $5, visitors can enjoy a guided tour of the Rosson House and discover the historical lifestyle of its past inhabitants. This activity is particularly appealing as it combines educational experiences with the convenience of nearby dining options for a meal or drinks post-tour.

As you wander through the house, it's not hard to picture the mistress of the home enjoying her tea in a delicate cup, adorned with lace gloves. Or perhaps that's just my imagination.

Visiting such homes often gives me a sense of unease; I almost expect to encounter a spectral figure in a pinafore lurking around each corner. Thankfully, that was not the case.

Regardless, spending an afternoon touring Heritage Square and its historic structures is an excellent way to pass the time.

For many years, I resided near Spectrum Mall, which I still fondly refer to as Christown. This place has always shown great promise.

However, the mall consistently fails to reach its full potential. Perhaps it's due to the groups of intimidating youths loitering around, or the low-quality, unappealing clothing shops that contribute to making it a less desirable shopping destination. On my last visit, I was surprised to find a single large communal dressing area in one of the stores. Quite shocking, indeed.

Efforts have been made to enhance the mall's appeal by introducing a variety of stores, and while there has been some improvement, the undesirable crowd persists. And please, avoid the Walmart at all costsâit is by far the filthiest, most unpleasant part of the mall. It's best to steer clear of it. Moreover, if you park near the entrance, be ready to encounter vendors who are quite insistent, selling tamales and unsettling dolls. Although I recognize their hustle, their approach can be overly assertive and somewhat troubling, especially when they follow you to your car.

The food court also leaves much to be desired. For a better experience, I suggest driving up Lincoln, turning right on Scottsdale Road, and heading to Scottsdale Fashion Square. There, you'll find private fitting rooms and no one will pressure you into buying odd dolls.

If you're a fan of Chinese cuisine, Tao Garden will likely appeal to you. The restaurant offers a wide variety of standard, delicious Chinese dishes, boasting an extensive menu. Their selection includes numerous chow meins, lo meins, tofu options, seafood, and soups, presenting a challenge when it comes to making a choice. The vegetable spring rolls are tasty and crisp, and they're fairly simple to prepare well, in my opinion. The accompanying sauce is also exceptional.

Regarding service, I didn't encounter the slow service mentioned in another review. My server performed adequately, though a bit more attentiveness wouldn't have gone amiss. Overall, I enjoyed my experience at this restaurant and would certainly visit again. The prices are reasonable, and occasionally, you can find discount coupons in the New Times.

I've often pondered the sustainability of Harry and David's business model outside the festive season. During December, when gift choices become perplexing, many opt for an H and D gift basket, typically containing jam, a salami stick, and crackers. Similarly, if your employer presents a holiday gift, it's likely to be an H and D basket.

However, once the holiday cheer subsides, who remains a regular customer of this company? Does the demand for large salami sticks and exotic sweets persist throughout the year?

I'm a big fan of Sprouts for their top-notch fruits and vegetables, which are always fresh, with many organic options, all at fair prices. They stock a comprehensive range of produce, free from the excessive pesticides often found in supermarket offerings.

Moreover, Sprouts offers a great selection of vitamins and frequently runs sales on them, helping you save money. Their store also includes a modest selection of frozen items and organic pantry staples such as macaroni and cheese, cereal, and canned goods.

The deli at Sprouts is equally commendable. Not only are their sandwiches tasty, but they also offer a variety of delicious ready-to-eat options from their chilled section.

Additionally, if you inquire at the store, they can inform you about various upcoming workshops, covering topics from healthy living to managing depression.

If you're in the market for charming, laid-back attire, American Eagle offers a variety. Their selection includes tank tops, t-shirts, small polos, capris, shorts, and more, similar to what you'd find in any typical apparel shop, yet their range distinctly leans towards a preppy casual vibe.

What draws me to this store particularly are their jeans. They provide several cuts tailored to different body shapes, all of which are high quality. Additionally, their prices tend to be lower than what other mall stores charge. It's often possible to snag a stylish pair for less than $50.

Next time you visit the mall, make sure to drop by and explore their collection. If there's a sale ongoing, you might also discover some great deals.

My affection for Golfland/Sunsplash remains strong, and I'm proud to say so. Despite my dislike for the presence of noisy, unclean children who urinate in the pool, I still genuinely enjoy the place.

During my youth, I was thrilled by the wild water slides that seemed to launch you into the air, teetering on the brink of disaster. These days, however, I prefer the calm of the lazy river.

I find it perfectly fine to relax in a floating tube, carried gently by the currents of a looping stream.

It's crucial to bring ample sunscreen and apply it regularly to avoid getting severely sunburned.

The Waikiki beach area, known for its large waves, is also enjoyable, though it often becomes overcrowded. It might be wiser to explore quieter attractions to avoid the chaos of crowded spaces.

I get it, the Big Bang is a crowd favorite, but honestly, I can't stand it.

It feels like a form of punishment to be there, listening to the same performers deliver the same songs and jokes repeatedly.

Initially, I might have enjoyed the place when I first heard a female performer belt out "I wanna shoop baby," but that charm wore off quickly after hearing it a few more times.

Here's the backstory: I used to oversee alcohol promotions, and the Big Bang was on our list of venues every Friday night. So, for half a year, I was there every week, and the novelty faded fast after the first visit.

While it might be great for occasional celebrations or a sporadic visit, as a regular haunt for the weekends? Absolutely not.

For those on the west side, Pat's Pizza Plus is an excellent choice for affordable pizza. It may be a tiny spot in a shopping center, but the pizza is quite delicious. Although there are superior pizza places, if you're looking for something fast, inexpensive, and tasty, this is a good place to visit or order from.

Ah, Staples, a place I'm quite familiar with.

Working from home often means visits to Staples are inevitable. I don't have a supply closet, so I purchase all my office necessities there. The staff at this particular store not only know my name but are also exceptionally helpful and friendly.

They efficiently guide you to the exact location of the items you're searching for and offer recommendations when needed.

Staples stocks a comprehensive range of home office supplies, from furniture and writing instruments to organizers and mouse pads. Their prices are generally reasonable, though some items might be found for less at Target or similar retailers.

However, for those who prefer getting everything in one go, Staples is superb.

Absolutely fantastic!

For authentic, homemade Italian cuisine reminiscent of what your mother might cook, this spot is ideal. The meals are scrumptious and very reasonably priced. Surprisingly so, given the quality. It's a quaint local Italian eatery that truly impresses.

You might be able to bring your own wine, though I'm not entirely sure. It's best to call in advance to confirm and inquire about any corkage fees. I opted for a soda during my visit (quite the surprise, I know!), but I plan to bring a bottle of wine next time if permitted.

I enjoyed the tortellini, which was exceptionally tasty. My boyfriend had the ravioli, which he thoroughly enjoyed, though I didn't sample it due to the meat content. We both indulged in the homemade cannolis, and they were completely worth it.

This has quickly become one of my top restaurant choices, and I have a feeling it might become one of yours as well!

Tucked away in a nondescript building, this charming Greek eatery is a hidden gem. Its exterior gives no clue to the delightful dining experience that awaits inside. The ambiance is reminiscent of a family-owned establishment, complete with a menu filled with traditional Greek dishes.

The selection of dishes is quite broad, surpassing what is typically offered at other Greek spots I've visited. On the menu, you'll find gyros, sandwiches, pitas, various plates, and starters. I particularly enjoy the hummus starter and the falafel dishâthey are both exceptionally tasty. Additionally, their spanakopita is notably delicious.

Do not miss out on the homemade baklava for dessert; it's a decision you'll appreciate.

Brookstone is an exciting place to shop. They stock a variety of quirky items, which adds to the enjoyment of exploring their store. During my last visit, I encountered an amusing exercise machine that you mount and simulate riding like a cowboy or cowgirl. It's named something like ihorse or igiddy-up, though I'm not entirely sure of the exact name.

They also offer top-notch memory foam mattresses that feel like sleeping on a cloud!

If you're in need of a unique gift and are unsure what to buy, Brookstone is the place to go. With their wide range of products including electronics, items for bed and bath, kitchenware, and numerous gadgets, you're sure to find something distinctive and appealing.

My feelings towards Gap are mixed. At times, I leave the store with a plethora of stylish outfits, while other visits leave me questioning its continued existence.

I do wish Gap was more consistent, but it's a hit or miss situation, isn't it?

Currently, I'm quite fond of Gap, primarily because of their Red clothing and accessory series. A portion of the sales from this line supports a charity that supplies AIDS medication to both adults and children in Africa. It's a commendable initiative, allowing you to buy everything from t-shirts to purses adorned with the Red emblem. I own a t-shirt that reads "Hamme(red)," which I got simply because it was the only one left in the Red collection at that time, not due to any penchant for drinking.

Red products are available both online and in physical stores. If you're going to buy fashionable items, why not support a good cause simultaneously? Give it a look.

944 has evolved into a respectable magazine. It originated in Scottsdale but has since spread to Los Angeles, Las Vegas, and possibly other locations. Initially, it was quite poor in quality, riddled with typos and offering articles that hardly seemed worth reading. Many people were drawn to it primarily for its extensive collection of party photographs, featuring the typical crowd of overly tanned men with spiky hair and women with bleached blonde hair, captured by their photographer at local bars.

Today, the situation has improved significantly. With a competent editor and skilled writers, 944 has enhanced its content and expanded into major cities. I once received this magazine at my doorstep while residing in a Scottsdale apartment â the complex distributed it to all tenants. However, since relocating, I've noticed fewer copies.

Although 944 will never top my list of favorite magazines, it's impressive that it began here and can still be enjoyable occasionally.

I often wish Lombardo Gelato had a location in a mall I visit more frequently than Fiesta, Arrowhead, or Desert Sky. It feels like they're deliberately making it difficult for me!

Regrettably, I rarely visit those malls, yet they are the exclusive spots where you can find Lombardo's. It seems I'll have to savor this delightful gelato place only occasionally.

During my last visit to Fiesta Mall, I tried their cookies and cream gelato, which was exceptional. They also offered a pineapple flavor that was authentically delicious, complete with real pineapple pieces. It was a tough choice, but I ended up indulging in the cookies and cream.

If you find yourself tired while shopping, a stop at Lombardo Gelato can instantly lift your spirits. Plus, you can work off the indulgence with some vigorous shopping right after.

Whenever I suggest taking my mom out for lunch, she often opts for JB's. I can't quite understand her preference for it; to me, it seems like a slightly upgraded Denny's with a more subdued crowd. The menu, however, offers similar dishes at comparable prices.

I find the food acceptable. It's neither terrible nor impressive. The greasy options are ideal for curing a hangover, and they do offer a decent breakfast buffet on Sundays.

However, it's also a favored spot for families, which means you might encounter children's messy hands on buffet items. Consider this when you're about to eat some scrambled eggs.

I've tried the desserts, which include the usual brownie with ice cream and various pies, and found them quite enjoyable.

Overall, JB's is a reasonable option if you're unsure where to eat. And while I assure you I don't dislike children, I recommend arriving at the buffet early to avoid the little ones who might be a bit messy.

Fantastic small pizzeria! It's also quite welcoming for families, allowing you to enjoy your meal even in a lively atmosphere.

Besides pizza, the menu features a variety of dishes including tasty stuffed shells, various pastas, sub sandwiches, salads, and excellent appetizers. Buono's is an ideal spot for a quick weekday lunch, offering affordable specials and generous servings.

Should you find yourself craving a quick taco, burrito, quesadilla, or even a burger (oddly enough), consider visiting Del Taco after hours when superior alternatives are unavailable.

This establishment is a fast food joint, so it's wise to temper your expectations from the start. During my university days, I frequented this place, albeit primarily during the wee hours, which was probably the worst time for my health.

With a vast array of offerings ranging from french fries and nachos to shakes and salads, it seems challenging for them to perfect any single item.

The food isn't terrible, but it's not particularly impressive either. If Del Taco is your sole choice, then it might be worth a try. However, if other eateries are an option, I'd recommend passing on this one.

As the weather warms up, it's a good idea to consider ways to stay cool. Visiting Sugar Bowl is one such method.

Sugar Bowl, a charming pink ice cream shop, offers delicious ice cream, sundaes, shakes, and more. They do offer lunch options; however, it's best to dine elsewhere and save this spot for a sweet treat.

The food at Sugar Bowl is average, featuring standard fare like sandwiches, salads, and soups. However, their ice cream stands out as exceptionally tasty. Additionally, you can visit nearby galleries and stores afterwards, which is a great way to walk off the calories indulged in during your visit.

A recent visit to Biltmore Fashion Park has rekindled my affection for the place. The outdoor setting of this shopping center is delightful, though it can become uncomfortably warm.

The area boasts a wide variety of stores, including upscale brands such as Gucci and Saks, alongside everyday retailers like MAC, Origins, Brookstone, Tommy Bahama, and Pottery Barn.

What truly enhances the experience are unique stores like Lilies and Ladybugs and Betsey Johnson, which are not found just anywhere and are always worth visiting.

Additionally, there are numerous nearby dining options, ranging from CPK to Cheesecake Factory, and the pathways are beautifully adorned with grass and flowers. In my opinion, it offers an ideal shopping experience.

I adore shopping at Target. It's a one-stop shop with a vast array of items all conveniently located under a single expansive roof. Looking for stylish yet comfortable workout gear? They've got it. Trendy jewelry pieces like earrings and necklaces? They've got those too. Need electronics or cleaning products? You'll find them there as well. They even stock food and home decorations. The list is endless. What's more, Target offers unbeatable prices that don't compromise your values, unlike Walmart. For fans of Morningstar Farm's vegetarian options, Target offers them at lower prices than most supermarkets, and they've even started carrying wine in many locations. It's truly everything you could hope for.

This location is quite nice, though it's not ideal for those watching their calorie intake. I decided to sample the waffles, and I'm truly pleased that I did. They were rich, delicious, and the hashbrowns were outstanding. I would certainly visit again.

A friend of mine chose eggs, pancakes, and potatoes, and mentioned they were nearly the best he's ever tasted. You might not guess it from the outside since the restaurant appears somewhat shabby, but stepping inside and trying the food will leave you happy you did.

Pottery Barn is a store I'd frequent if my budget allowed. For now, I content myself with browsing their selection at Biltmore Fashion Park.

The store offers a wide range of products including furniture, bedding, home accessories, and small gifts. However, the prices are steep and the discounts during sales are minimal.

I managed to find some adorable pillows that matched my couch at a reasonable price, along with a fantastic picture frame. The larger items, though, I simply admire from afar.

Fans of modern or contemporary home furnishings and decor will appreciate Pottery Barn's offerings. They also carry exquisite jewelry boxes, making it a great place to find a unique gift that might not have crossed your mind.

Meh. 
Islands feels similar to a Chile's or Applebees. 
The food is passable but not particularly memorable, and I find the prices slightly steep for the quality of the meal.
The servings are generous, however, side items such as fries or a dinner salad are not included and must be purchased additionally.
The menu does offer an interesting selection of beverages, which is a plus, but I would recommend bypassing this restaurant and spending your money elsewhere.

I rate Arizona Center three stars because I once worked there at a restaurant (hint: Hooters). Without the nostalgia, I might deduct a star or two.

It's a letdown since the Arizona Center could be exceptional. The addition of some appealing, new shops could transform it into a vibrant outdoor mall, drawing more than just vagrants and prostitutes.

Unfortunately, that's not the case, and we end up dealing with vagrants who snatch fries from your plate when dining outdoors at Hooters and prostitutes who steal tips from tables.

It's not always quite so direâArizona Center attracts visitors who buy cactus magnets or kokopelli sweatshirts at its many souvenir shops before they head to the airport. There's also an Uno's Pizzeria, I think, and a cinema. Plus, it's a popular spot before Suns games (though not lately) and other local sports events.

A highlight is the option to rent their grotto for special outdoor events. The setting is picturesque with lush trees, streams, and flowers, and the rental price is quite fair compared to other high-priced venues in Arizona.

Showstoppers Live, my beloved, is more than meets the eye at Casino Arizona, which offers much more than mere gambling. They provide a variety of gaming activities like blackjack, keno, and slot machines, but they also host concerts. Among these, Showstoppers Live is my favorite, featuring performances by impersonators of Elvis, Tina Turner, The Four Tops, and others.

The venue is also known for its generous servings of cocktails, ensuring a delightful evening. Additionally, there's food available, and I even glimpsed what seemed to be an ancient pottery collection during my last visit. Cheers to Casino Arizona for such diverse entertainment offerings!

Something bizarre occurred while I was here. A woman by the counter mistook me for Victoria from Young and the Restless. How strange is that? I bear no resemblance to her, and I should know since I watched that series frequently in my youth. It was amusing trying to persuade her otherwise, though I doubt she was ever convinced.

The coffee I enjoyed was quite good, just an iced coffee enhanced with a splash of vanilla. I decided to experiment with something new, and it turned out to be delicious. Were this cafe nearer to my home, I'd likely become a frequent visitor.

Looking for vitamins or supplements? Hi-Health offers an extensive range, including some surprisingly extractable items and a variety of carb-free products that I hadn't imagined existed!

The employees here are extremely engaging, to the point where it's hard to tell if they're just being friendly or if they're a bit too insistent. All I know is that there are times when a person prefers to shop in peace, but that seems impossible here. Even a casual mention of just looking around won't deter the staff; they persist in offering assistance relentlessly. You'll need to resign yourself to their eager help, whether you're in the mood for it or not.

However, you might consider checking out Trader Joe's first. They also have a decent selection of vitamins at more competitive prices than you'll find here.

The Orpheum Theater stands as an essential component of Phoenix's cultural scene. Constructed in the 1920s, it consistently hosts a variety of entertaining events. The venue features theater, dance, and various other performances. Additionally, it will host the inaugural opera by the Phoenix Metropolitan Opera in December 2007, marking a significant first for Arizona. Exciting, isn't it?

Delicious Thai cuisine! Lemon Grass Thai Cafe, situated in a strip mall, might not look impressive from the outside, but the dishes served inside are delightful.

I particularly enjoy their vegetable bird's nests. These are crispy fried nests loaded with vegetables and a tantalizing sauce. The desserts also left a memorable impression, especially the coconut ice cream and the custard, both of which are excellent.

Castles-n-Coasters, formerly known as Golf-n-Stuff, has always been dear to me. Despite its somewhat rundown appearance, it remains an enjoyable destination, especially if you're not bothered by the large groups of middle and high school students.

During my younger years, I visited this place countless times. It was the chosen location for our school outings from fourth to eighth grade. I vividly recall one instance when my eighth-grade class made the trek from our middle school to Golf-n-Stuff. It's worth noting that at my middle school, it was typical for boys to sport gang-related colors and bandanas. We probably weren't the most reassuring sight for drivers waiting at traffic lights. As we walked past, I could hear the successive clicks of car doors locking, which I found amusing. It seemed I was among some intimidating peers, though I didn't consider myself one of them.

The venue offers various activities, including golf, a vast arcade, go-karts, bumper boats, and roller coasters. It's undoubtedly a place full of fun, but as I mentioned earlier, it tends to attract a crowd of tough-looking youngsters. Reflecting on it now, I might feel compelled to lock my car doors too if I saw them approaching en masse.

Bungalow is fantastic. The cuisine may not be the healthiest, but it sure is tasty. I've tried both their veggie burger with fries and their grilled cheese with fries.

What can I say? I have a thing for fries. No judging, please.

Continuing on, their bloody marys are exceptionalâspicy and packed with everything you'd expect in a good bloody mary.

Additionally, Bungalow's location is quite trendy. Having lunch there allows for a pleasant stroll around Old Town afterwards, which is great for burning off some of those calories.

I purchased several items from the pastry section at Mekong Supermarket. The baked cream bolos and coconut cream/sesame buns are my favorites. I usually heat them in a toaster oven to enhance their flakiness. On one occasion, after my visit to Mekong, I stopped by AA Wholesome as evening approached. The baker was actively preparing fresh pastries. In search of a coconut-flavored treat, she suggested a tiny, freshly baked coconut tart. Surprisingly, it measured only about 2.5 inches across. Although delicious and satisfying in terms of flavor, the cost was $1.45 each. This price was slightly higher than usual, yet the size justified it. However, I would not purchase it again. The bolos and buns, similarly priced, provide two servings each, offering better value.

The bakery maintains a clean and well-organized environment, with pastries made fresh daily. Pastries from the previous day are sold at reduced prices. It's best to visit just before closing to catch these deals. Unfortunately, I've never found my preferred items available at a discount. Despite the high prices, which are indicative of their quality, I would rate them three stars. A three-star rating is quite respectable.

I've only been there once, yet I've often thought about returning. My expanding list of destinations to explore is to blame! Hence, I find it hard to concur with those who claim that the valley lacks good food. Seriously??

I sampled a few sandwiches; unexpectedly, the vegetarian option was the highlight. The durian shake was fantastic. (Caution: familiarity and affection for durian are essential, otherwise it might shock you!).

Consider taking some baguettes with you. Remember, they accept only cash.

The fry bread was delicious, surpassing the corn muffins in the same basket. The salmon was mediocre; not particularly memorable. The menu was expensive, especially for someone like me who couldn't eat enough to justify the cost.

The most impressive aspect of this location is undoubtedly the view. While this resort offers other dining options with more flavorful dishes, it's advisable to enjoy happy hour here and seek other venues for lunch and dinner.

I took my mother out to dinner on Monday evening. It was our second visit to this restaurant, but unfortunately, it will be our last. Tapino doesn't seem to suit her tastes. Of the three appetizers we tried, she only liked the lamb kabob with quinoa, which cost $9. Out of the dishes I tried, it ranked second.

I had hoped to sample a glass of rose wine, priced at $7, knowing my mother likes it. However, she felt too tired for wine, so I've saved that idea for another time. Our meal began with butternut squash ravioli served with sage butter, costing $8. I love the combination of brown butter and sage, but my mother does not share this preference. I enjoyed the creamy sweetness of the squash and the firm texture of the ravioli. The sage butter brought a subtle saltiness, and the toasted pecans on top provided a perfect crunch. I wished I could have eaten all three pieces myself, as she didnât enjoy the one she tried, which was quite frustrating.

Next, we had baked escargots with butter, parsley, lemon, and puff pastry, also priced at $7. This dish was somewhat underwhelming compared to the ravioli. I liked the texture contrast between the snails and the overly crunchy pastry. However, the flavoring of butter and parsley was lackluster. My mother only tried one of the six escargots provided. Despite this, I finished the rest as I was quite hungry.

Finally, we had a skewer of three lamb kabobs with bell peppers and onions, served over cold saffron quinoa with a side of cucumber sauce, all for $9. The lamb was flavorful enough on its own, making the sauce unnecessary. The quinoa was particularly enjoyable.

I captured some photos of our dishes, and I plan to take a photo of the ravioli during my next visit.

On 8/11/12, I planned to enjoy a mani/pedi session with my sister and niece before dining with a friend that Saturday evening. We initially visited Scottsdale Nails II. Unfortunately, they were fully booked until late afternoon; it was only 10:30 am. The receptionist informed us of our scheduling conflict, so he recommended McDowell Mountain Nails on Frank Lloyd Wright Blvd. Although unfamiliar with it, I was aware of the location and proposed to my sister that we give it a try.

Located in the Target plaza, flanked by a Jamba Juice and a Ross, MMN was not hard to locate. Its exterior was modest, especially compared to Scottsdale Nails II and my previously favored Shea Nails on 92nd St. (refer to my reviews for more details). The interior was compact yet tidy, and, crucially, it did not have the overpowering chemical odor we encountered at our first stop. Upon entering, we met a young Caucasian male and an Asian female who was busy on a phone call. This was somewhat unusual as we typically see salons staffed entirely by Asians. I inquired if they could immediately accommodate our mani/pedi needs, including a simple manicure for my niece. The man confirmed they could, and after the woman ended her call, she organized the staff for us. I was assigned to "the new girl," which initially made me question why I was chosen for the newcomer. However, I remained optimistic about the experience.

Ann, the "new girl," was delightful. Despite being new to this salon, she had extensive experience as a nail technician. She had just completed her orientation that morning and I was her first client. Ann was gentle, attentive, and easy to talk to. For those concerned about language barriers, Ann speaks clear English and is also a biochemistry student, which made for engaging conversation.

Our session concluded just after my sister and niece finished theirs. My sister started with a spa pedicure followed by a manicure, while Ann began with my manicure. Seeing the decorative work on Linda's nails, I decided to add a pedicure for my niece, costing an additional $5 for color and $10 for designs.

The total came to $55 for my gel manicure and spa pedicure, and $25 for my niece's treatments, with a generous tip of just over 20%. My sister also opted for acrylic nails and a spa pedicure. We were all thrilled with the results and the service at McDowell Mountain Nails, promising ourselves a return visit next year. A note for future visits: MMN only accepts credit cards for services, so cash is needed for tips.

Date: 7/31. 
I had a late lunch consisting of Quiche Lorraine accompanied by a side salad. It appeared quite appetizing. However, it failed to satisfy my texture preferences. My taste buds were still enchanted by the onion tarte from Coup des Tartes. I was hoping this quiche would replicate that experience, but it was somewhat dry. Additionally, the salad was slightly lacking in dressing.

I would not choose the quiche again. Nevertheless, I plan to return and sample different dishes. For now, I will enjoy looking at the pictures I captured at Essence.

On 4/18/12, I indulged in a delightful late afternoon meal that began with a traditional mojito. I opted for the standard version over the Garden mojito listed under specialty cocktails due to a cucumber allergy. My choice was a simple mojito with Bacardi as the base. It was priced at $6 during happy hour and was excellently prepared with fresh mint, lime juice, a touch of ginger ale, sugar, and rum. Initially, the sweetness seemed a bit much, likely from the ginger ale rather than soda, but the alcohol might have influenced my eventual enjoyment.

I contemplated ordering a bruschetta plate featuring two types of cheese but changed my mind after perusing the dessert menu. Instead, I chose a small serving of Pesto chitarra for $10 and considered getting cherry zeppole later. This pasta has been on my mind for years, ever since I first saw it on another Yelper's post. The dish lived up to my expectations. Despite years of anticipation, it did not disappoint. I devoured the entire dish: every strand of "guitar" pasta, both halves of the grape tomatoes, every pine nut coated in grated parmesan, and all the pesto sauce. Some charred pieces of toasted focaccia were left behind, but the uncharred portions were perfect for soaking up the pesto-laden EVOO. The meal was exceptional.

At this point, a sensible, health-conscious individual might stop eating. However, I continued, especially since I was only halfway through my mojito. I ordered the zeppole for $6.50. They took a while to arrive, but I was not in a rush. When served, the six sugar-dusted, cherry-filled Italian dough puffs were irresistible, especially with the accompanying almond crema and Maker's Mark bourbon mascarpone. The strong bourbon flavor in the mascarpone was notable, and had I known how much I would enjoy the almond crema, I would have requested an extra pot of it.

Rating: 4.25 stars.

I eagerly anticipate my next visit.

Several years back, I attempted to dine here but the place was overcrowded and the wait was too long, ranging from half an hour to nearly an hour, so I decided to leave. Since then, I've kept CK on my list of places to try. Recently, when I learned that CK was promoting a Fourth of July deal (purchase one main dish and get another for $4), I figured it was a good opportunity to discover what the hype was about.

A fortnight prior, I arranged to meet a cousin for lunch at CK on the holiday. We were pleasantly surprised to find that CK also offered a brunch menu. As avid breakfast enthusiasts, we were excited to explore the breakfast offerings. While our server checked some ingredients for me, my cousin opted for one of CK's famed dishes, the Green chile burger, featuring poblano chile, cheddar, and chipotle aioli. We noticed the absence of the chipotle aioli, but this issue was swiftly resolved upon our request. The service was notably friendly and prompt during our meal. I hesitated between choosing the French omelet and the Lemon-ricotta hotcakes. Initially confusing the omelet with French toast, we were eager to order it, but I ended up selecting the Classic French omelet with sautÃ©ed spinach, gruyere, and herbs, along with a hotcake. Unfortunately, the omelet was overdone. Both my cousin and I found it less than satisfactory, so we informed our server who kindly replaced it with another plate of hotcakes, which we devoured quickly. Regrettably, I didn't capture a photo as I was too eager to eat. My cousin thoroughly enjoyed her burger, finishing it entirely, which was surprising as she usually doesn't eat as much as I do.

The ambiance of CK was charming, featuring elegant dark wood furniture, cozy booths, and heavy red curtains contrasted with light floral decorations. The setting seemed a perfect blend of classy bistro and country French aesthetics, which I found quite appealing.

Days before the Fourth, I planned to try the dinner menu with a friend. We met there just before 6 PM. The restaurant was bustling, louder, and darker than during the day. We faced a wait of about 30 minutes and chose to wait at the bar, where we were given a buzzer. He ordered a cucumber-infused cocktail, and I chose a blackberry-prickly pear mix. Unfortunately, both drinks were served without coasters, causing water to drip onto the table and, in my case, onto my clothing. Even after being seated, our drinks remained without coasters, now accompanied by water glasses, leading to a messy table.

Before being seated, I needed to use the restroom. I had noticed earlier that navigating the restaurant in my four-inch heels was challenging due to the slippery textured floor. On my way back from the restroom, I slipped on a water spill in the hallway between the kitchen and the bar. Fortunately, I managed to regain my balance without falling. I alerted a passing employee about the spill and the potential hazard, but she seemed indifferent and continued on her way without addressing the issue.

The dinner itself was satisfactory. My friend was interested in the salmon but opted for the filet mignon, while I, secretly wanting the filet, chose the salmon so we could sample both dishes. The filet mignon was excellent, cooked to near perfection, though slightly redder than requested. The kitchen had run out of mixed vegetables, so my friend was served bok choy, which he initially hesitated to try but ended up enjoying. The salmon would have been great if not for a slight off-taste, which was somewhat masked by the lemon-white wine sauce. Nonetheless, we finished our plates.

Despite some setbacks, our experiences at CK for both brunch and dinner were enjoyable overall.

My friends and I gathered at this location for a happy hour and had a great time! I got there early, which allowed me to find a parking spot directly in front of the entrance. The retail section of the place offered a unique assortment of items. It featured everything from leather jackets sold by weight and eco-friendly organic t-shirts, to hand-painted glassware and retro-style candy. There was even a boxing ring available for impromptu sparring sessions! Regarding the jackets, I assumed they were priced uniformly per pound. However, each jacket had a different price per pound, which was a bit misleading and made me less interested in shopping. I decided to explore the restaurant's food and beverage options instead. The indoor seating was designed for communal dining with long tables and tall benches. Outside, picnic tables and a food trailer created a casual dining atmosphere, where customers would order and pick up their food. This setup was fine for outdoor dining but less appealing indoors, especially as some of my friends ordered food and others did not, and we preferred to stay away from the smoke and chilly air.

Two friends managed to arrive before the happy hour ended at 6 PM, but Linda missed the drink specials due to a phone call. I tried a grasshopper cocktail for the first time and liked it so much that I later bought ingredients to make it at home. The friend who missed the happy hour special had wanted a light beer just before 6 PM but was told it wasn't available. We all enjoyed our choices and planned to return for another happy hour.

One friend, who is both gluten-free and vegetarian, had to modify her order after finding out the kitchen was out of certain ingredients. She ended up enjoying an omelet skillet with mushrooms, spinach, and goat cheese, praising the freshness of the vegetables. I ordered brisket sliders and homemade potato crisps. The crisps were supposed to be baked with extra virgin olive oil but turned out too greasy and overcooked. However, my gluten-free friend found them irresistible. The brisket sliders were recommended as the best, but I found some pieces tough and the leftovers fatty. I wouldn't order them again. Linda chose a baked cinnamon-pecan French toast for dessert, which looked so good that I tried some despite my pecan allergy. I carefully avoided the nuts but still enjoyed the caramelized parts of the toast. I hope the kitchen can create similar desserts with different nuts like walnuts or almonds.

Although we're not eager to return for a meal, another happy hour here is definitely a possibility.

After a two-hour exploration of some exquisite instruments, Violeta and I agreed to gather at the local cafe.

The cafe was bustling at 1pm, featuring two distinct areas. Both sections shared the same decor, yet one resembled a typical coffee shop. It boasted a curved counter, decorated with cookies and deli cases stocked with water, juices, and more, though we opted for the alternative section. This area offered a more expansive ambiance with large windows that somewhat brought the outdoors inside, giving it the vibe of a lively, eco-friendly bistro. I appreciated the setting, though it could have used more than one busser. It seemed there was only one, leading to a delay in getting tables cleared. Eventually, I approached him to request our table be cleaned. The wait would have been less bothersome had I not been in a hurry to eat before heading to school.

The cafe had an upscale, organic feel. The line cooks appeared as though they belonged in a high-end steakhouse, and the menu presentations suggested a commitment to quality. The menus hinted at local and some organic ingredients, yet I hope for better quality oils in the futureâno to GM soybean, canola, cottonseed, and corn oils! My meal, a 6 oz. grass-fed burger with perfectly seasoned sweet potato fries, was delightful. I plan to try the desserts next time, as they looked temptingly sinful.

P.S. I was less thrilled about having to fetch my own cutlery and napkins. The setting would be better suited to cloth-wrapped cutlery presented on the tables, rather than housed in metal holders as if in a buffet or workplace cafeteria. However, the paper napkins provided were notably absorbent and high-quality.

For several days, I had been longing for a chocolate croissant. I finally decided to sample the ones available here. By the time it was 2:30 PM, the selection of pastries and desserts was limited. I initially wanted to try both an almond and a chocolate croissant. Unfortunately, they were out of almond croissants. Only three chocolate croissants remained, along with a few raisin ones. I opted for a chocolate croissant to take away. Before I left, I tasted it to decide whether to buy the others. Ultimately, I took all three.

Each chocolate croissant cost $2.70, plus tax. I didn't get a chance to sample the local coffee. I plan to return earlier next time, hoping to get an almond croissant, or perhaps two.

The arrangement of the tables impressed me; they created a romantic atmosphere. I am eager to have dinner here soon. I noticed three different types of entremets in the display cases, and the truffles looked tempting.

Over a week ago, during happy hour, I enjoyed calamari with aioli, a Rene Barbier red wine, and a brandy-flambeed flan. I also indulged in several delicious dinner rolls. The first thing that struck me about the calamari was its striking hue. I inquired if it was saffron. Indeed, it was. The calamari rings had been dipped in a saffron-infused batter, making them both visually appealing and flavorful. The aioli was delightfully simple. Regarding the flan, Xavier proposed a challenge: if I didn't find it to be the best flan I'd ever tasted, he wouldn't charge me the $7 fee. Although it wasn't the finest I've experienced (my mother's flan holds that title, and I've been told I make an excellent one myself), it was still exceptionally tasty. I saw no reason to argue over the price and happily paid the full amount.

For my next visit, I plan to try the frog legs and perhaps a sangria or two.

This morning, I received another pair of texts from "Iolanda." I thought they might amuse some of you. I have no plans to return to 98 South. Hopefully, this information is useful to you. By the way, aren't orangeheads the best? It's so much simpler to throw insults from behind a disguise!

19 minutes ago: Clearly, rebuttal isn't your ally, but jealousy seems to live right next door.

9 minutes ago: I assumed the drink was intended for your male companion, yet it was you who ended up leaving it behind. It's probably unwise to have your photo out there... pug! You're such an easy mark. Let's head to the west side... yay!

Roughly five or six years back, my wonderful sister gifted me a charming jar of Aveda Soothing Aqua Therapy as a Christmas present. I had long been curious about this product but felt hesitant to spend $24 on 16 ounces of bath salts, a price which has now risen to $30. The jar came as part of a gift set, although Aveda typically does not provide product discounts. I am grateful, however, for the ability to tailor gift sets with particular items that I know the recipient will adore.

Should you ever find yourself puzzled over holiday, birthday, or special occasion gifts, consider visiting an Aveda store. Many women I know adore Aveda's offerings. Some deny it, yet secretly love them despite the high costs. And if you're buying for a man? Let me share a secret: men also relish Aveda's pampering products. I've purchased hair care items, mint soaps, and aftershaves from them, and even the toughest men can't help but smile when they receive these gifts.

Returning to the topic of the soothing bath salts, I use them sparingly for special occasions. This might be when I run out of my usual detoxifying Epsom salts or when my Aura Cacia Pure Aromatherapy Foam Bath sampler doesn't seem appealing. It's disheartening to think that after tonight's delightful bath, I'll only have enough left for one more luxurious soak. I know where to purchase a new jar, but some joys in life feel more special when received as gifts. With Valentine's Day approaching, it's something to think about.

I'd love to rate this particular store with five stars, but I can't due to the decline in customer service over my last few visits, which occur once or twice annually. The once warm and enthusiastic welcomes have diminished, and the once customary hot cup of licorice-mint tea is now seldom offered. Despite these changes, my affection for their products remains, though I now mostly purchase them from Moodswings salon in Tempe.

A useful tip: Epsom salt baths are excellent post-massage. They significantly reduce soreness and inflammation. I was skeptical when my former therapist recommended them, but after trying it, I found it genuinely beneficial. Now, I rarely skip a post-massage soak, even if it takes hours before I can take one.

Students are eligible for discounted rates exclusively on Thursdays. On other days, the ticket price for everyone is $9.50 after 6 p.m., although seniors might receive a discount. Fortunately, garage parking is free for the first four hours.

Additionally, if I arrive at least fifteen minutes early, I can fit in a quick exercise session. Climbing the staircases is a great way to stay active before watching a film.

On 11/22/10, I inadvertently missed my turnoff. My mind was elsewhere, and I automatically drove the usual route home. Consequently, I had some difficulty locating the parking area due to unfamiliarity with the city's streets and their directional signs. However, once I located the place, everything went smoothly. I managed to save some money compared to the cost of long-term airport parking. Interestingly, I discovered FastTrack while booking flight tickets online. Before finalizing the parking reservation, I decided to check FastTrack's own site. To my surprise, it was cheaper than using the link from Orbitz! (Note: You have the option of choosing between covered or uncovered parking, with the former being more expensive.)

Our experience with the shuttle service involved two different drivers. The first was quite amiable, but the second went above and beyond. He not only helped with our luggage when boarding and disembarking but also placed our bags directly into my car when we returned to the parking lot. His exceptional service warranted a larger tip compared to the first driver.

Shuttles to and from the airport are frequent, but you can also contact the dispatcher directly to confirm the shuttle's arrival using the number provided by the driver. We definitely plan to use this service again in the future!

Rated at 2.5 stars.

I visited during happy hour, yet the offerings on the special menu failed to appeal to me. Consequently, I opted for a medium Emilia Romagna pizza, featuring mozzarella, parmesan, and 12-year aged Aceto Balsamico balsamic vinegar. The cost of the pizza was likely around $14. Unfortunately, the pizza's bottom was overly charred. Additionally, its ultra-thin crust lost its crispiness within minutes, turning soggy shortly after. Although the initial slice at the restaurant was enjoyable, the reheated leftovers at home were excessively salty, leading me to discard them. This was not cost-effective for the price, regrettably. At the restaurant named Fred's, I consumed only one slice because I was eager to sample the day's special cobbler, an apple cobbler served with Haagen-Dazs ice cream, which I remember having to order without powdered sugar due to a corn allergy. It was pleasantly not too sweet. I would consider trying other cobblers they offer, but the high price ($9, plus the ice cream contains corn syrup) deters me. The profiteroles also caught my interest, priced at $9, which breaks down to $4.50 each, and I recall there being two per serving.

The bartender, resembling a bouncer, might seem off-putting with his stern expression, but he was actually quite amiable during our initial conversation. However, a subsequent visit with friends after a mixer a month later revealed a less welcoming side. He seemed too preoccupied to engage beyond taking our order, offering no greetings or pleasantries that evening. This, combined with the steep menu prices, discourages me from returning.

Initially, I considered giving a 3-star rating, but after reflecting on my experiences for this review, I've decided on 2 stars. Hopefully, others will find their visits more satisfying.

Date: 8/06
My initial visit occurred during happy hour. I opted for two sushi rolls: a Philadelphia roll and a spicy salmon roll, both deep-fried and topped with roe. Typically, sushi establishments are accommodating when it comes to substituting ingredients due to allergies, often without an additional charge. However, Kabuki was an exception. I have been informed by various restaurant owners, chefs, and cooks that they are usually willing to make such changes without any issue. Unfortunately, the chef at Kabuki did not share this approach. Consequently, the images of the food I captured lack certain ingredients. I also ordered a glass of house pinot grigio, which initially came with a large black speck in it, though this issue was swiftly addressed.

The selection of appetizers and beverages for happy hour was limited. The servers showed adequate hospitality, yet the sushi chef clearly displayed irritation when I had to send back a dish due to the presence of an allergen I had specifically asked to avoid. It would be understandable for the chef to be upset had I omitted this critical information or had an extensive and complex order, but the error occurred on just the second dish, despite a clear list of allergens provided as a reminder.

The ambiance was unremarkable. However, I appreciated the single red mosaic tile in the women's restroom, which provided a striking contrast to its predominantly black decor.

The Bavarian cream truly astonished me. It was seductive and smooth, surpassing all other versions of this donut type I have sampled to date. If you indulge, you'll find yourself (quite literally) unable to face the world the next day. Proceed with care!

The waterfall serenaded us with its melodious lullaby just as we noticed it at the entry of the restaurant. That night was somewhat cool, and I sensed Mamang might resist the idea of eating outside. Nevertheless, I opted for outdoor seating. Spotting several heaters around, I was confident we'd stay warm. It was a pleasant shock to get a table adjacent to the soothing waterfall we had passed earlier! My worries about Mamang feeling too cold were unfounded; in fact, she ended up feeling overly warm. Luckily, cousin Melissa was happy to switch seats with her.

Our meal included flaming saganaki, an "award-winning" gyro platter (with lamb and beef, delicious rice, sautÃ©ed vegetables, and perfectly cooked lemon-roasted potatoes), a side of Greek salad, and for dessert, flaming galaktoboureka (custard in crispy phyllo, crowned with vanilla ice cream, set aflame, and finished with a caramel drizzle). The three of us indulged heartily, yet no complaints were heard. It was Mamang's first taste of Greek food, making the evening memorable with its outdoor setting, ambient lighting from palm trees, the waterfall, and delectable dishes. It was an ideal farewell for our beloved grandmother, feeling homesick after six months in the US. She departed for Manila the previous day, Monday. I hope she finds more joy back home. Mamang, whenever you enjoy a fresh mango shake, remember me! In spirit, I'll be enjoying one right beside you :)

First downside: The dim lighting. It hindered my ability to appreciate the visual appeal of our meals. It also meant that our photos likely turned out poorly. Fortunately, my cousin's digital camera had a strong flash. See the attached photos for reference.

Second downside: The service was disappointing. Our appetizer arrived, but no utensils were provided. Unable to locate our server, I fetched three sets from another table. Additionally, we nearly missed the flaming performances of both the saganaki and galaktoboureka. Both cousin and grandma mistook it for an actual fire, which was amusing (unless it had been a real emergency). A prior warning from the staff would have been helpful.

Third downside: The restroom conditions were appalling. The counter was soaked, and the floor was strewn with paper towels. This was a stark contrast to the wonderful atmosphere we enjoyed on the patio, despite the inadequate lighting.

I was nearby for an event starting in half an hour on November 11, 2010, feeling quite famished. My earlier meal, consisting only of desserts and wine, seemed insufficiently nutritious for the night's end. Thus, I opted to visit Red Devil. The place was nearly empty, hosting just one dining couple, and it appeared most patrons preferred takeout that night.

The bartender seemed amiable initially, but his demeanor changed when I inquired about the food's components. He became less engaging, losing his smile. I nearly walked out then and there. Regrettably, when my meal was served 25 minutes later, I wished I had. 

The calzone I ordered was disappointing with its limp crust devoid of any crunch, and the mozzarella-ricotta blend was unappealing and tastelessâI couldn't discern any ricotta flavor. (Refer to the attached photos.) The only decent aspect was the marinara sauce, yet it hardly mattered since the main dish was unenjoyable. I quickly packed up the leftovers and left after a mere five minutes of trying to eat. I had a party to catch.
