Postscript: Reflecting on my environmental ideals, I'm embarrassed by my actions. I discarded the leftovers immediately upon leaving Red Devil, despite my initial intention to keep them. I should have left them at the restaurant.

As my car was being fixed at The Auto Shop and we had some time to kill, I decided to take Mom for a nice breakfast at Matt's Big Breakfast, where I had previously only enjoyed a lunch. However, the queue was too long, so we opted for lunch at AE across the street, highly recommended by the shop's manager.

The place was basic, with cafeteria-style seating and TVs. They offered self-service coffee and tea, and Splenda was available for those who prefer it. The breakfast options were appealing, yet we had to wait for the egg delivery for about 10 minutes. Instead, we chose the Friday special: grilled tilapia on a bed of salad and a gyro pita with extra feta on the side. The tilapia was frustratingly fragile, breaking apart easily when I tried to eat it, and was quite tasteless since I skipped the house vinaigrette due to allergies. Fortunately, the added feta made the meal palatable. The gyro pita was better, though Mom wasn't fond of the meat. It wasn't as good as the gyro I had recently at MBFGR, but it was decent for the price. AE imports their gyro meat from Chicago three times a week, as the counter staff informed me.

I was tempted by the baklava, but had to pass due to allergies. Nonetheless, the menu had plenty of satisfying options.

Two weeks prior, I enjoyed a whole-wheat pancake at the Dobson branch, topped generously with blueberries and glazed pecans. It was a Tuesday, which meant benefits like double stamps. The pancake was large, covering the entire plate, as is typical there. Unfortunately, my experience this Monday at the Central Ave. branch was less impressive (for details, see my review and photos from that day). Later, for lunch, I chose the Isle of Capri omelette. It came with an English muffin and country potatoes, serving enough for two. I opted out of sharing a photo due to its unappealing appearance in a styrofoam container. Despite its look, don't be deterred by the aroma of feta and olives; the omelette is quite tasty!

I absolutely adored the interior atmosphere. The view overlooking the pizza oven was appealing. Both the salad and sandwich I enjoyed for lunch with a companion were exceptional. I wish I could express the same enthusiasm for the pizza I consumed in the evening. However, I prefer thin-crust pizzas, and the one I tried was overly thick and doughy for my taste. I also brought back a pizza for my mother, who similarly did not enjoy it.

I appreciated the outdoor seating on the patio, though I arrived too early to experience the full romantic impact of the candlelit setting. The area's downtown vibe made me long to live there.

I visited this location several times a few years back when I resided in Chandler. Many from the Vietnamese community recommended this spot for Pho, including nail artists and colleagues. However, that was before the emergence of numerous new pho establishments.

Pho has never really excited me, and I'm unsure if I've sampled it at this venue. I have experimented with various appetizers and stir-fries here. Unfortunately, none have impressed me enough to merit significant praise (or, to put it another way, none have inspired me to post a review on YELP). The dated decor certainly doesn't add to the appeal. The one redeeming feature of Saigon Pho, for me, is the server, Crystal. She's exceptionally welcoming, efficient, and consistently offers recommendations tailored to your taste preferences.

Yelp Eats Week 2011 offers a 50% discount. Here's my experience on July 16, 2011:

I arrived earlier than my friend and was seated at a small table for two. I received the regular dinner menu initially. I had to request the Yelp Eats menu, which was unusual since other restaurants had provided it automatically (first oddity). Upon receiving it, I noticed a sticker advising against sharing meals (second oddity). While waiting for my friend Linda, I ordered a mojito for $7.50. I inquired about some dishes with our server, Ana, who was very knowledgeable about the menu (commendable job, Ana!). The mojito, excellently made with dark rum, fresh lime, muddled mint, sugar, and a splash of soda, arrived just as Linda walked in. She, too, opted for a mojito based on past experiences.

We chatted briefly before ordering. I chose the Bistec Encevollado (steak with onions) and Linda selected the Frituras de Frijoles Negros (black bean fritters with avocado dip). Despite my intention to skip appetizers to save room for dessert, Ana repeatedly asked about our appetizer choices. Linda decided to start with an appetizer and possibly order more later. Ana's repeated inquiries felt somewhat pushy (Linda ended up ordering another appetizer and a dessert later). Both the appetizer and my steak arrived simultaneously. I offered Linda a taste of my steak, which she declined due to her preference to limit red meat intake. However, she did try the Papas de la Casa (spicy homestyle potatoes), which she found overly salty. I described them as "highly-seasoned." They were indeed salty, and although I didn't detect the spiciness, my mother noticed it when she tried them at home. Linda offered me some fritters, but I declined as I had tried them before and wanted to focus on my steak. It turned out to be beneficial that Ana encouraged Linda to order more, as she enjoyed the Frituras de Camarones (three crispy shrimp pancakes with Romesco sauce). The sauce, which appeared to be thickened with nuts, had a distinct flavor that Linda couldn't quite identify, but it included almonds and sherry.

Ana checked a few times if I was ready for dessert, but I waited for Linda to finish her meal. I was still savoring my mojito and considered ordering another. Eventually, I chose the chocolate bread pudding with homemade dark fudge rum sauce, and Linda agreed to try the lime pie. Both desserts were delightful, though I particularly enjoyed the pie. That evening, the fudge rum sauce was irresistible. Regarding the lime pie, I managed to restrain myself after a few bites since I knew I had another one waiting at home.

We intend to return, especially on Mojito Mondays, which feature $3 mojitos all day. We hope the service attitude was just a temporary issue related to Yelp Eats Week. This location is quieter compared to the one on Camelback, which Linda appreciates. Despite the service, I tipped 20% on the pre-discount total of my bill, not wanting to appear stingy.

Upon entering, I noticed a strong body odor smell in the restaurant, reminiscent of onions. Had I not been meeting a friend, I might have chosen a different venue.

The Cuban bread served was outstanding.

I had marked Tortas El Guero on my list for several weeks. After hearing a friend rave about their torta, I decided to check it out during my upcoming days off. I arrived before 4:30 p.m., only to find that the woman at the counter spoke no English. Fortunately, my basic Spanish helped me communicate enough to modify my order slightly. If I had arrived after 5 p.m., I would have encountered the bilingual Caucasian server.

I opted for the carne asada torta. The bread was satisfactory, but the fillings were disappointingly scant. I would recommend that TEG either opts for smaller bread or increases the amount of filling. The price of the sandwich was excessively high. I would not purchase this sandwich again at such a price, especially considering the larger, equally delicious options available at Phoenix Ranch Market, where the telera bread is exceptional. Consequently, I had to order two additional tacos, one pastor and one carne asada, to use their fillings to supplement my torta. From my experience, should I return, I would choose the pastor torta, though a return visit seems unlikely.

Next door, however, the Michoacan ice cream parlor is a place I'll visit again. The coffee and mango ice creams were a treat. I find myself craving the coffee flavor even now.

Date: 02/07/10. I opted for take-out from Whitey's White, selecting a white cheese pizza with alfredo sauce and garlic. The crust was overly thick, lacking any crispy texture. The flavor was mediocre; not compelling enough for a repeat order. Post-meal, I experienced some allergic reactions, which isn't unusual at chain restaurants. The following day, I attempted to reheat a few slices. Unfortunately, they did not improve in quality, losing their flavor and failing to crisp up. Consequently, I discarded the remainder. It's unfortunate, as this place could have been an excellent spot for dining after spending time with friends nearby.

After watching "Roker on the Road," I developed a strong desire for dosa. I debated between "Udupi Cafe or Taj Mahal?" before settling on a return visit to Udupi Cafe.

I scrutinized the dosa offerings and chose the Udupi Special spring dosa, which was new to me. I inquired about allergens in the dosa and chutneys. I was confidently informed that the dosa was safe. However, I could not have two of the three chutneys [coconut and jalapeno-cilantro (?)], but the sambar was fine. (The presence of an allergenic ingredient was noted in the coconut chutney.) The assurance regarding the sambar was unexpected, as it typically contains allergens, which I've been warned about at other establishments. My server suggested tamarind sauce as a substitute for the restricted chutneys. Eager to taste, I sampled the sambar, enjoying a delicious piece of potato and some broth. Delicious! On a second taste, I was cautious of potential hidden allergens. Suddenly, both my server and the host came over to advise against consuming the sambar and dosa due to allergens. Frustrated, I had to send back my Udupi special spring dosa and the sambar, leaving me unsure of what to order next, knowing discomfort and nausea awaited me (symptoms began as I was paying).

The host then advised against any dosa with fillings, as the kitchen couldn't exclude a particular allergenic ingredient. Normally, this wouldn't be a major issue since other dosa options exist that could be served with chutneys, but the chutneys also contained the problematic ingredient. The chutneys, I learned, were prepared in large batches earlier, making alterations impossible. Consequently, dosas were no longer an option for me at Udupi Cafe. I opted for the assorted appetizer platter instead, which would have come with just tamarind sauce had I not requested plain yogurt as an additional accompaniment. When I asked if something could be added to the yogurt for flavor, the host suggested carrots. I agreed to carrots.

I enjoyed three items from the appetizer platter: cauliflower pakora, samosa, and veggie cutlet. I did not enjoy the dense mysore bonda or the bready medhu vada, though the latter was quite tasty when dipped in tamarind sauce and yogurt. Reflecting on the meal, I was disheartened by the constant reminder that everything was deep-fried.

Given Udupi Cafe's inability to modify dishes and the apparent pre-preparation of most items (contrary to other experiences where chefs eagerly modify sauces), I am unlikely to prioritize this cafe in future cravings for Indian food. There are plenty of other options available.

I extend my best wishes to Udupi Cafe and its team, hoping they continue to serve both vegetarians and omnivores with their entirely vegetarian menu. I recommend trying the Gobi Manchurian; it's quite delicious!

[The meal wasn't entirely disappointingâI managed to capture some visually appealing moments. I only wish I had a close-up of that veggie cutlet and the samosa.]

On 06/02/11, I brought my mother along for her first visit (and my second) to our chosen dining spot. We opted for a small Mista salad and a large Clevenger pizza, which features an olive oil base, sausage, spinach, red onions, feta, and omits the tomato sauce. The salad was served quickly, as it was ordered by our server before we had even chosen our pizza. The pizza, however, took longer to arrive because the staff needed extra time to thoroughly clean the oven from cornmeal to prevent any allergic reactions I might have. It was definitely worth the wait!

The Mista salad included a blend of mixed greens, tomato slices, crunchy walnuts, feta cheese, and was dressed with Florencia's excellent balsamic vinaigrette, which is also available for purchase. The combination of crunchy, creamy, and tangy elements made the salad not only enjoyable but also satisfying enough to be a main dish. Indeed, I was quite content with just half of the salad and would have been ready to head to our planned movie, but we ended up waiting about 30 more minutes for our pizza. However, the wait was trivial as the Clevenger pizza surpassed the Bravo I had during my first visit, which I had praised highly in a previous review, having consumed half of a medium pizza in one go.

I must apologize for the poor quality of the pizza photos included here; my Mac powerbook, which I normally use to adjust the lighting, is currently being repaired. Enjoy your meal!

Rated 2.5 stars.

My expectations were quite high prior to visiting the DBG for Las Noches de las Luminarias, influenced by tales of its enchanting atmosphere. However, the reality did not quite match up. The commercial dazzle of decorated homes, shopping centers, and eateries in recent years has outshone the somewhat simplistic display of luminarias made from plastic, resembling brown paper bags, and the basic strings of lights on trees. There were, admittedly, instances where the charm was undeniable, particularly near the grand, illuminated Christmas tree and at certain points where light columns encircled building tops, inviting a closer inspection amidst the soft strains of jazz that floated through the air like whispers of velvet. Yet, the evening was marred by excessive crowds, likely due to an unforeseen promotional deal offering tickets at half price ($12.50 instead of $25). The throngs of attendees made navigation difficult, particularly at one musical venue where my cousin and I had to backtrack due to the impenetrable crowd, complicating movement for those with mobility issues in the chilly, packed conditions.

While I believe the experience might have been more pleasant with less company and a more intimate setting, the standard entry fee of $25 seems steep. Instead, I might opt for a simple walk near my home for some exercise and invest $50 in enhancing my own space with ambient lighting, which promises longer-lasting enjoyment than a single evening at the DBG.

I'm not sure what happened to my reviews of U.S. Egg, yet I must admit, their protein pancakes are a favorite of mine. The space is limited; hence, plan for a longer wait during weekend peaksâbest to get there before 10 AM or after 11:30 AM. They stop serving breakfast at 2 PM. My mother is a fan of their skillets. I suggest skipping the biscuits and gravy.

After several months of postponing the evaluation of my garbage disposal for either removal or repair (I was reluctant to summon a repairman for just one issue), I found myself urgently needing a plumber to address a continuously leaking toilet tank after the shut-off valve proved ineffective. I turned to Yelp, where Gabi's glowing recommendation was a lifesaver! The positive feedback from both Gabi and Karri meant I didn't require further endorsements - if Duane was satisfactory for Gabi, he would suffice for me.

I reached out to Duane on Monday, hoping for a same-day visit, though I would have been content with an appointment as soon as Thursday. Duane let me know he was booked for the day but could fit me in the next day, necessitating a day off from work. Despite my reluctance to miss work unless absolutely necessary, I recognized the urgency: 1.) a leaky tank could lead to more severe and expensive damage if not addressed promptly, and 2.) conserving water is critical, particularly in the desert.

Duane not only managed all the necessary repairs within 90 minutes the following afternoon but also helped select a replacement garbage disposal at a local Home Depot during that time. He suspected the issue might be a simple obstruction like a stuck penny or shattered glass, as had occurred previously. Additionally, he inspected another toilet tank at the behest of a housemate. Instead of exploiting the situation for unnecessary repairs, Duane proved his integrity by confirming no repairs were needed. He eagerly demonstrated how to perform future repairs and even offered future guidance over the phone if I chose that option. I concur with Gabi and Karri that his charges are quite reasonable, and he is indeed a friendly and accessible person.

Duane's numerous commendable qualities, coupled with his extensive handyman and interpersonal skills, truly make him a gem!

Rated 4.5 stars!

I have visited Liberty Market multiple times, and today I had my first breakfast there. It was a delightful meal consisting of a stack of three pancakes priced at $6.5, with an extra topping of homemade granola for $1, accompanied by Grilled Flattened Meatballs for $3.5, and a double espresso for $2. The service was excellent. Unfortunately, I couldn't enjoy the homemade maple syrup, house-whipped cream, or any of the fruit compotes and flavored syrups available at the coffee station due to dietary restrictions. However, when I requested chocolate chips, they offered me a homemade chocolate syrup made from chocolate, sugar, and coconut oil, which was quite tasty. This syrup would also be perfect on ice cream.

I've noted previously, but it's worth mentioning again: purchasing an espresso or any specialty coffee at Liberty Market entitles you to unlimited refills of regular coffee during your meal. Even after a double espresso, I indulged in some of their house blend coffee. After consuming one and a half pancakes and the somewhat oily meatballs, along with the caffeine, I felt energized for several hours on just four hours of sleep.

P.S. Although I tipped over 20% at the register, I felt that Bruce, my server, deserved an extra tip for his patience during my extended stay. Another reason to appreciate Liberty Market!

Addendum: Bruce also provided directions to the quickest route to 101 N and offered a complimentary coffee for the road. My affection for Liberty Market continues to grow.

Helpful hint: Access free wifi by using the code found at the bottom of your receipt.

I made my initial "official" trip last Thursday and was quite taken aback by the experience! Previously, my visits were unremarkable, such as the time I returned footwear at the now-closed Naturalizer outlet. However, this visit had a specific purpose: to buy several olive body butters and shower gels for my mother. A major bonus is the presence of a See's Candies store directly across the mall on the north side of Tatum.

During a brief scan, I noticed an Express store among other unfamiliar shops. I might have explored these, but my current shopping goal is to find organic business-casual and dress attire suitable for both work and leisure, which seems unavailable at any local mall. The complex also features a children's play area and a separate Costco. I intended to quickly reach the wholesale club by foot, but the entrance did not face the mall exit, and my time was limited. I'll try again later.

PV mall has certainly been a revelation, much more so than Arizona Mills or even Tempe Marketplace. With the closure of the Body Shop and See's Candies at Scottsdale mall, I anticipate visiting PV mall more frequently to satisfy my monthly chocolate cravings.

Here's a tip: I was unaware that Spencer's doubled as an adult store until I saw some intriguing items there. I also noticed a few onlookers lurking around as I browsed the novelty section at the back. It was amusing to see the clerk saying farewell to a couple of teenagers, who seemed like they were familiar faces around there.

Rated 2.5 stars.

I brought my younger cousin along to O&I for happy hour, opting to sit at the bar. It was her inaugural visit. Although I admire the bar's island design at O&I, I often feel out of place there. I've tried to sit there alone several times, but I usually end up moving to a table. Without my cousin, I might have left entirely, as I have in the past. Despite my efforts to persuade her to try a cocktail, she refused, so I settled for a wine. Obtaining a taste of a few wines before making a selection here is inexplicably difficult. Just recently, at Beckett's Table, a server had no issue letting me sample two wines I was torn between. Very disappointing!

We chose the Italian Sausage flatbread and the hummus appetizer. The flatbread featured crispy crust, spicy sausage, bright piquillo peppers, and creamy goat cheese. Despite my usual aversion to peppers, I would order it again. The hummus came with homemade pita and a "petite Greek salad" of just red grape tomatoes and cucumbers, topped with a lot of feta. Oddly, the salad was on the hummus, not beside it. Given the appetizer's price, more vegetables would have been appreciated, like some lettuce, to make removing the cucumbers easier. As served, removing cucumbers would mean losing much of the tasty baked hummus. That would be a shame!

We had to leave before 6 p.m., missing the celebrity guest bartender. My cousin enjoyed the food and ambiance. The experience could have earned four more stars if not for the bartender's attitude when I requested wine samples.

Note: The happy hour menu has been significantly reduced, now offering fewer than eight items, a sharp decline from the previous selection of numerous appetizers, several flatbreads, and a few salads. Remembering this, along with the wine and salad/hummus issues, I might have to stop visiting O&I for quite some time.

Years ago, I held a membership at the Chicago Botanic Garden during my residency there. Upon relocating to the Phoenix valley in 2003, I discovered the Desert Botanical Garden (DBG) online. I immediately visited and secured an annual membership without prior exploration. Living in the desert, it seems fitting that the DBG would showcase an extensive collection of cacti, reminiscent of a Crowded House tune. My visits, however, may have been ill-timed (summer evenings, fall afternoons), leaving me somewhat disappointed. It was unfair of me to compare these gardens with Chicago's, which boasts 26 distinct gardens over 385 acres. Each garden deserves appreciation for its unique qualities. I enjoyed a relaxed jazz night there during a cool fall evening, enhanced by beautifully lit trees. Unfortunately, I've missed out on attending events like Agave on the Rocks, the Luminaria, or seeing the Chihuly exhibit.

I recently reviewed the garden's event schedule and found many appealing options. It looks like I might invest in another membership this year.

Here's an interesting fact: Did you know that pineapples and aloe vera are botanically related to cacti?

On the day before today, 10/21, I whipped up some honey-buttermilk pancakes for myself. They were loaded with Ghirardelli chocolate chips, banana slices, and cinnamon-roasted almonds from Costco. Despite their deliciousness, they didn't satisfy my craving for the protein pancakes from US Egg or the bespoke ones from Good Egg that I've been longing for recently. Consequently, after a positive appointment with my internist in Chandler, where I received good news about my triglyceride levels (HDL at an impressive 89!), and after undergoing my annual physical and additional blood tests, I opted to visit Good Egg. I used my customer appreciation card, which I had been saving for over a year, to get a free meal.

At the restaurant, my server Bailey was both friendly and observant. She recommended that I add dollar pancakes to my meal since I was undecided between pancakes and lunch items. Inspired by two episodes of Diners, Drive-ins, & Dives about breakfasts I watched while on the treadmill on Monday, I was also tempted by corned beef hash and Matt's famous hash browns in downtown Phoenix. I chose a full stack of pancakes for $7.50 and a side of corned beef hash for $3.95. During my meal, I noticed the dollar menu placed between the condiments. It mentioned that for an additional dollar, I could opt for "today's sweet deal." Bailey informed me that today's choices were either an apple streusel bread pudding with caramel sauce or a strawberry shortcake with homemade strawberry topping. The presence of corn syrup in the caramel simplified my decision.

For weeks, I had been desiring the blueberry-almond-wheat germ whole wheat pancakes. Guess what I ended up ordering? A stack with banana slices, candied slivered almonds, and Ghirardelli chocolate chips! Despite the mix-up, they were delightful. The toasted slivered almonds provided a unique texture compared to the whole candied almonds I keep at home, and the chocolate chips did not burn as they did when I cooked them myself. I had forgotten to coat the chips in flour, which prevents them from sinking and burning during cooking. Yesterday, I merely topped the pancakes with chips, which explained the charring. Moving on, the corned beef hash I ordered crispy was well-seasoned and nearly perfect in texture. The meal was a wonderful blend of salty and sweet flavors. The coffee was strong and freshly brewed, served with a thermos at the table for refills. To top off a splendid dining experience at Good Egg, I enjoyed a strawberry shortcake. Plus, the large cup of coffee provided for the road was a thoughtful gesture.

For those who appreciate Good Egg, consider their current promotion. If you purchase a gift card worth at least $25, you'll receive a $5 discount on your bill. This offer is valid until 12/24. [I managed to snag an even better deal, though.]

I went there for the first time yesterday, on a Thursday, and came out empty-handed. I had several inquiries about food allergies. However, the store employee seemed indifferent. It felt as though I had to coerce her into contacting someone for the information. Considering each cookie costs $2.50, and I've had better and bigger cookies for less, the lack of effort was disappointing. Especially since I was ready to buy at least two cookies. This could have led to numerous repeat visits if I liked them. Yet, she seemed reluctant to make a simple phone call. She even made a face. Interestingly, the employee at Chill Out next door also refused to contact their cookie supplier. It's a shame. They've lost a customer, as I've resolved never to return to Tammie Coe.

Date: 05/08/10

Recently, a friend and I enjoyed a superb meal here, marking my first visit since a previous Yelp event at Firesky Resort some months earlier. Opting for the outdoor seating due to the pleasant weather that afternoon, we noted that indoor dining had just commenced for the evening, though no patrons were inside yet. Feeling quite famished, we quickly ordered our drinks (only water, as we had already enjoyed wine at the bar and reception) and requested our main courses. The wild salmon, which sounded irresistible, was our unanimous choice; she paired hers with fingerling potatoes, while I opted for asparagus.

The entrees were beyond words in their beauty and taste. The salmon I selected was exceptionally moist, as evident in the photos. The experience of eating it was a journey: from the crisply seared skin seasoned just right, to the buttery soft flesh beneath, and down through the flaky layers to the succulently tender medium-rare core. Recalling the experience sends shivers of delight through me. The side dishes were just as impressive, with crisp, tender asparagus accompanied by olives, grape tomatoes, artichoke hearts, and fennel. It's definitely time to look up a gift certificate on restaurant.com for another visit soon.

It was an unexpected pleasure to discover that James Siao is now the chef de cuisine at Taggia. He kindly offered us a complimentary dessert, which was a delightful gesture. Although all the dessert options sounded tempting, the tiramisu was irresistible. Taggia's version was a visual and gustatory delight, featuring multiple layers that were both cool and creamy. The high-quality cocoa added a rich dimension to the dessert, which was flavorful yet surprisingly light on the palate and stomach. True to its name, the tiramisu was a perfect pick-me-up.

I am eager to return!

5/29/10

Rating: 4 stars!

I invited my mother to dine here for the first time. We decided to try the calamari appetizer, a favorite of hers. Alongside, I ordered the Day scallops and Forbidden rice. The calamari was presented beautifully atop a generous amount of mizuna, dressed in yuzu, and sprinkled with a mix of toasted black and white sesame seeds. It was divine! Without the scallops, we would have been content with just the calamari and more of the delicious cracked honey-wheat bread with herbed butter. The scallops, however, were also impressive. My mother initially regretted the choice due to the price, but the sight of the dishes, which were kindly split by our server at no extra charge, changed her mind. She was astonished by the size of the scallops, the largest she had ever encountered. Each was about three inches across. They might have appeared slightly undercooked in the middle, but were seared to perfection. Unfortunately, I had a severe allergic reaction to the Forbidden rice, despite its exquisite taste in a fragrant cream sauce. I recommend trying it if allergies are not a concern. Sadly, this dish might no longer be available as it isn't listed online anymore.

6/2/10

Rating: 2 stars!

Recently, I persuaded my mother to join me at Bloom for happy hour, especially after our recent positive experience with the calamari. Bloom is usually quieter during happy hour, which typically means faster service. However, today was exceptionally slow; it took a while to even get water and view the drink menu. Despite the slow service, the happy hour menu is still appealing enough to return, but next time we'll opt for seating at the bar. For drinks, my mother enjoyed a Blood orange margarita, and I had a Black and blue mojito. Although I'm allergic to oranges, my mojito was enjoyable, and my mother preferred her visually appealing margarita. As for food, my mother opted for another serving of calamari, while I was tempted by dessert. I chose the banana dessert plate, which I had loved before. Unfortunately, it didn't live up to my memories. The chocolate-dipped bananas were fewer and tasted stale, the banana muffin was dry, and the milkshake was forgettable. It felt like a disappointing downgrade from my previous visit. Perhaps it was a hint that I should have chosen a different dish, especially since this one is soon to be discontinued. Not every visit can be successful, it seems.

The tri-tip quesadilla and brisket were outstanding. The sweet biscuits paired with honey butter were irresistible. The chicken was decent. However, it's best to avoid the sweet potato side and the disappointing roasted artichoke.

Date: January 30, 2010

Rating: 2.5 stars.

I visited this quaint little cafe while my meal was being prepared at the adjacent market. The space was charming. The cookies appeared tempting. However, the moment I posed my usual inquiries, the staff became defensive. This changed the initially welcoming atmosphere. Nonetheless, the latte I selected was flavorful.

Twelve years after our initial meeting in Madrid, my cousin visited last month. I seized the chance to introduce her to Postino, a place I'd been eager to try. We chose a Tuesday for our visit, which turned out to be serendipitous. Before our outing, I had glanced at the online menu and discovered Postino's Tuesday special: a $20 wine bottle and bruschetta deal starting at 8pm. Despite the bustling noise inside, opting for the indoor seating was preferable, especially since my cousin had just praised the ideal weather in San Francisco during her previous stop before Phoenix.

Our evening was delightful. We indulged in a bottle of Heron chardonnay and a generous serving of six large bruschetta halves. The varieties included ricotta with dates and pistachios; smoked salmon with capers and herbs; roasted red peppers with goat cheese; and prosciutto with figs and mascarpone. My cousin, who prefers savory flavors, loved the red peppers and goat cheese combination. Although I frequently eat that pairing, my sweet tooth led me to favor the ricotta, dates, and pistachios most. The mascarpone and salmon were equally appealing. I'm generally not keen on prosciutto due to its saltiness, but the sweet mascarpone nicely balanced the flavors. The salmon and capers were exceptionally flavorful.

The ambiance was vibrant and positive. Our server managed to be both attentive and unobtrusive. The restroom was charmingly decorated. My sole critique concerns the dim lighting inside; I've mentioned this before and will reiterate: the visual presentation of food enhances the dining experience. More lighting would be beneficial.

My cousin has extracted a promise from me to revisit Postinoâor perhaps a similar venueâon her next trip. Such enthusiasm surely stands as a testament to Postino's appeal.

Today, I opted to test my fortune by attempting to secure some enticing cinnamon-sugar donuts (including the donut holes!) from FnB. Previously, I had always arrived too late, but today, ironically, I was too early. Pavle informed me that I needed to wait an additional 15 minutes. Consequently, I decided to visit Truckin' Good Food to order a crepe, which typically requires 12 to 15 minutes to prepare due to the crowd eager for French treats. I also planned to limit my browsing among the various stalls to save money, recalling that my last visit cost me about $44. Despite my intentions, the allure of sweets was too strong; I ended up sampling an unnamed vendor's Espresso Almond brittle and GoodyTwos' three toffee flavors: almond, dark chocolate and seasalt, and hazelnut. I enjoyed the toffees so much that I purchased two quarter-pound bags of the almond and hazelnut varieties. My spending at this point? $15. I hurried back to T'GF.

Unfortunately, the Brittany crepe was unavailable again. Jeff mentioned the loss of his buckwheat honey supplier and was unsure of their whereabouts. I noticed two honey vendors but didn't inquire about buckwheat honey. Instead, I ordered a crepe named "My First Time," which was delicious, especially with the added crunch of walnuts, which were missing in my last order. The crepe cost $5.

While waiting, I explored Moms Gone Nuts, sampling their roasted cinnamon almonds and cashews. They also offered other nuts like walnuts and pecans, some spiced with jalapenos and "smart sugar." I bought a bag of almonds and cashews for $9.

I also purchased zaatar bread and hummus for $11, noting the price increase from $5 to $6 for the bread.

My total expenditure for the morning was $40, disproving my earlier savings theory, but I was pleased to support local vendors. I cherish these moments during my favorite time of day, enjoying the outdoors, a delightful breakfast, and meeting new people.

P.S. Returning to FnB, I joined a line for the freshly-made donuts. Watching Charleen prepare Roasted Chicken Tortas was tempting, but I resisted. The brownies with pecans and figs also caught my eye, but I avoided them due to my pecan allergy. My total spending was $45.

Note: Buying too many donuts might not be wise unless shared immediately. They began to harden within hours, possibly due to being covered at the stall.

Awarded three stars due to the excellent happy hour food deals: Taylor Street pasta, Prince Edward mussels, and aqua clams. Create your own hand-tossed, hearth stone pizza or try the bistec del Furio. All are exceptionally delicious! I have not dined here during dinner hours because the service tends to be sluggish. Expensive menus are acceptable to me, provided that the service is informed, attentive, and efficient.

Rated 4.5 stars!

Gratitude to Yelp for its random selection of a friend who received free tickets. This allowed me to finally experience "Fiddler on the Roof," a show I've longed to see for years! Despite our distant seating at the back, our view of the stage was unobstructed, and the sound quality tonight was exceptional. Interestingly, the line for the bathroom was significantly longer before the show than after.

I thoroughly enjoyed "Fiddler on the Roof." John Preece's portrayal of Tevye, the village milkman, was both humorous and captivating. The entire cast also delivered outstanding performances. The Russian dancers were particularly delightful, marking a highlight of the performance. It's advisable not to miss the wedding scene for a restroom break; the Russian dance performance there was nearly enough to earn a standing ovation from me! As an aficionado of musicals, it was a delightful surprise to learn that the song "If I Were a Rich Man" from this musical inspired the 1993 hit "Rich Girl" by Louchie Lou and Michie One, later covered by Gwen Stefani in 2004. "Sunrise, Sunset" was another tune I recognized instantly. The sets and costumes were impressive. I highly recommend catching this production!

I stopped by to spend the remainder of my CSM gift card before the market shuts down this coming Saturday at 5 PM. All items, except those from the deli and freshly made, were discounted by 25%. The store appeared nearly depletedâonly a third to half of the shelves were filled. The deli and pastry displays were almost empty. The produce section was nearly bare, though a few bottles of AZ wine remained. Had I not switched to exclusively drinking organic and sustainable wines recently, I might have bought some.

For a meal, I chose some pasta, quinoa, and sweet potato salads, which I found quite delightful. The quinoa salad's lemon-herb vinaigrette was particularly appealing. The pasta had a perfect texture and wasn't overly oily. The sweet potatoes were excellent, neither too mushy nor overly sweet. To maximize the use of my gift card, I ordered two sandwiches. I sampled a few bites of each and packed the rest for later. The bacon in the Smoke Shop sandwich was notably lean and tasty. The aioli was also a highlight. The multi-grain bread was wonderfully crunchy. The "Friggin' chicken" sandwich impressed me too; it was quite spicy from the jalapenos, but the mango chutney and cheese balanced it well. I really enjoyed the bun. However, I found the a la carte prices somewhat high, though the local and sometimes organic sourcing is a consolation.

While the grocery and wine bar are closing, the Wednesday night and Saturday morning markets will continue. The atmosphere tonight felt somewhat melancholic, possibly influenced by a recent thunderstorm that might have deterred the usual crowd.

Added 5/11/12:

Having enjoyed goats' milk ice cream and cheese before, I ventured to buy two products from Black Mesa Ranch in Snowflake, AZ: Goats Milk Caramel Fudge Sauce and Goats Milk Caramel Sauce, each priced at $9.50 before a 25% discount. I plan to use these as dips and toppings for ice cream, among other uses. This morning, I'm enjoying the caramel sauce with a banana. My breakfast includes whole wheat pan de sal, a slice of Breadsmith's sesame seed-encrusted rustic Italian bread, an organic banana, Maranatha organic crunchy roasted almond butter, and organic coffee. The caramel sauce is exceptionally delicious, with a rich flavor and silky texture, while the goats' milk adds a subtle background note. Unless you dislike goats' milk, this caramel is likely to please both newcomers and aficionados alike. I haven't tried the caramel fudge sauce yet, but I'll update this review once I do.

I have visited the dining establishments at Arizona Grand several times, with some no longer in existence, such as Latitude 30 and The Phantom Horse Grill. The Lobby Grill resembles TPHG in terms of decor but is situated differently. I would have tried it sooner had I been able to locate itâsimply follow the signage until it feels like you've gone too far; that's when you're close. Finding a parking spot might seem daunting, yet it's actually just a short stroll away, just past the "hill."

Initially, there was some confusion since it appeared that the main dining area was shut, and only bar seating was available. Fortunately, the host allowed us to use a booth, which was much more comfortable than the chilly, dim bar area, contrasting with the cozy, bright main dining space. The service was somewhat slow, even though there was just a small family there before us, and I had already decided on my meal from their online menuâI was eager to try it! (I look forward to the day I can order online and have my meal ready upon seating.)

We opted for the Filet bleu cheese pizza and the Reinvented Waldorf salad. Our meal took around 35-40 minutes to be served, so having a book or some form of entertainment is advisable if you're eating solo or if your companions aren't keen on chatting. Luckily, there is a gift shop just across the corridor. The shop is quite decent for a resort, offering items like Brighton jewelry, though it lacks the newest pieces found in malls. However, discussing jewelry isn't my focus here.

I noted the prices of our dishes; they were somewhat pricey. Yet, when my Mom is happy to ignore the cost for another piece of that delicious pizza, with its soft filet and sharp bleu cheese (we left only a tiny piece, which I enjoyed later that night!), and the excellent salad with its irresistible candied walnuts, it's clear this place is a hit.

We plan to return very soon!

11/04/12

There's a massive Asian festival happening!

I took my aunt to see the "Fire & Sand: Contemporary American Glass" exhibit today. To our surprise, we stumbled upon an Asian festival. It seems these events, featuring jewelry and crafts, are quite common in this area. My aunt was thrilled; shopping and bargaining are her favorite activities, especially since they're typical in Manila and other Asian cities. She felt right at home! I was less enthused and decided to take a walk while she browsed the stalls. During my walk, I discovered some food trucks, including the "Hey Joe" food truck, though we had just had a large breakfast, so I passed on that. I did come across a Maui Shave Ice truck, but I'll save that for another review.

Afterward, we did visit the glass exhibit, which was definitely worth the trip from North Scottsdale to Mesa! I took some photos, which I've uploaded, despite them being technically not allowed. I'm looking forward to coming back soon to experience some live performances.

Disappointing happy hour sushi selection!

Visited this establishment on the 20th following a lengthy hiatus (over a year, perhaps?). The familiar faces of chefs Julio and Roberto, along with manager Leo, were still present. I reminded them of my dietary restrictions and ordered: spicy tuna ($4.50), spicy salmon ($4.50), and a soft-shelled crab roll ($7.95). Julio was responsible for the first two dishes, while Roberto handled the crab roll. Luckily, I inquired about Roberto's alternative ingredients. He proposed using radishes and yamagobo (pickled burdock, resembling shredded carrots). Without my intervention, the crab roll might have been as underwhelming as the other two. The tuna and salmon rolls were predominantly rice with scant fish paste. I managed only a few bites from each before abandoning the effort. Despite my hunger, I had the leftovers boxed and later discussed the matter with Leo, who graciously comped one of the dishes. This seemed fair, given that I had consumed about one dish's worth. In future visits during happy hour, I plan to limit myself to the reliable soft-shelled crab roll, which is encased in nori, then rice, and topped with a thin omelet slice. Delicious!

Unsatisfied with the other two rolls, I switched them for a rainbow roll ($8.95), which typically includes salmon, yellowtail, tuna, shrimp, along with avocado and cucumber. Although it lacked some ingredients, it was still flavorful, more vibrant, and offered a better texture than the mushy salmon and tuna rolls.

I doubt I'll revisit for happy hour soon, especially now that I've discovered a new spot, Tempe's Sushi 101, for better happy hour sushi options.

On the date 8/25, the happy hour featured a white wine cooler priced at $4 and a prosciutto platter for either $7 or $8, both selected from the HH menu. The wine cooler, served ice-cold and prepared on the spot, was consumed quickly and was notably refreshing. The prosciutto platter was satisfactory; the cheese was enjoyable, prompting me to consider trying more cheese antipasti later. However, the peppers were not to my liking due to my sensitivity. The breadsticks were a highlight, though I wished for more.

On 12/16, I opted for the Pub Burger, which was exceptional. It included havarti cheese, thick bacon slices, mayo, and BBQ sauce (requested on the side), all within a sesame-seeded pretzel bun. The experience was reminiscent of a famous scene from "When Harry Met Sally." Unfortunately, the fries were a letdown. My server promptly replaced them with a new batch, but these too were disappointingly soggy.

I had hoped to maintain a four-star rating for this venue, but during my last visit, the noise level forced me to use earbuds from my purse to focus on my reading. Although I enjoyed the music, the volume was excessive. My server agreed to lower it, which only happened midway through my meal. I had intended to order a cocktail, but ironically, my server couldn't hear my request. Ultimately, it didn't matter as I had finished nearly all of my burger, savored the crispy bacon, and most of the bun. I left satisfied with my meal and proceeded to Camelview for a movie, "Black Swan," which I found quite provocative and recommend watching.

The design of the space is appealing, with spacious seating areas. It's brightly lit and maintained cleanly. The only issue was the strong smell of urine in the ladies' restroom. I took my mother to watch two 3D films here yesterday evening, "How to Train Your Dragon" and "Alice in Wonderland." Both films were outstanding, providing a lot of entertainment and it was fun to match the actors with their character's voices.

Why hasn't the technology for playing 3D movies been perfected yet? We attempted to watch "Clash of the Titans," but after spending 20 minutes trying to correct a malfunction (the 3D previews weren't even watchable), the staff opted to stop the show and issued everyone passes. This was fortunate, as several audience members were insisting on complimentary hotdogs. Free hotdogs? Really? Hotdogs are inexpensive, costing around $5. It's best to remain calm and patient; the management typically resolves such issues by offering a free pass for any film, including 3D ones which cost $13.75 here at Westgate. I've experienced similar issues at AZ Mills Harkins 3D IMAX where the film also failed to start properly, and I received complimentary passes there as well. (Hotdogs, seriously? It's akin to using an $8 drink voucher to purchase a beer or a glass of wine priced under $5.)

By the way, the 3D experience at AMC, especially at Westgate, surpasses that at Harkins. Perhaps this is because the films I watched last night were more enjoyable, whereas the movie I saw at Harkins ("Avatar 3D" in Dolby 3D) was disappointing compared to the 3D IMAX version at AZ Mills. More investigation is needed.

Two weeks ago, I visited a cafe for a ham and cheese croissant and felt significantly overcharged. Initially, I had intended to satisfy my craving for a hazelnut royale but was deterred by its high cost of $6 each. After some persuasion, the male proprietor convinced me to try the croissant instead. He warmed it in the microwave before charging me $8 plus tax. This price seemed excessive, particularly for a croissant nearing a day old. I had hoped for a crispier texture, yet microwaving left the bottom soggy, with only the top layers achieving slight crispness. Upon examining the take-out menu, I discovered the croissant was not listed under dinner options. It appeared instead under breakfast items, priced at $5.95 with white sauce and $6.55 with scrambled eggs. Consequently, I was upset to have paid $8 for a basic, leftover breakfast croissant.

Disheartened by my meal choice that evening and frustrated by the escalating prices, I resolved not to return anytime soon, or possibly ever.

10/21/12

I placed a takeout order for my go-to choice, a large Popeye pizza. Unfortunately, the pizza I received tonight was a disappointing version, the poorest quality I've experienced in recent times and certainly the worst from Redendo's over the past two years. (Interestingly, I realized only today, after reviewing my past comments, that this visit coincides with the two-year anniversary of my first meal here!) After finishing work, I called Redendo's to order and was told it would take 20 minutes. I stopped at a drugstore nearby to return some items. When I reached the restaurant, about thirty minutes had passed since my call. A familiar young employee, previously mistaken in taking orders, handed me the pizza, claiming he made it himself. This was surprising as I knew him only from his duties at the register, answering calls, or fetching orders. Normally, the staff shows me the pizza before I pay, but he simply opened the box. I observed the toppings of spinach and ricotta, commented positively, and hoped it tasted as good as it appeared.

Upon reaching home, I opened the box and immediately realized the pizza was below standard. Recently, I began requesting less mozzarella and more ricotta. Tonight, I forgot to specify, but was pleased to see ample ricotta. Yet, both mozzarella and goat cheese were missing! The pizza did have an excessive amount of garlic, as seen in the photo. Garlic covered the pizza and had fallen off the slices I reheated. Despite its health benefits, and my recent recovery from a respiratory infection, the overpowering garlic was too much, and its impact worsened the next day. The pizza was bland and unenjoyable. Notably, I experienced headaches after eating it on both occasions, a new and unpleasant reaction for me. I speculated whether the new employee had altered the recipe or why he took the initiative to bake it instead of the usual chef. If a quality pizza couldn't be made, why wasn't I informed during my order? I could have chosen a different dish and spent my $25 elsewhere, avoiding this unsatisfactory experience.

Regrettably, I must now reconsider my future patronage at Redendo's due to the inconsistent quality and presentation of their dishes, despite the enjoyable meals shared there with my family in the past. I appreciate the good times and great pizzas we had, but moving forward, I cannot trust what might be served.

UPDATE:
I revised my rating from 5 stars to 4 after remembering my dislike for their calamari. My mother and I, avid calamari enthusiasts, consistently search for it on menus during our dining outings. We prefer calamari with a light, crunchy coating, whether it's made from panko, flour, or standard breadcrumbs. Typically, I enjoy them with a simple dash of lemon juice. We have tried Rigatony's calamari twice, forgetting our initial experience; the dish tends to be overly breaded and doughy.

---
This local Italian restaurant, with locations in Mesa and Chandler, offers $6.95 express lunch specials from Monday to Friday, featuring daily variations (I adore their baked stuffed shells and chicken cutlet piccata!). Additionally, an early bird special is available from 4 p.m. to 5 p.m., included in the "Pasta-bilities" lunch menu, where diners can select their pasta, sauce, and toppings (with plenty of vegetarian choices), accompanied by an excellent antipasto salad (comparable to Olive Garden's) and ciabatta bread. I appreciate the availability of whole wheat spaghetti.

My top picks include the cannelloni, jumbo stuffed shells, chicken piccata, and both the alfredo and marinara sauces. Don't miss the apple bread pudding topped with an exquisite Frangelico caramel sauce!

5/27/10

Upon reading several reviews about Hillside Spot, I was intrigued enough to visit. I observed that even at around 10:30-10:45 AM on a Thursday, the queue was lengthy. The noise level inside was unexpectedly high. Despite the heat and bright sunshine outside, I opted to sit outdoors due to the indoor noise. Unfortunately, the only tables available outside had no umbrellas. [This place would earn 4 or more stars if it weren't so noisy!] However, don't worry. A helpful staff member agreed to set up an umbrella-covered table upon request.

Before visiting, I had browsed the menu online and had some dishes in mind. The bustling crowd and loud atmosphere on my initial visit made it difficult to explore the display cases filled with various pastries like cupcakes, apple pie slices, cookies, tarts, muffins, and scones, which change daily. Make sure to check them out! (The apple pie is particularly delicious!) Although the daily special was tempting, I chose the Croque Madame and Pancakes with Apple Compote. Orders are placed and paid for at the counter, where you also pick up a marker for your table. Remember, food preparation takes time.

The Croque Madame was exceptional, despite some burnt parts. The French bread, likely from MJ Bread, was excellent, topped with a creamy bechamel sauce, sliced ham, melted gruyere cheese, and a fried egg. I would definitely reorder this dish.

The pancakes were tasty, thanks to the batter. However, the "apple compote" was not as expected. I am accustomed to thicker, sweeter fruit reductions, so Hillside Spot's version, which was less sweet and stewed, was a bit of a letdown. Luckily, I had brought my own maple syrup to enhance the flavor.

7/24/10

My second visit to HS occurred in early June, where I sampled the berry pancakes with homemade whipped cream. They were excellent, and I nearly finished them all. If I hadn't sampled the apple pie, I would have certainly completed the dish. The addition of perfectly ripe bananas made it even more spectacular.

The exterior of the building is attractive, with stunning views overlooking a nearby artificial lake. I found pleasure in strolling through the park where this library is situated. However, using the library facilities presented a different experience. During my visits, it was often either shut or overrun with loud children and teenagers who moved in and out without supervision, alongside adults loudly conversing on their phones. The area designated for computers was perpetually packed, leaving no available seats or clear tables, as they were often cluttered with belongings from absent owners. In essence, the library resembled a bustling cafÃ©, complete with a section for purchasing coffee and pastries, rather than a serene space conducive to focused work.

The library offers a decent array of CDs, DVDs, and books-on-DVD. I utilized this service a few times, appreciating the ability to reserve items both in person and online, with prompt notifications for pickup. However, I ceased using these services due to hygiene concerns. The items reeked of body odor, presumably because previous users might have carried them under their arms, a common practice, especially in our desert climate where sweating is inevitable. Despite thorough cleaning with sanitizing wipes and multiple hand washings, the smell lingered, which was quite off-putting. If you doubt this, test it by smelling a DVD or book during your next visit. Consider yourself forewarned.

Visit for the refreshing walks and scenic views by the lakes. The park also features playgrounds for children and numerous picnic spots equipped with grills and tables. Fishing is an option too, though consuming the catch is not advisable due to water contamination with toxins and algae, as indicated by posted signs. If exploring all the trails, it's wise to have company, especially near dusk. There's a particular spot with only one way in and out, posing potential risks if someone with bad intentions is trailing you.

I hope your visits to this library prove more enjoyable than mine.

The setting is visually and tactilely stunning, that's certain, yet the cost for such uniqueness is steep. I appreciated the time spent in the lobbyâsince seating at the sushi counter wasn't available until 5:30 p.m.âbut it was disappointing to see that the cleaning staff had overlooked the food scraps on the coffee table near the sushi host desk. Even more so when a representative approached to highlight a bar menu on the table and inquired if I desired anything from the bar, surely she must have seen the clutter.

I opted for a $9.50 spider roll (soft-shelled crab), a $10 vegetable tempura appetizer, and a $19 baked lobster roll, all offered at half price for the restaurant's first anniversary week. While the dishes were enjoyable, and the lavish decor added to the experience, I would only willingly pay $9.50 for the crab roll again. The other items, not so much, even at a discount. A $19 five-piece lobster roll should deliver an experience akin to iconic movie restaurant scenes from "The Ugly Truth" or "When Harry Met Sally"âyour choice.

For those with deep pockets or not footing the bill themselves, this place is a prime sushi destination in the vicinity of Old Town Scottsdale.

Lovely storefront design! The abundance of green plants, including lush trees and vibrant flowers, made it feel as though I was in a tropical paradise. This brief moment brought a delightful sensation, almost like receiving a precious gift. :)

Currently, the usual merchandise isn't on display because the shop has showcased their Easter collection. There's an array of charming items, such as pastel and foil-wrapped hollow chocolate bunnies in both milk and dark varieties, mini-eggs, large eggs (some hollow, others filled), jelly beans, pastel truffles, and ornately decorated eggs. I was disappointed to find that the mini-chocolate bunnies ($1.15) didn't come in dark chocolate. However, I was informed they were available in medium and large sizes ($5.65 and $9.70, respectively).

My visit was intended for purchasing 13 candy bars in both milk and dark chocolate. I ended up buying those along with three mini-chocolate milk bunnies. [Shh!! The dark chocolate bars with almonds are just for me!] :D

Note: See's is known for offering free samples to customers. What might be less known is that clerks have two or three types of truffles to offer, so your sample might differ from the previous customer's. Today, I received a dark chocolate bordeaux with brown sugar buttercream as my complimentary treat. I haven't tried it yet. I often wonder if See's will replace the corn syrup in some of their products with pure cane sugar. Hopefully, that change happens soon...

After noticing a $28 Dior Addict lipstick (Stiletto, a term that evokes both allure and danger, reminiscent of Fonda's role in Single White Female) at Sephora, I was intrigued enough to visit a couple of department store cosmetics sections. I was curious if they had any "gift with purchase" deals. (It turns out such promotions wouldn't start until September.) My journey began and ended at Macy's due to limited time, the service I received, and a lower price offered by the Macy's Dior representative for the lipsticks I was interested in buyingâspecifically, at least two shades, Stiletto and Envy. I also explored the $30 Rouge Dior and $34 Serum Rouge options. Preferring not to return used lipsticks, I tested several shades using the disposable brushes provided for customers. Soon, a woman positioned herself persistently to my right and slightly behind, within my line of sight. Despite my friendly greeting and continued browsing, her presence made me so uneasy that I opted to purchase only the two lipsticks I originally considered, knowing I could return if I liked the products.

The original salesperson processed my purchase, and the total exceeded my expectations. Upon inquiry, she admitted to mistakenly quoting the price of a different item earlier. The difference was minor, so I chose not to dispute it and left the store.

A few days later, I revisited Sephora to replenish my supply of Clinique products, which I prefer to buy in multiples to replace those compromised by Arizona's heat. I lack the patience and time to salvage broken pieces for later use with a brush. On this occasion, I purchased five shades for approximately $77, including tax (three for personal use and two as gifts for my mother).

Macy's could have gained more from my visit if not for the unsettling experience of being monitored by a security guard, making me feel like a suspect. This overshadowed any miscommunication about pricing by the sales representative. I've decided to avoid this Macy's location in the future. Should I choose to shop at Macy's again, I might visit the Chandler store or one in another state. Alternatively, I might just spend my money at Dillard's or return to Sephora.

Thank you to Pomegranate Cafe, Russell, and the entire team for making me momentarily forget my illness. Despite my casual attire of yoga pants, a Life is Good t-shirt, a zip-up hoodie, and glasses, I was in high spirits anticipating my meal. The cafe was unexpectedly crowded, with a queue even forming to order! With most indoor seating occupied and the noise level high, I opted to dine outside to avoid drawing attention to my unwell appearance. Before settling down, I had to place my order.

Having checked the menu online beforehand, I planned to order the French toast without powdered sugar, as usual. However, I was tempted by the basic breakfast but ended up choosing the Kamut toast with almond butter, jam, and fruit. I considered ordering a smoothie or an elixir, priced at $8 each, but the only elixir available was aimed at female hormonal balance, which I didn't need. I decided against the smoothie as well when I noticed it contained grape seed oil extract, saving myself $8. I finished my order with a Cartel Coffee cappuccino and a cucumber-free glass of water. I reiterated my request for no powdered sugar on the French toast, which would take 20 to 25 minutes due to a delay in the kitchen. I paid for my items and was informed that everything would be ready in about 30 minutes, which was longer than expected, but I was too weary to complain and focused instead on securing a table.

I found a suitable table outside, which needed cleaning. A shy, charming staff member assisted me. I appreciate the humble and friendly nature of the staff at vegan, vegetarian, and gluten-free places, which often feature a hippy-chic, colorful, and eclectic decor. Indoors was vibrant, but I chose a mosaic-topped table with mismatched chairs outside, carefully selecting a clean seat.

The wait for my food was shorter than anticipated. My cappuccino and water arrived quickly, the latter served in a canning jar without a lid. Shortly after, the French toast was served with powdered sugar by mistake, but Russell promptly corrected the order. The Kamut toast, almond butter, jam, and fruit remained on the table, which I enjoyed despite the raw almond butter not being to my taste. The dish was enhanced by the unexpected addition of chia, sesame, and sunflower seeds, which added flavor and texture. The corrected French toast arrived soon after, perfectly crispy on the outside with a soft, delightful interior, and beautifully complemented by strawberry-rhubarb jam and agave syrup. It was a thoroughly enjoyable meal.

I will definitely return!

Originally, I intended to enjoy the happy hour at Fleming's due to a gift card I had, but the crowded bar and outdoor heat deterred me. Instead, I opted for Roy's, aware of their limited happy hour offerings like complimentary edamame. Settling for the Waimanolo salad, I was pleasantly surprised to find Roy's had expanded their menu. Now, they offered four dishes including ahi tuna and Wagyu sliders, along with select wines and all signature cocktails at just $5 each during happy hour. Previously, I found the beef skewers underwhelming and opted against the calamari despite its appeal. My focus was on the Wagyu sliders with caramelized onions and sweet potato fries, which seemed tailor-made for me. I initially chose a chardonnay but switched to another signature cocktail upon remembering my past experiences with their espresso and lemon martinis. The highlight was discovering the Hawaiian-style sidecar, enhancing my happy hour excitement.

The Fred and Ginger cocktail, a blend of Hennessy VS cognac and Domaine du Canton ginger liqueur with a candied ginger garnish, was both stunning and delightful. Regrettably, I couldn't finish it as I needed to save space for the sliders, fries, and an unplanned dessert. The sliders, reminiscent of upscale Whoppers, were served with herb-seasoned sweet potato fries with occasional cheese drizzles in a mini-Chinese takeout box. Both the cocktail and appetizer were exceptional values at $5 each.

I was tempted to keep Roy's happy hour my little secret.

Reflecting on the experience, the cocktail and appetizer alone would have sufficed, but I lingered to sample the Chocolate souffle, priced at $9.95. This dessert, a unique take on chocolate lava cake accompanied by homemade vanilla bean ice cream and raspberry coulis, required a 20-minute preparation time. The edges of the cake resembled a chewy, fresh-baked brownie, while the center oozed like molten brownie batter. However, the vanilla ice cream disappointed in both texture and flavor, making the dessert seem overpriced compared to the earlier delights.

I eagerly anticipate my next visit to Roy's happy hour with friends.

At Talking Stick Resort, the Coffee Garden serves Peet's Coffee along with a variety of frozen and blended beverages. They also offer pastries made in the resort's own kitchens. I chose a medium iced latte, priced at $3.70 plus tax. It was served without sweetener, though options to add sugar or select from Peet's Coffee syrups like Caramel or White Chocolate Mocha were available. Additionally, I picked a brown sugar and cinnamon scone for $3.75 plus tax. Both items were exceptionally tasty. The scone was ideally sweet and moist, presented on a stylish yet disposable black square dessert plate. The coffee was delivered in an attractively designed plastic cup, echoing the blue motif of the casino floor, complete with a matching blue straw. As the cafÃ© had just opened a few hours earlier, they lacked to-go boxes for the sizable scone. Fortunately, a Peet's representative offered a plastic bag originally used for the plate, and even allowed me to keep the plate. This experience not only provided a satisfying coffee and scone but also left me with a charming, reusable keepsake.

The store was neat, well-lit, and orderly. The attendant at the register was attractive, composed, well-dressed, amiable, cheerful, and articulate. It's conveniently located inside the shopping center. I'm a fan!

The ongoing promotions include "Buy three, get two free; Buy two, get one free; and Buy one, get the second at half price." I managed to pick up my mother's preferred body butter fragrance and found a gift set that included a matching shower gel and a bath glycerin soap, all for $20. Unfortunately, I discovered too late that there is also a larger size of the bath gel, originally priced at $15. With the promotion, I could have bought two body butters for $36 (each costing $18) and gotten the larger bath gel at no cost. Nonetheless, the bath soap will be perfect for my mother's upcoming travels, as it's less likely to leak, so it all turned out well in the end. :)

My cousin and I visited this spot to indulge in desserts prior to attending the First Friday Artwalk tonight. The rosemary shortbread was absolutely delightful; I regret not purchasing more than a single piece. Additionally, the brownie chunk cookie was a hit with us. 

I plan to return here during my next visit to the artwalk!

In March, my mother and I noticed an advertisement for a Filipino restaurant in the local plaza. We had just finished eating pho, so our visit to the restaurant had to wait until our next shopping trip. Upon our return, we were greeted by the exceptionally welcoming owners, whom we hoped would achieve great success.

As it was nearing the end of the day, the buffet offerings were limited and unappealing. We opted instead for the pork skewers and liempo (pork belly), which the owners, a husband and wife team, took great pride in. These dishes were served with a side of rice and achara (pickled papaya and carrots). Additionally, I ordered a saba at langka, which consists of bananas and jackfruit in a lumpia wrapper, deep-fried.

The food preparation took longer than anticipated, but the delay was manageable as my mother was busy with grocery shopping. The wait proved worthwhile. The pork skewers were reminiscent of my childhood in the Philippines, where street food was a staple. Such memories include BBQ, various street snacks, and "dirty" ice cream, commonly found around Metro Manila and educational institutions. The nostalgia was so strong, it made me reconsider my dinner plans, favoring a return to Mekong Plaza over other cuisines. The liempo, however, was less impressive. I thought we should have ordered more BBQ skewers instead, as they were more flavorful. Although my mother liked the liempo, she agreed that the BBQ was the highlight. The owners certainly had a reason to be proud of it.

Regarding dessert, it was disappointing. The presentation was unappealing, and the sweetness was lacking. The turon was served with a caramel sauce, which I finished only because it enhanced the dessert's flavor. My mother predicted my disappointment and suggested that homemade would have been better, a sentiment I shared.

Nevertheless, the pork BBQ is highly recommended. Do try it if you have the chance!

On July 28, 2012, I joined some friends who had begun their evening with drinks at happy hour, which started at 5:30 PM, and had already eaten by the time I got there at 8:40 PM. Luckily, I found an excellent parking spot right in front of the entrance. Upon entering, the overwhelming noise and the smell of stale beer immediately made me uncomfortable. Despite this, I had informed my friends of my arrival through a text and a Yelp check-in, so I stayed. I located my friends at a table for four, sat with them, and had to raise my voice just to say helloâa definite annoyance. I find it extremely frustrating to shout just to talk to someone right next to me, and even more so, having to lean in close to hear them. I longed to be at the quieter Four Peaks, enjoying a Peach ale.

I remained at the table for about twenty minutes, during which time several servers walked by without offering any assistance. I was relieved I had brought my own water, as the loud environment was giving me a headache and I was both hungry and thirsty. After about 30 minutes, while standing near some stairs with two friends, a server finally approached us to see if we needed help. By then, I had decided to leave and was already bidding farewell to my friends.

It's unfortunate that I missed out on trying the beer samplers, priced at $1 or $2 for 3 ounces, depending on the type. It would have been enjoyable to sample various beers and gauge the servers' knowledge, especially since I'm new to beer and know I prefer less hoppy varieties.

Beer prices were disappointing: $5 for a pint and $9 for a pitcher, not even during happy hour. A pint from the local Four Peaks brewery was also $5. I had hoped to see a variety of beers from O.H.S.O. brewery but found only two options. Ultimately, none of this mattered as I received no service at all.

Nearly a year has passed since our last visit to Byblos. The lamb shanks, deliciously served over nut-studded brown rice, are a highlight. Convincing my Mom to join me here is never a challenge. We both adore the tomato bisque, described as "to die for," though I haven't enjoyed it in two years due to food allergies. The hummus consistently impresses us, especially when accompanied by tomato wedges and a few cornichon pickles. Warm, toasted pitas are our usual request. Recent reviews have led me to question whether the management has opted for cheaper ingredients.

The chicken kabobs also offer a delightful taste. However, the lamb shank dinners are a must-try. I generally pass on the desserts.

I have a couple of grievances. The overpowering smell of sanitizer is noticeable and consistent during our visits, which have numbered four or five. It significantly detracts from the experience. Additionally, the service from an older gentleman is often unfriendly. Initially, I attributed this to cultural differences, but I now believe he simply dislikes his job.

The restaurant's decor, particularly around the counter area, could benefit from a redesign. As of last year, the entrance hallway resembled an office in a run-down building rather than a welcoming space for waiting customers and displaying desserts. On a positive note, the women's restroom has always been clean during my visits.

I've dined here several times previously. On my initial visit, which was less than two years ago, I opted for the chicken shawarma plate, complete with pickled vegetables, hummus, garlic sauce, and pita bread. Unfortunately, many pieces of the chicken were undercooked to the point of being inedible, with some even appearing blood-red. When I voiced my concerns to the waiter, he seemed genuinely surprised, as if complaints were unheard of at this establishment. He returned shortly with who I assumed was the chef, who appeared even more insulted by my critique regarding the undercooked chicken. He insisted that their cooking times were meticulously managed, yet he agreed to prepare a new plate for me. After twelve minutes, a new, slightly better-cooked chicken dish was served. I resolved to make the best of the situation and attributed it to an off day, finding solace in the pickled vegetables and the exceptional garlic sauce.

Days later, I returned with my mother and we decided to try the lamb kabob plate. She was not particularly impressed, having had superior lamb shanks at Byblos. It became clear that the hummus was lacking. Nonetheless, the garlic sauce continued to impress, pairing wonderfully with the tabouli.

Months later, just two days ago, I opted for take-out for both of us: a chicken shawarma sandwich without pickles for myself, and two variations of gyro for my mother. It had taken me a while to try these sandwiches, but they were well worth it. The shawarma is a favorite here for good reason, and the combination of sauce and garlic is sublime. Even a simple pita with just lamb and lettuce proved delicious due to the quality of the meat, which required no additional condiments.

Additionally, you have the option to choose whole wheat pita over the standard type. Haji-Baba pitas, made nearby, are available at the counter.

For those picking up take-out, payment can be made upfront or after browsing the grocery aisles. Chocolate lovers should try the Swiss chocolate bars available here, particularly the Milka brand, which offers a variety of flavors. Despite other brands using lesser ingredients, Milka uses quality components, making it a superior choice for just under two dollars a bar.

While shopping, it's easy to get distracted by the grocery offerings, but the enticing aromas of food will likely keep your focus on the main reason for your visit.

I dined here several months back. The excitement was palpable as I discovered a sushi spot in Phoenix that even offered brown rice as an alternative for sushi mealsâthough I might be mixing it up with a different place.

One dish stood out: the free appetizer. It included tempura chips, possibly topped with a squid salad. I regret not ordering more of that dish alone. Instead, I opted for an Ao Yasai (a dish of mixed gourmet greens with ginger) and a sushi roll with brown rice. The latter seemed overpriced for the small size served. The flavors were so bland that I can't even remember the type of roll I had. Quite disappointing, really.

I had resolved not to return. Yet, I'm considering giving Hana another chance, maybe for a meal with friends at lunch or dinner, focusing on appetizers and perhaps some wine or sake.

On my initial and thus far only trip to Fleming's, I rated it at 2.5 stars.

Upon entering, I immediately noticed the excessive darkness, which I personally dislike. Additionally, the staff seemed stressed or detached, lacking any welcoming smiles. It was only 4:15 pm, shortly after opening, with few patrons present yet. About eight individuals were at the bar. I was quickly introduced to my server, whose indifferent demeanor suggested that dining here might have been a mistake.

I opted to try the Prime Burger priced at $6 and requested to taste a few red wines before selecting one. At other establishments, sampling wines is usually an easy request, often proactively offered. Unfortunately, this was not the case at this Fleming's, where my question seemed to worsen my server's mood, though I did manage to sample two small pours before making my choice.

As I awaited my burger, I powered up my laptop, grateful I had brought it along due to the lengthy wait. The bar became busier, and the servers appeared increasingly frazzled, making me curious about the cause of their distress. My burger arrived in just under 20 minutes, featuring a large patty with cheese, a layer of thick, peppered smoked bacon, and vegetables on a pretzel bun, crowned with a large onion ring. While the burger itself was tasty and well-cooked to my medium preference, the bacon was overly salty, prompting me to remove it. This was disappointing given the generous serving of bacon.

Despite the issues, I would consider another Prime burger, without the bacon, during happy hour at a different location.

While enjoying my meal, I realized the reason behind the staff's apparent stress: many patrons in the bar had ordered the burger, just like a nearby table of six. At $6, the burger is quite affordable, which might not translate into substantial tips for the staff. This could be a factor if the servers maintain their unenthusiastic attitude.

My mother and I opted to explore this boutique while a relative and her daughter, who is nearly 18 and visiting from New Jersey, went to Forever 21, a store where I've never been tempted to buy anything. We discovered that Love Culture offers quite a selection of adorable apparel. The prices were reasonable; I managed to pick up four stylish tops suitable for spring and summer, priced between $13 and $22, which I could wear to work under a suit.

The store was well-lit, vibrant, and had spacious aisles. The employees appeared amiable. However, I'm not keen on their return policy. It was only during checkout that I was informed of the 22-day return period, with no mention of the policy on sale items, shoes, and accessories being non-returnable. I learned of this the hard way when I tried to return a handbag the following day and was informed that it was ineligible for return according to the policy stated on the receipt's back. Despite searching the area around where the handbags and shoes were displayed, I found no signage indicating that these items were final sale, not even at the checkout counter.
