Despite these issues, I would consider returning to see what other attractive outfits I might come across. However, I would be much more cautious about buying their shoes, accessories, and discounted merchandise.

I'm grateful to about.com for introducing me to a hidden gem known as Enchanted Island. My sister, along with her two children, aged 8 and 6, visited Arizona for the first time last August. Before their visit, I researched kid-friendly locations on about.com, and Enchanted Island was highly recommended.

The children were thrilled with the various rides available. Unfortunately, my niece was too tall for the bumper boats, which was the only disappointment. Despite this, my nephew had a great time. Fortunately, there were plenty of other attractions suitable for my older niece, quickly drying her tears. Although the rides mainly catered to younger children, both my niece and nephew had a blast and reminisced about their fun days there for some time. My sister and I were delighted to see them so happy. We appreciated that the amusement park was situated within a beautiful, real park. Initially, I was concerned due to some negative online reviews about the park's condition, but it was much nicer than expected.

I want to express my thanks again to about.com for pointing out this delightful spot. None of my colleagues or friends were aware of its existence. I hope others can also discover and enjoy it with their families.

10/27/10

If it hadn't taken 20 minutes to receive two sandwiches, I would have rated this meal with four stars. Reflecting on the photos and the delicious taste of the sandwiches makes me want to go back. However, the lengthy wait and the unpleasant attitudes from the cook who took my order, and another person who seemed to be in charge, make me reluctant to return. :( The sandwiches were enjoyable, particularly the cheesesteak, although it became apparent halfway through that it was slightly too salty. The marinara sauce on the parmigiana provided a nice balance to the cheesesteak's richness and creaminess, prompting me to continue indulging in the eggplant. I enjoyed the robust wheat roll, yet the soft white roll under the parmigiana was less appealing.
Endured a six-hour wait for Nikki Sixx's book signing due to poor management, wishing they had informed us about the delay.

I dislike this location due to its parking garages that charge fees. Since I'm already spending at the shops and restaurants, paying extra for parking seems illogical and deters customers. I prefer visiting places like Desert Ridge or Tempe Marketplace instead.

This is authentic Mexican cuisine. As soon as you enter, you're transported to Mexico. The establishment isn't fancy, typical of many places in Mexico, right? It's so authentic that the staff member initially taking my order had to find an English-speaking colleague to assist. The food is genuinely authentic. I've only tried the street tacos, and they might just be the best I've experienced in the U.S. They're served between two tortillas, seemingly dipped in grease and possibly pan-fried. Not the healthiest choice, but they're deliciously tender (soft, not crispy) with succulent carne asada, onions, and cilantro. Adding their spicy sauce enhances the flavors even more. These tacos are slightly larger than usual, and four were quite filling. The price was $7 for four tacos and a diet coke. The staff was appreciative and welcoming. I'll definitely return. If you've enjoyed tacos in Mexico, try this spot.

Eager to sample a new sandwich shop in the mall, I noticed a special on a philly cheese steak with fries for $5.49. The cashier offered to add a drink for an extra dollar. Agreeing, my bill came to over eight dollars, which seemed steep due to tax. It turned out the drink cost $1.69. I wasn't about to quibble over 69 cents, yet felt misled. Odd. Receiving my sandwich, it was merely as big as Subway's six-inch. Disappointing. It took just four bites to finish. Ever tried those frozen philly cheese steaks from Costco? They're microwaved and surprisingly superior. I won't return; the food isn't worth the expense. I'd pay $8 for quality mall fare like Sarku or Sbarro, but not for subpar food. If desired, I could produce something more edible and sell it for $8, likely with more nutritional value and better taste.

I believe In-N-Out Burger is overrated; it's not the ultimate burger. However, it's decent, and the service is consistently excellent. Getting your order can be slow, which seems ironic for 'fast food,' yet they ensure accuracy. The menu offers few choices, mainly burgers and fries, with no vegetarian options. The quality surpasses McDonald's, though it's not as impressive as Smashburger.
I visited in the evening, missing the scenic views, yet the meal was enjoyable, particularly as I wasn't footing the bill :)

We arrived in time to catch the final moments of the live band's performance, only to hear a clichÃ©d LMFMAO track instead. The venue offers a great city view and seems pleasant, especially at sunset. Despite the Saturday night bustle, the service was commendable. I didn't sample the food, so no comments there. The establishment features two areas: one with a stage and another separate room, both appearing to have ample seating.

These oily burgers, encased in paper reminiscent of Seattle's "Dick's" Old Fashioned Burgers, are enjoyable. I appreciate the provision of small ketchup dipping cups over packets, which simplifies drive-thru dining. My latest choice was the green chile burger, notably cheesy and delicious, served hot with perfectly melted cheese and not overly sauced. Drive-thru wait times can be lengthy, yet the wait is justified. The fries are ordinary yet acceptable.
Great cuisine, though somewhat expensive. Manageable if you visit during happy hour or if it's within your budget.

I appreciate the variety of fries available here, though I favor the standard ones. My top pick is the Arizona Smash burger, topped with jalapenos, guacamole, and cheese, and you can opt for chicken over beef. This spot is somewhat more expensive than other burger joints, but the flavor is superior, in my view. It's challenging to explain, so best to experience it personally.
I tried the Hobo Eggs! It seems just 9 individuals in 6 years have completed it. I was nowhere near finishing. It really ought to be called the Hobo Potatoes, given it's primarily potatoes, not eggs.

Laser tag is simply enjoyableâno question. Despite its terrible setting (poor neighborhood adjacent to a biker bar), it remains an excellent venue for laser tag. It's puzzling why Laser Quest venues are often situated in less desirable city parts, likely due to lower costs. Fortunately, this meant my extended "Ironman" laser tag session was affordable at $12 and thoroughly entertaining. The facility was packed, expansive, and equipped with numerous ramps, walls, mirrors, and shooting apertures.
I've never visited China, yet this place nearly replicates it with its Chinese-style buildings and a big pond full of fish. It's a great spot for photography and strolling.
Their chicken salad was mediocreâneither terrible nor particularly impressive. Perhaps I'll opt for the ham on my next visit. Lol.
Passion fruit iced tea is incredible. Burgers are average, unremarkable. The tropical beach-themed interior decor is delightful, enhancing the dining experience. The service is also satisfactory.

I liked this venue. Service was excellent, from the hostess to the waitress. The food arrived fast, convenient since we were off to a show later. The sushi wasn't the best ever, but it was acceptable. Naturally, it's pricey as it's located in Scottsdale. The interior was appealing, especially the fish tanks embedded in the floor at the entrance. It's a compact but snug place. Overall, a satisfactory meal option for quick sushi if you're nearby.

This spot is somewhat concealed. I visited on a Monday evening to see friends. Karaoke was on, and despite it being late (9pm), some young children were present; one was quite a talented vocalist. Service was adequate, the building seemed new, and while the inside is snug, there's a large outdoor patio encircling it with bar access. We had a thin, greasy, very cheesy Brooklyn-style pizzaâextremely tasty.

Service here is terrible. Our "server" was slow to serve our meal and forgot to provide utensils, plates, or napkins. I repeatedly had to approach the bar to order a drink, often waiting excessively. Once, I found it unattended. I might as well have donned an apron, gone behind the bar, and prepared my own beverage. Despite this, they offer a great outdoor area perfect for enjoying Phoenix's warm evenings. I don't see why the band plays indoors; probably because local residents complain about the noise. If noise is an issue, don't reside next to a damn bar! Fools.

Why review an Albertsons supermarket? Uncertain, yet I appreciated finding all I needed under one roofâespecially Vanilla Coke Zero, which is often hard to locate, but was readily available here. The store boasts excellent customer service, ample parking, a wide range of products, and resides in a modern, well-maintained building. It could become my go-to for groceries.

This spot stands out because it offers meals until midnight, unlike many others that close their kitchens earlier. It boasts a vast menu ranging from pasta to burgers, and all the dishes I've tried are tasty. The establishment is modern, featuring a clean, inviting atmosphere with a large array of TVs and comfortable seating. It has high ceilings and ample space. The service is satisfactoryâunremarkable but effective.

Odd pairing, yet as a novice, I assure you it's tasty. The Kool-Aid, served in a mason jar, is also refreshing. The chicken's seasoning is among the finest I've experienced, similar to Johnny's seasoning salt. It far surpasses KFC. The mix with waffles offers a delightful sweet-salty contrast. You'll enjoy it.

This spot is alright, though somewhat overhyped in my view. The pizza features an ultra-thin crust, distinct from the oily, floppy Brooklyn type; it's rather upscale and refined. Service was satisfactory, the ambiance cozy and dim, with prices leaning towards the expensive side. In summary, it's not extraordinary, but I wouldn't mind returning if others were keen on it.
Long queue due to unskilled workers unaware of proper car washing techniques.
Not bad. The soft tacos were unusually large; they're typically smaller and more numerous. Oh well.
This spot's somewhat unclean. Doubt I'll return unless absolutely necessary.

The coffee was excellent, but the food was just average. I sampled the turkey and early bird sandwiches; the latter was tasty, though perhaps not justifying its cost as it's something I could likely prepare at home. It's served on plain sandwich bread without any sides. This spot probably livens up in the evening when it transforms into a wine bar.

Fantastic, thrilling trek you'll adore, particularly if you're a newbie. The trail has two routes; one is significantly tougher. It certainly gives you a good workout. The scenery is stunning, with gorgeous red rocks. Main drawbacks include terrible parking. Additionally, certain areas are somewhat crowdedâtrails can be quite narrow. Apart from that, it's incredible.

This stadium is impressive, though parking could be better, a common issue at many stadiums. I often park on the street or further away, resulting in a walk. The retractable roof is a clever feature, especially for Arizona. We recently visited and enjoyed excellent seats and discovered a somewhat hidden underground bar, which was unique and intriguing. Another distinctive aspect is the swimming pool available for rent, reportedly costing $3,000, which breaks down to $100 each for 30 guests. The major downside is the home team, The Diamondbacks, who are quite disappointing.

I'm awarding this place 5 stars largely due to its aesthetic and ambiance, reminiscent of a quaint ghost town. I skipped the mine tour and didn't explore every spot, but merely strolling around was impressive. It truly transports you to the old west momentarily. Such attractions are rare in my hometown (Seattle, WA) and likely in other northern cities too. Thus, I strongly recommend it for visitors. Our visit was brief, yet the walk offered delightful views. It would be an ideal spot for a lunch outing. During our visit, a cowboy show was performed. I plan to check out the mine tour next time. The mountain views are spectacular as well.

I dashed in to pick up some rice for a friend's wet phone. It took 20 minutes because I was delayed by two customers paying by check, one fussing over tomato prices. Seriously? Ugh. I'll avoid coming back unless absolutely necessary.
Incredible since you have the freedom to design your own burger with endless possibilities. There's every type of cheese and sauce imaginable, along with various meats and vegetarian options.
Quaint, dimly-lit bar offering tasty meals; its lack of windows surprisingly adds to the charm. Eager to return for karaoke night. Excellent service. It's a compact yet snug spot.
Folks, it's Burger King. If it's too pricey, simply cook burgers at home or get a small deep fryer for your fries/chicken strips.

This spot is excellent. I wouldn't include it in my recommendations for visitors, but it's ideal for locals as it doesn't resemble Phoenix whatsoever. Located in a former residential area, old homes have been converted into businesses like bars and cafes. I appreciate the live music without a cover charge and the diverse audience it attracts. Being from Seattle, it reminds me of a Seattle bar with its architectural style, trendy patrons, music, and extensive beer menu (the server even had to fetch a Coors Light from the back).
It's a McDonald's with decent service, similar to others except it's attached to a gas station. The drive-thru often has a lengthy queue.

I enjoy this venue despite its reputation for attracting an older demographic; I've observed a diverse age group. Perhaps it's my own aging that makes me prefer it over bars filled with obnoxious types sporting reverse caps, stretched earlobes, and tattoos. My visits are on Wednesdays for the excellent 80s tribute band, Rock Lobster. The ambiance and lighting are appealing, and it's easier to communicate with the bartender when ordering drinks due to the lower music volume. However, it is pricey, so I tend to stick to beer.
This location earns additional points for employing little people.

Excellent prices during happy hour and quality service. The establishment is relatively new, featuring an impressive patio where misters ensure you stay cool. The appetizers are generally tasty. I sampled the Martzan beer but didn't particularly enjoy it; I prefer lighter beers.

This restaurant offers excellent cuisine and interesting memorabilia decor, with generally good service. Yet, the costs are exorbitantâ$22 for a burger, fries, and a diet coke for lunch, including tax and tip, which seems excessive.

I concur with another reviewâthe staff here are odd. I've noticed it's inconsistent, but during my last visit, the woman at the counter was notably unfriendly. Historically, Subway displayed a variety of bread options beyond basic white and wheat on their menu. However, when I visited yesterday, this list had disappeared. Having not visited Subway recently, I inquired about the available bread types. The woman briefly responded then turned away. So, I settled for white bread. They earn one star for their palatable food and another for the $5 price tag. Overall, two stars. Service receives zero stars.

This establishment isn't particularly impressive. The building is dated and somewhat cramped, lacking in modern amenities like multiple TVs. However, the cuisine is exceptional. The highly praised carne adovada truly lives up to its reputation, featuring tender spiced pork with melted cheese on top, served alongside rice and beans also topped with cheese. The dishes here pack some heat. I was tempted by the habanero burger but hesitated due to fear; perhaps on a future visit. Service quality was decent, though a bit slow, and it's unclear whether this changes when busier. There's a large outdoor seating area, which was unoccupied during our visit. The ambiance is a quirky mix of divey and enjoyable, making it a good spot for those who appreciate fiery meals.

This place earns a solid three stars. The standout feature is undoubtedly its affordability. You can get three tacos loaded with meat, rice, beans, and a drink for just $5.99. Surprisingly, I couldn't finish everything, which is rare for me. The quality of the food matches the price; the carne asada was somewhat flavorless and less tender than preferred. If you're looking for a quick, inexpensive meal, Rolibertos is a viable option.

Loved the fettucini alfredo but the garlic bread, too crunchy, didn't impress. The restaurant's small and oddly located, yet the bar setup and atmosphere are appealing. We ended up eating at the bar due to no available tables. Its small size means it often fills up. Uncertain about reservation policies, but it's wise to book ahead or be prepared to wait. The bartender was swamped with both bar and table service. Oddly, there's no wine listâonly options for wine by the glass or carafe. Nonetheless, the food excelled.
It's an average spot for enjoying a taco and Corona, not exceptional though. They have a charming bartender, whose name escapes me.
This theater stands out for exclusively showing unique indie films unavailable elsewhere. However, the actual cinema rooms are somewhat outdated and worn.

This spot excels at breakfast, likely the finest in AZ. Prices are fair, with a variety of healthy options and excellent service, including unique southwest-style dishes that epitomize Arizona. I've visited this and other locationsâall consistently impressive. Concerns linger about this particular one closing due to its site, but I remain hopeful. Superb breakfast.
They're typically fast, knowledgeable, and courteous here. Highly recommended.

2011 is set to be an outstanding year! There's usually a short wait to enter this venue, indicating its popularity. The service is excellent and the food matches in quality. Additionally, it boasts an impressive name!

To witness Phoenix's least appealing area, visit hereâit starkly contrasts with old town Scottsdale. Here, the inhabitants are impoverished and unattractive, unlike the affluent and attractive ones there. The attractions are disappointing, everything is too expensive, and while the deep-fried treats taste great, they're also unhealthy. It's best to eat following a spin on the teacups.

I wouldn't call these the best tacos in town; they seem a bit overhyped to me. They're decent, but I don't understand the excitement. Oddly, they're shut on Sundays and Mondays. My first visit was a Sunday (unaware they were closed). Waiting in my car to find another spot, I noticed a man yelling shirtlessly in my rearview mirror, which frightened me, so I quickly drove off. I ended up at Tacos Carbon (or a similar place), which was surprisingly good. I found it superior and the area less intimidating. Be aware, this area isn't the safest. The tacos are fine, but they don't really stand out from other street tacos I've tried in Phoenix.
The cuisine is satisfactoryâtypical pub fare, yet tasty. Service was quite good, both amiable and effective. The space is somewhat tight and confined.

I visited on Cinco de Mayo and surprisingly, it wasn't busy. The carne asada was excellent. We were seated in the rear, which was somewhat strange. However, I received a complimentary t-shirt, which was awesome! The service was also commendable.

This location isn't great. It seems tough for a costume shop to stock all necessary items, yet I've always left empty-handed. It's wiser to prepare early and buy costumes online. If you're looking to overspend on blue napkins, however, this is the place for you.
Costco suits those who tolerate large quantities and crowds. I prefer visiting during quieter times, ideally early on a weekday afternoon.

Does it matter if they microwave their burgers or use leftover chicken gizzards for tenders? They're still tasty. Perhaps their slogan should be, "Burger King: experts at making the unappealing delicious."

Does it matter if they microwave their burgers or use leftover chicken gizzards for tenders? They're still tasty. Perhaps their slogan should be, "Burger King: experts at making the unappealing delicious."

Avoid this spot if you're allergic to peanutsâeach table has buckets of them and shells litter the ground. We visited on a Monday evening; the service was better than usual, with frequent check-ins and quick drink refills. The appetizers were okay; hot and fresh yet lacking in flavor. The fried onion appetizer was tasty but didn't compare to Outback's bloomin' onion. The steak was decent, though its doneness seemed off, feeling somewhat tough. The loaded baked potato was excellent, and the mac and cheese was average; nothing extraordinary but still enjoyable. Generally, it's an ordinary steakhouse; not outstanding but fine for a meal, albeit slightly pricey. You might find similar quality for less at Applebee's, where, unlike here, tossing peanuts on the floor isn't an optionâunless you bring your own, which would be odd.

This establishment merits a solid four stars. Despite its small size in a strip mall, the interior is exceptionally clean and appealing. The service is amiable, and the street tacos are excellent. They're a bit more expensive than anticipated at $2.50 apiece, yet they surpass the usual size of street tacos. It's certainly a fine choice for a somewhat more refined "authentic" Mexican dining experience. They seem to offer ice cream too, though I haven't sampled it.

Enjoy the scenic overlook of "A" mountain and Mill Ave from their terrace. Nice selection of beers. Tasty food. To economize, visit during happy hour. Service tends to be quite satisfactory. The establishment is also spacious. It's somewhat more refined than your typical brewery, yet still affordable.

Each visit to this location has featured excellent service. The sales representatives are knowledgeable and provide the information needed to choose a phone wisely. They're also personable and engage in light conversation. Service can be slow occasionally, but it's generally manageable. Additionally, it would be beneficial if they offered more demo units for the popular models.

I'm puzzled by the other negative reviews. The seating was adequate. It's an acceptable theater, not outstanding. They offer White Castle burgers. It seems it was a prominent theater back in 1956 before being demolished and reconstructed, likely in the 90s. Inside, there's a small museum dedicated to its history. I watched Bad Teacher here; the screen was small, yet the crowd was courteous, unlike my experiences at places like Arrowhead where people chatted throughout the film.

This Panda Express offers affordable, ready-made Chinese cuisine with several options. The service here is consistently efficient and accommodating, with ample seating always available. The interior is well-maintained. A reliable choice.

Hmm, I'm unsure about this venue. It's gloomy and melancholic with somber tunes in the background, reminiscent of a funeral. There weren't many patrons, which is concerning for a Saturday evening. The cuisine was mediocre; we had pulled pork which was passable, but the mac and cheese we received was cold, although they did mix up our order with beans initially but corrected it swiftly. I'd have preferred the beans since the mac and cheese was disappointing. The design of the eatery is terrible, divided into two narrow, dimly lit sections. Our side featured a TV, possibly the tiniest I've seen in any bar or restaurant, just an 11-inch old boxy model. The atmosphere is quite downbeat. They could at least add some candlelight to enhance the mellow jazz vibe. I'm skeptical about returning. I might consider eating here again if it were free.
I haven't visited this place in some time, yet I recall stopping by previously, enjoying live Irish tunes, and having fun. I must revisit to experience it once more.

Having frequented this place intermittently for a while, I'm ready to provide an updated critique.

Pros:
*Operational 24 hours during weekends
*Reasonably priced drink menu with a good selection

Cons:
*The Wi-Fi is terribleâbeyond slow. Staff seems indifferent, leaving me struggling to access emails on a connection worse than dial-up.

*Restrooms are external to the cafÃ©, often locked, requiring a key. If you bring a laptop, you must leave it unattended, which is hardly ideal.

While seating is adequate, not all tables have access to power outlets, which is frustrating when I need to use my laptop for extended periods.

Situated in the Arizona Center downtown, this quaint shop is familiar to me since it's near my workplace. Owned by a couple, it boasts another branch in Gainey Ranch, Scottsdale.

The store primarily stocks items appealing to tourists. Although prices seem slightly steep, the shop is tidy, the staff are exceptionally friendly and kind, and there's a diverse selection of merchandise available.

After hearing positive reviews from several Yelpers, I decided to visit this shop today for the first time, searching for a 3-quart saucepan due to mine malfunctioning. Sadly, they were out, but I picked up a candle instead.

I appreciated this location for various reasons. They offer a pleasant range of gently used kitchen gear, all appearing to be in excellent condition. Their inventory includes a diverse array of items from cookware and bar accessories to dishes, cookbooks, and other kitchen essentials.

Despite not finding what I came for, I'm eager to return. The staff was welcoming, the selection impressive, and the prices reasonable. It's quickly become a top choice for consignment shopping, though a heads-up: parking can be challenging here.

Though I'm no expert in Mexican cuisine, I occasionally enjoy it. This was my first visit to Macayo's, so I decided to dine in at this particular branch.

The restaurant boasts vibrant, colorful decorations and ample thematic decor. The service was excellent, and I had a pleasant experience.

However, I found the menu somewhat expensive and the offerings underwhelming. I ordered two tacos and a small cup of chicken tortilla soup, which was disappointingly scant. While tasty, the soup was overly spicy for my liking. The tacos were decent, yet I've had larger, more flavorful ones from Filbertos for less money.

I might consider returning for happy hour or to show visiting friends the unique decor and sample some dishes, but I wouldn't frequent here regularly. The food was mediocre and didn't justify the cost.

I visit this QT early before work to pick up necessities. Like other QTs, it's consistently busy with a steady flow of customers throughout the day.

The service is swift, allowing for quick visits. The staff are amiable and proficient, and the premises are usually clean. They offer competitive fuel prices, tasty and affordable coffee and muffins, and ample gas pumps and parking, ensuring minimal wait times.

The main issue is the poor driving in the parking lot, necessitating heightened awareness to avoid accidents during morning visits. Aside from that, it ranks among the top gas stations in the valley for its speedy, courteous service and good prices.

**3.5 Stars**

I've visited this theater several times previously, and it's decent enough. It resembles the other AMC theaters I've frequented, with no significant differences.

This location features 24 screens and offers reasonable matinee prices, plus a good range of films. There's plenty of parking, snacks are available, and it's conveniently located just off the highway. It's somewhat hidden in a large strip mall, surrounded by numerous dining options should you wish to grab a bite before or after your movie.

I plan to come back for more films since my recent visit was quite enjoyable.

Indecisive about dinner last night, I eventually chose pizza after much deliberation. Unsure whether to cook or grab takeout, pizza seemed the simplest choice.

I opted for Red Brick for three main reasons: proximity, novelty, and a desire to avoid driving to Barro's.

Upon entering, I was greeted by a pleasant ambianceâclean, appealing, and welcoming. The menu suggested simplicity, so I ordered a small pepperoni pizza.

Expecting a thick crust, I was disappointed to find it thin and mediocre in taste, and somewhat oily. While not terrible, it fell short of my expectations.

Interestingly, they offered gelato, a rarity at pizza places. The mint gelato I tried was delicious and improved my overall experience, raising my rating by a star. Without the gelato, my rating would have been lower due to the pizza alone. The decor, friendly staff, and gelato contributed to a better rating.

I might revisit Red Brick, not because it's exceptional, but because of its convenient location.

My mother and I visited this breakfast spot for the first time today and thoroughly enjoyed it. It was our first visit, and the experience was delightful. The establishment is quaint with limited parking; however, I believe they provide complimentary valet parking based on what I've heard.

I was torn between giving 3 or 4 stars, but opted to round up because the place truly stands out and is enjoyable. I have high expectations for such unique places, so bear with me as I mix some criticism with praise.

The interior was charming and well-decorated, offering ample seating and a variety of items for purchase. However, the ordering process was confusing and slightly annoying. Orders are placed at the register, and although they are supposed to call out your name, we waited without hearing ours. I eventually checked at the counter only to find our food had been waiting, unannounced. Furthermore, the food was left unguarded on a pickup table, posing a risk of being taken unknowingly.

We were also very thirsty and had trouble finding water after placing our orders. We were directed to a complimentary water station in the dining area, but the glasses were small and lacked ice, which was frustrating given the heat and our thirst. The cramped space required us to make multiple trips to quench our thirst.

Now for the positives: the food was excellent. Both my mother and I loved what we had; the English muffins were a highlight. My mother was so impressed that she purchased a pack to take home. I chose the eggs rancheros, which were delicious and a new dish for meâI finished every bit of it. It came with fresh fruit and a tasty English muffin served with what seemed like homemade jelly. My mother enjoyed her pancakes as well. Overall, this is a delightful dining spot, and I look forward to returning.

I've been frequenting this particular Safeway for several months, and it's fairly decent. My shopping experience has improved since I began last summer, especially after a renovation at year's end that significantly enhanced its appearance.

This Safeway is somewhat datedânot the most modern or stylish I've visited, but it's pleasant and I feel at ease shopping there. It stocks nearly everything needed for a comprehensive shopping trip, including the typical Safeway Deli, meat counter, pharmacy, and a good variety of food and miscellaneous items.

I rated it 4 stars because A) it was recently renovated and B) the store maintains cleanliness.

I arrived here post-coffee from across the street, entered, and immediately took to it! It reminded me of a Fresh and Easy layout but was significantly more appealing. The item variety was limited, yet the goods offered were competitively selected, reasonably priced, and the staff welcoming.

I learned that Walmart owns this location. Intriguing. I hope their other stores could match this one's cleanliness and vibe. Though I didn't purchase as much as expected, I'll likely come back next time I'm nearby.

En route to the Airport, I opted to grab a snack at Ted's since it's near my home and I hadn't visited before. It seemed like the perfect opportunity to try it.

The place was decent. The decor was unremarkable, and while the experience didn't astound me, I had a good time. After waiting in line, I chose a jumbo beef hot dog topped with chili. Austin selected a sausage with various toppings and fries. We enjoyed our meals and I intend to go back soon. Quite satisfying!

I often visit this specific Subway for several reasons. Primarily, I work at the Arizona Center, making it conveniently located for a quick meal during a busy lunch hour when I'm very hungry.

Generally, I'm not keen on Subway. I find their food mediocre and have discovered healthier dining alternatives.

Typically, there's a long queue due to many of us having lunch simultaneously. The premises are well-kept, and the staff performance is mediocre. The menu is straightforward, with plenty of seating available, both indoors and outdoors.

Recently, I've been reading extensively and sought additional books for my work lunch breaks. I tried Bookmans and Changing Hands unsuccessfully before opting for Borders to explore their selection.

I had visited this Borders previously, though not recently. I appreciate the store for several reasons, particularly its ample stock and the consistently amiable staff.

As I browsed without a particular title in mind, I knew the type of book I was interested in. I enjoy their bargain section and the store's layout, marked clearly by overhead and direct signage.

Although I made no purchase, I enjoyed the experience. The staff was welcoming, the operating hours convenient, and the option to order elusive titles is available should they not be in stock.

Today, while shopping, I was thrilled to find a Jersey Mike's at the mall. After a busy morning of errands, I was too exhausted to cook and opted for a sub there instead.

The restaurant was spotlessly clean and well-decorated, with plenty of seats. Despite the heat outside, I chose to eat inside. I ordered a #9 club sandwich, which included turkey, roast beef, cheese, and various toppings, bacon included.

However, I specifically requested no bacon. The server, busy with multiple orders, accidentally added bacon to my sandwich and omitted mustard. After catching his attention, he corrected the order by removing the bacon and adding mustard.

Along with my meal, I enjoyed chips and a drink, finding everything delicious and well-priced. Additionally, I received a complimentary cookieâa white chocolate chunkâdistributed by the cashier as he refreshed the display. It was delightful.

I'm a fan of Jersey Mike's and look forward to future visits.

I adore Smashburger, truly. I delayed visiting this branch but managed to go tonight. Sadly, the service was disappointing, and despite likely returning, I'm displeased with this particular branch. Here's the reason:

I arrived at 5:30, choosing the all-American burger and onion rings. Initially, the place was quiet, but it filled up as I began eating.

Mid-meal, I finished my drink and needed more. I also decided to get a fork due to the small size of the onion rings. By then, the restaurant was packed.

When I stood to get my refill, I noticed a busboy clearing my table. My burger was barely touched. I tried to stop him, but he didnât hear and continued to the kitchen with my meal. I was livid, having paid $10 for a meal that was being discarded prematurely.

I caught a server's attention and explained the situation. She fetched the busboy, who seemed young, and I reiterated that I hadnât finished. Both he and the server apologized, but I was more interested in getting my meal back than apologies.

They offered a new burger and fries, but I declined since I was nearly full. I requested the manager, but the busboy disappeared into the kitchen and didnât return. I wanted to ensure they understood the issue.

After leaving, I called the manager from home to express my frustration. The manager apologized, took my details, and offered a gift certificate for a free meal, which was my initial desire.

Despite enjoying the food, I'm hesitant to revisit this location soon because of this experience.

I decided it was time to replenish my bra collection and sought a professional fitting, which I believe every woman should experience.

I discovered a wonderful boutique in Scottsdale, nestled within the same complex as Saba's Western Wear. It's a charming, quaint, and cozy shop that feels like a home, complete with pink walls and an array of bras and accessories for women of all sizes.

The store serves women of every shape, size, and color, offering extensive support options, including post-surgical products, and they're willing to place special orders.

They operate on Saturdays from 10-2 and are closed Sundays. Although they prefer appointments, walk-ins are welcome, as I experienced myself. A professional young lady welcomed me, answered all my questions, and helped me select some everyday bras without any fuss.

In the fitting room, she measured me and presented various options. I was pleased to find the prices, ranging from $40-70, quite reasonable.

The fitting was free, enhancing the overall positive experience with knowledgeable staff who provided genuine service without any aggressive sales tactics.

The boutique also has a longstanding branch in Tucson, established for 50 years, with the Scottsdale location open for 15 years.

This place offered exactly what I needed: expert service without pressure, and I gained valuable insights about bras. Some information was familiar, while some was new.

I highly recommend visiting this boutique for a satisfying experience.

Following disappointing visits to various unnamed auto parts outlets, I opted to try this place instead, despite it being slightly off my usual route.

I needed quality windshield washer fluid for my Jeep before leaving town, not just any low-grade product. I found what I was looking for here!

Upon arrival, the service was decent, the premises were tidy and well-organized, and I successfully obtained my item. I'll definitely consider coming back!

I visited this shop impulsively to explore its offerings. A charming small store featuring an excellent array of paper goods and items. It's not large, yet it adequately provides everything necessary for scrapbooking. There's even a lab available for use! Delightful shop, but it's shut on Sundays, which is disappointing.

I visited this cinema impulsively at a friend's behest, eager to catch a film during the holiday break. It was my first time at this hidden spot near the fashion square mall, and it was quite the discovery.

Observations from my visit include:
A) The cinema is quaint and dated, likely established in the 70's, later becoming an indie film venue after a newer, larger cinema opened in the mall.

B) Parking is scarce and frustrating; I spent 10 minutes just trying to find a place.

C) The cinema isn't terribleâit's simply morphed into a niche venue for indie films, with only two ticket booths causing lines to extend around the block when busy.

D) On Christmas Day, the audience was predominantly seniors, all seemingly over 65. I felt out of place as the sole non-retiree there, amidst a crowd definitely not suited for socializing in line.

I'd only revisit under extreme coercion.

Stacy's is adorable! When you arrive, you see it's a small shack with some outdoor seating. It appears most patrons prefer takeout, though you're certainly allowed to dine at their tables.

Upon arrival, you place your order at the window and they prepare your meal as you wait. A few of us were chilling in the parking lot, which was quite enjoyable! I chose the BBQ Brisket to go, which was decent. I particularly enjoyed that it was smoked and that the BBQ sauce was served separately, allowing me to add as much as I wanted.

The menu is somewhat limited but decent, with reasonable prices. I got a kick out of their makeshift dining area, complete with a spray-painted "man cave" sign. Hilarious.

The place is charming, best for takeout, and while parking can be tight, it's definitely a charming spot and quite satisfactory overall!

I visited the book club at this venue yesterday and doubt I'll return soon. Initially, the day began promisingly but concluded with a negative impression of the establishment.

Upon arrival, the restaurant was nearly empty, leading to excessive attention from our server, who frequently urged us to place orders. Not particularly hungry, I still felt compelled to order due to her persistence. I chose the American hot dog with fries and a coke.

As the others placed their orders, one girl's slider request was overlooked and unfulfilled. The server appeared just as shocked as us when notified. Post-delivery of our food, the service quality plummeted. The venue became crowded due to a USA/Canada hockey match, and it seemed our table was forgotten. I had to request the manager to fetch our bill after not seeing our server for nearly an hour. Moreover, the bill had to be returned for splitting so each could pay their portion.

Despite being a sports bar, the service was subpar. Our table felt neglected, without refill offers, and we had to signal other staff for our bill. I'm not inclined to revisit, as both the food and service were disappointing.

Regrettably, I must rate this establishment poorly, though I'm not entirely thrilled about it. My first visit was last night for dinner, and I'm not eager to return soon.

Feeling peckish for something unconventional, I stopped by a place I've often passed but never entered. I reluctantly paid $11.50 for a meal that ultimately disappointed me.

I assembled my meal, choosing from options like meat, pork, chicken, and fishâI opted for meat. Despite adding various veggies and sauces, which a chef grilled, the meat's odd texture and the small serving bowls detracted from the experience. The meat was thinly sliced and somewhat chewy, and while the veggies and garnishes were fresh, the choices were sparse, leaning heavily towards typical salad ingredients like tomatoes, cucumbers, carrots, and celeryâa peculiar yet healthy mix. I wished for more diversity.

The staff was amiable and accommodating, and the venue had the air of a repurposed fast food restaurant.

Overall, I'm underwhelmed, especially compared to other Mongolian-style meals I've enjoyed. Unfortunately, this visit didn't measure up. :-(

Since I'm new to this part of town, I've been on the lookout for a good BBQ spot, especially since my favorite places are now too far away on the East side. A couple of weeks back, I discovered a restaurant, dined there, but didn't leave a review. I returned tonight hoping to replicate the pleasant initial visit, but it fell short of my memories.

My first visit was on a quiet Saturday night, but this Friday evening saw a modest increase in patrons. At the counter, while checking the menu, the server seemed to understand I was dining inâthough later, she mistakenly prepared my meal for takeaway. This mix-up began when she suggested I wait at the bar, but I opted for a seat at the back.

I ordered a Brisket sandwich and sat in the back. While others received their meals directly at their tables, I was eventually handed a to-go bag without a drink. I clarified that I intended to eat in and requested a plate, to which she apologized and returned the food to the kitchen. Thirsty, I went to fetch a drink myself and noticed the staff abruptly stop their chat and avoid eye contact as I approached, making me wonder if I was now seen as a troublesome customer.

When my meal was finally served properly, the brisket was just okay. Had I reviewed them after my first visit, they might have earned 4 to 5 stars. Now, they get just 3.

Yesterday's date had us hungry, so we hopped off the light rail at Mill to grab a bite. We stumbled upon Silvermine Subs shortly afterâwhat a find!

It was my first visit and I enjoyed it. The place isn't upscale, but it offers straightforward, tasty meals at fair prices. They offer a variety of both hot and cold subs, alongside various sides and combos. I chose the King Bullion; a delicious choice! I opted for a small 5-inch sub, a large soda, and chips. The service was swift, making it a popular spot among college students, likely due to its proximity to campus.

I'd definitely go back. It's delicious, affordable, and conveniently located near the light rail on Mill.

In the mornings, I grab coffee and a snack before heading to work, stopping nearby because it's close. I'm not particularly fond of Einstein's due to various shortcomings, yet I keep going as it's conveniently there.

This location doesn't impress me much. Service is sluggish, the coffee area often needs restocking, and I frequently have to request more coffee creamer. The long lines around 7 am are also due to slow service. Their bagels aren't great, but I prefer the muffins, which are decent, and the prices are reasonable.

Overall, it's an alright spot, but Einstein's has grown dull and monotonous, making me crave better service and quality. At least there's ample seating here.

I visited this spot last evening to check it out, and it's surprisingly decent. Certainly a neighborhood dive, it's an old, quaint restaurant that appears to have stood the test of time. Definitely a family-owned establishment.

The menu is extensive, offering a wide range of choices. I opted for the original Gyro and a Greek salad. The salad was particularly enjoyable, and the Gyro was both filling and delicious. You certainly receive value for your money here!

I suggest giving this place a shot, especially for the Gyros, which are completely worth it. It's a simple, unpretentious dive, yet the food compensates for the lack of ambiance! Also, note that it's closed on Sundays.

I had great expectations for this establishment, often seen throughout the valley, believing it to be a decent spot for wings and beer. However, while I maintain that belief, my stomach disagrees. My visit left me disappointed, and I've shelved any plans to return.

Last night, I sought a new dining experience, nothing extravagant or pricey, just a break from the usual. Craving chicken wings but not from Wendy's, I opted for Wingstop. That's how I ended up there.

Upon entering, the space wasn't large but accommodated a good number. After perusing the menu and posing some queries, I chose the 3-piece chicken wing combo at a fair price, selecting the BBQ flavor.

The meal arrived in about 10 minutes. I couldn't finish it. The fries were overly salty and had a strange, possibly spicy taste. My tongue was confused! The wings were smothered in BBQ sauce, excessively so. It seemed as though they had taken BBQ sauce from Wendy's or McDonald's and lavished it on the wings. It was overwhelming, and even after scraping some sauce off, I couldn't eat the rest.

My stomach was upset all night. It rejected what I had eaten. I awoke in the night feeling nauseous but fortunately didn't vomit. It was too much for my stomach to manage. :-(

I doubt I'll return anytime soon.

I had dined here previously, though it had been a while. After attending a horse show on Saturday, John C and I, famished and in need of a drink, decided to revisit. It seemed like a good time to return.

The restaurant offers a solid selection of dishes and a comprehensive drink list. We visited around 5 PM on Saturday, finding it unusually quiet, with just a family nearby and a couple of patrons at the barâa bit slow for a weekend.

The service was satisfactory; John C enjoyed a bloody mary and quesadillas, while I opted for slider appetizers, and we both chose sweet potato fries. Drink prices were fair, though the venue was almost deserted.

In the end, I satisfied my craving for K O'Donnell's, pleased with the visit. I left satiated, particularly enjoying the sweet potato fries.

How could anyone dislike the library, particularly one as impressive as this? I've visited twice and adore its architectural splendor. Constructed from steel and glass, it truly is a gem. With glass elevators, reflecting pools, and art everywhere, it's a delight to behold.

If every library were like this, attendance would surely increase. This one boasts five levels, each designed for a unique function. I plan to come back again.

Despite my fondness for pizza, California Pizza Kitchen doesn't quite hit the spot for me. It lacks the special quality that would make me a regular visitor to the franchise.

Upon our arrival, the staff greeted my date and me warmly, and we asked for a booth. It was a quiet Sunday evening, and the place wasn't very crowded. Oddly, we were placed in a massive booth designed for six, even though there were plenty of smaller booths available. The reason for this choice remains a mystery.

We started with a focaccia appetizer, which was outstandingâdefinitely the highlight of our meal. However, Patrick's mojito was off, lacking mint and tasting strange, but after mentioning it to our server, she promptly corrected it. (I'm not much of a drinker, but I trust his judgment.)

For the main course, I chose the Santa Fe Chicken Pizza, which was decent. Patrick seemed pleased with his meal too. We skipped dessert and lingered for a while longer.

Our server was competent and professional, though the service did drag a bit. It might have been due to understaffing. At one point, I was so thirsty and out of soda that I went to the bar myself to fetch a refill, which was quickly promised by the bartender. She seemed quite busy.

I wouldn't hesitate to dine here again. It wasn't a bad experience overall.

This weekend, with Memorial Day approaching, I decided to explore a new spot I found on Yelp. It intrigued me with its unique and interesting vibe, exactly what I was seeking.

The establishment is situated in a commercial area, housed in a warehouseâa non-traditional setting for a restaurant, which I found quite appealing.

The decor was decent, providing a somewhat Greek ambiance due to leaf motifs painted near the hostess stand, although it isn't a Greek restaurant.

Upon arrival, I was promptly seated at the front. It was early, so I opted for breakfast. The server was competent and amiable. I chose French Toast on cinnamon bread, which was exceptionally deliciousâI consumed it quickly, savoring every bite.

My visit was thoroughly enjoyable, offering a cozy atmosphere. It's not the usual chic breakfast spot, yet it's tasty enough to indulge in some really good food at reasonable prices.

I envision bringing my mom here. There were many seniors present, likely because it was around 8:30 AM on a Sunday, typical for that time. I definitely plan to return!

This spot is decent enough. While it falls short in certain aspects, it compensates in others, making it a fairly good location overall. The Habit offers a fast-casual dining setup where orders are placed at the counter and collected when ready. The interior is vibrant and well-appointed, with a good variety of menu options. The prices are reasonable, though there were some discrepancies in how my order was processed.

You can grab a standard burger combo for $5.95, which comes with fries and a beverageâa great deal! Additionally, the drink refills are unlimited, a plus for someone like me who drinks a lot of soda while dining out. However, opting for anything other than the standard fries incurs extra charges, which I found disappointing. I opted for sweet potato fries as a special treat, but they billed these separately from the combo, doubling the cost I anticipated. The sweet potato fries were around $2.95, which seemed excessive. While I get the idea of a small upcharge, the full a la carte pricing was frustrating. The food is decent, but not exceptional.

The service was warm and welcoming. The manager made rounds to ensure customer satisfaction, and the meals were both hearty and delicious. I appreciate this as a better alternative to typical fast food and enjoyed a quick, satisfying meal here. In future visits, I'll stick to the regular fries to avoid the extra fee. Overall, it's a place worth trying.

I've passed this spot on the lightrail but only recently visited because it lacks its own stop, requiring a drive, and it closes early on Saturdays while remaining shut on Sundays.

I ventured there last Saturday for BBQ. It's located in a tidy strip mall with ample parking. The establishment offers sufficient seating and counter service instead of waitstaff, which suits me fine.

They serve both lunch and dinner. Not very hungry, I opted for a Beef Brisket sandwich from the lunch menu, which is essentially Ã  la carte with no included sidesâyou pick what you want. The cashier mentioned the dinner plate was a better deal with sides included for a few extra dollars, but I preferred a lighter meal.

The sandwich was decent. While not outstanding, I enjoyed my visit and might try the dinner option later. The place is clean, appears reputable, and offers a comprehensive menu. Debating between 3 and 4 stars, I chose 3 as it more accurately reflects my experience without feeling compelled to round up. It's definitely worth trying, and I genuinely liked it.

After a rainout at the Arabian Horse show at Westworld left me extremely hungry, I had planned to eat there, but the muddy conditions shortened my visit.

Post-show, I drove along Scottsdale Road pondering my dining options. I wanted something hearty but affordable, not fast food. Spotting Jasons Deli, I quickly parked and went in. I've visited other locations, including frequently the one in Awatukee, though this was my first time at this particular branch.

Their ordering process is uniform across locations: order and pay at the counter, then wait for food delivery to your table.

I chose a half sandwich with a salad. The sandwiches are large, and the salad bar is self-serve. I intended to have a Caesar Salad, but despite assurances, the salad bar lacked the necessary ingredients, which was disappointing, yet I managed with little fuss.

The food quality is decent, though I find the ordering process slightly uncomfortable. The prices are high, but the portion sizes justify the cost. I enjoy their deli sandwiches, and this visit satisfied my craving.

While it's not a traditional deli, it's satisfactory for filling meals. I'd definitely revisit.

I visited this dealership on Saturday to have my Jeep serviced and to explore the place. I scheduled an appointment and left my Jeep in the service bay.

Upon entering, I was welcomed and overall had a decent experience. However, I must mention that waiting for three hours was not ideal, although this seems common at most dealerships during warranty services, so I can't fault them entirely.

What bothers me is being pressured to consider purchasing a new vehicle while I'm there for service. I'm there to maintain my car, not to buy or exchange it. Why must salespeople do this? I understand it's their job to sell, but it shouldn't be every time. It's quite irritating.

**3.5 stars**

Unexpectedly, this spot isn't too shabby! Tucked in the desolate end of a strip mall, this charming little restaurant delivers scrumptious meals.

I popped in last evening to sample something new. Their menu boasts a range from Gyros and burgers to wings and Philly steaksâa real treat!

I opted for a Gyro, and it was delightfully flavorful! There's ample seating, TVs, and a menu that'll satisfy many. They're open late as well! Despite its location in a bleak strip mall, this place is worth a visit!

Chompies is always a delightful indulgence for me, regardless of the time. I recently visited this branch and picked up a sandwich on a Sunday. The service seemed slower than usual, and I'm not sure if that's typical or because it was a Sunday evening. Consequently, they lost a point for the excessive waiting.

Here's my take: I enjoy Chompies. I don't consider it bad. However, I don't find it exceptionally outstanding either. It's probably the finest option for authentic Jewish cuisine in Arizona. I'd confidently bring my parents here, given my Jewish heritage. Having been raised on this cuisine, I consider myself a reliable critic. In my opinion, it's the best representation of Jewish food in the Valley so far, though it's not the ultimate Jewish culinary experience I've had.

I must admit, it's delightful to discover what I deem a top-notch family restaurant. They boast an extensive menu, and the ambiance is cozy and invitingâperfect for family meals.

Given that it's an Italian restaurant, I appreciate that they offer a wide array of classic Italian dishes without the typical "chain restaurant" vibe. Their selection includes Calzones, Pasta, Pizza, Salads, etc., with a comprehensive menu that features plenty of choices! They also have a diverse wine selection, which I absolutely adore!

Keep in mind, my visit only involved a Greek salad, so my sampling of the menu was minimal, yet it was delicious nonetheless. The restaurant offers a laid-back environment, appears well-maintained and clean, and is staffed by warm, welcoming individuals, creating a charming setting.

After a day out with my buddy Austin, hunger drove us to this spot for lunch. It was my first visit, and I must admit, it impressed me.

As we entered, we noticed two Julio's locations. We opted for the smaller, fast-casual one with self-serve nachos, fountain drinks, and counter service. The other Julio's offers a full-service dining experience, but we preferred something simpler.

I chose the Burro enchilada with shredded beef, rice, and refried beans. The prices were great, and the portion sizes generous. Austin picked the mini chimis, which I sampledâthey were delicious!

I had plenty of leftovers for dinner, leaving me satisfied from our lunchtime visit. The place is cozy, tastefully decorated, features an outdoor patio, and offers a diverse menu.

Definitely planning a return visit.

After living here for some time, I've noticed Frys Grocery stores are either affluent and modern or dilapidated and dismal. I prefer the former, and this store fits that bill. It's a bit far, but worth the drive for its modernity and the convenient Bank of America onsite. It offers a deli, meat, household items, and moreâeverything one could need. I'll be back often!

AJ's evokes nostalgia for a similar store I frequented in Michigan, setting high expectations for me.

I'm thoroughly impressed by this grocery chain's consistent high standards in service and product qualityâthey consistently exceed my expectations.

This particular AJ's location maintains the chain's reputation without deviation, offering an excellent array of produce, wine, meats, fish, and other high-quality items. Service is exceptional.

During my visit, I enjoyed a jazz ensemble performance by an outdoor musician, which was quite enjoyable.

The store is somewhat expensive and caters to niche needs. While I wouldn't replace my regular grocery store with it, AJ's is definitely worth considering for top-notch produce, wine, and meats. It's a valuable addition, well worth the expense.

Located between Warner and Elliot off Priest, this full-service post office is where I handle larger mailings, purchase stamps, and engage in various postal tasks.

I appreciate the extended Saturday hours at this branch, with service counters open until 3PM and an automated attendant available for after-hours assistance. It offers postal box rentals, a drive-through letter drop, and sales of mailing supplies, maintaining a clean and orderly environment.

I rated this location three stars due to the typically long wait times, characteristic of many USPS branches. The issue isn't an overwhelming crowd but rather 4 or 5 individuals enduring lengthy waits. I've experienced a 20-minute line just to send a large envelope, a task that should take mere minutes.

While there is an automated scale in the lobby, new government regulations restrict what can be weighed. Not all envelope sizes are available, so pre-packaging at home might be more efficient for certain items.

Situated just a stone's throw from my splendid apartment, this location appeals to me for several reasons. Firstly, it offers remarkably inexpensive fuel and complimentary air for tires. The spacious parking and refueling area allows for effortless vehicle navigation with minimal concern.

Both the interior and exterior of this establishment are notably tidy. It's well illuminated and stocks a diverse selection of beverages and snacks, with the personnel being both immaculate and welcoming. I believe QT excels in maintaining cleanliness here, and the staff performance is outstanding.

Despite my ongoing affection for Fresh and Easy, this particular branch doesn't quite match up. Initially, I became a fan by frequenting their Ray and Kyrene store, which remains my preferred spot. Although this location stocks the same items and mirrors the interior of my favorite, something is amiss.

I continue to patronize this store for groceries since they offer excellent bargains, their ready-made meals are consistently good, and the clearance section presents notable savings. However, I have some reservations about this specific branch.

I'll keep visiting this store due to its proximity to my apartment, but the Ray and Kyrene location will always hold a special place in my heart.

I've been in the valley for a while but never visited souper salad until today's lunch.

The setup here impresses meâa salad buffet offering a variety of fresh choices, unlike the stale options elsewhere. It includes numerous selections, beverages, desserts, and fantastic breadsticks!

Today, I opted for a combo that included a drink, breadsticks, and a salad to go. The counter staff was amiable and pleasant, making my visit enjoyable. I'll surely return soon!

I'm a big fan of deli cuisine and have sampled several local spots, including this one, which I quite enjoy!

The prices are standard for a deli, yet seem to be more affordable than others. The selection is vast, and you can customize your order as you like. I particularly appreciate their Matzoh Ball soup, large deli sandwiches, and various sides. Delicious!

Recently, I've had lunch here several times with colleagues, opting for lighter fare to avoid the post-lunch drowsiness that doesn't sit well with my boss. My usual is a Kosher beef hot dog with fries, a pickle, and a small soda, all for $5.24. My friend often chooses the tuna on wheat and enjoys it greatly.

One unusual aspect is the buffet-style service. You line up, place your order, and proceed while your food is prepared behind a glass by the staff. The service is fast and efficient, and there's ample seating, even during busy times.

I'd suggest this place to almost anyone, and they have several locations across the valley. Tasty!

Since few venues were open on New Year's Day, I opted to explore the area. The bookstore had yet to open and already had a long queue, so I looked for a place to get coffee while waiting.

I stopped at a strip mall where I've previously shopped, finding a tiny coffee shop nestled among other outlets. It's quite cramped with hardly any seats, but I enjoyed my visit for various reasons. The prices were incredibly low, with a 12 ounce Mocha costing just $3.24, and the service was exceptional. I definitely plan to come back.

However, I rated it three stars because it only had two tables inside, which is problematic. I inquired about the Wi-Fi, and was told it was unreliable but would be repaired soon. I prefer coffee shops where I can work for a while, but the lack of indoor seating and unstable internet, along with no outlets and the discomfort of sitting outside in summer, makes it unsuitable for extended stays despite the good prices and service.

I stumbled upon my current doctor entirely by chance. Last year, needing medical care and lacking a local physician, I consulted my health insurance and discovered this clinic.

Several factors make me appreciate this place. It hosts multiple doctors, forming a collaborative team, and includes two highly competent nurse practitioners. What really clinches it for me? The Saturday morning hours! The convenience of weekend appointments is fantastic!

The clinic is exceptionally clean and modern. During my recent visit, the nurse practitioner agreed to electronically forward my prescription to my preferred pharmacy. Great!

I adore this clinic! It's become my go-to for healthcare.

Following a weekend devoted to tidying up, I gathered items to contribute to the local Goodwill. I needed to dispose of a desk to free up space at home and decided donating it was the optimal choice.

This Goodwill is situated in a shopping center, clearly visible from the street. The drop-off zone is behind the mall, conveniently designed so you can stay in your car without needing to enter the building.

I navigated to the back, finding the donation process very streamlined. I was fourth in a line of cars, with ample staff ready to assist in unloading. When it was my turn, a helpful employee took care of my items.

Later, I explored the store, noting their frequent sales and diverse inventory, including menâs and womenâs apparel, lamps, and various household goods.

I rated them five stars because they support the community, have an efficient donation system, and emphasize the importance of giving back.

Today marked my first visit to this car wash, and I was thoroughly impressed. Located at the northeast corner of Chandler with Kyrene as the crossroad, the facility is well-organized, clean, and operates efficiently.

The process is fully automated. Upon entering, you choose from two lanes to make your payment. A digital display offers various car wash options and additional services. I opted for the basic $5 car wash.

Post-selection, you insert cash, the barrier lifts, and you proceed to the wash area. You remain in your vehicle, which is standard. An attendant guided me in and pre-rinsed my car. However, he didn't adjust my mirrors, which was inconvenient as I had to do it myself post-wash, detracting from the experience.

A highlight is the complimentary vacuums, conveniently shaded to avoid discomfort from the sun while vacuuming. Additional services, including rainx treatments, are available.

A drawback is the limited space in the vacuum area, which can be problematic if full. Also, minimal space is available for adjustments like mirror fixing, which can be a hassle.

Do visit their website; it's user-friendly and informative, covering multiple locations across the valley, not just Chandler. The website itself earns praise.

During the holiday weekend, I visited this spot for a sub. I was curious about the establishment and its offerings. From the exterior, it seemed intriguing, possibly an old McDonalds? It's a two-story building with a large front window.

Upon entering, I perused the menu and chose a hot pastrami sub, which was quite tasty. It measured roughly 8 inches, and the pricing was fair. A great bargain indeed! It was rather quiet during my visit, with just one other diner and me. They offer happy hour deals, including some beers that pair well with the subs and other items. Quite cool!

The subs are satisfactory, but the venue could use some updating.

Feeling a bit peckish while heading out for New Year's Eve, I opted to grab a meal to silence my rumbling belly. I chose Pei Wei and had a pleasant time there. It seems to be a more subdued alternative to PF Chang's, yet the ambiance and cuisine are equally delightful.

The service was prompt, the venue was immaculate, and the meal was delicious. I ordered the sweet and sour chicken, which came in generous portions. I anticipated a reduction in serving size for some reason, but that wasn't the case at all.

My visit was enjoyable, and I'd likely go back if I found myself nearby and in need of a dependable dining option.

I'm fond of the Good Egg. Truly, I am. I've dined at several locations occasionally. This particular one is popular, clearly, though not as crowded as others, based on my observations.

This morning, I stopped by for breakfast while out. Realizing my hunger, and typically not stocking breakfast foods at home, I decided it was time for a visit.

The service here was swift and efficient. My visit was briefâI enjoyed scrambled eggs, an English muffin, and hash browns, all of which were delicious!

I'll likely return. Keep it up, Good Egg!

Wow, I can't believe no one mentioned this gem before! I'm totally smitten with it! Here's how I stumbled upon Barros.

Feeling famished and too tired to cook last night, I checked my fridge and realized I needed to eat out. I was in the mood for something fast and delicious.

While driving, I spotted Barro's from the street. I'd heard about it through Yelp reviews but hadn't visited yet. Tonight seemed perfect.

After parking, I walked in and immediately liked the vibe. The place was bustling with people at tables and booths, enjoying their meals without chaos. The menu was impressive, offering a great variety of dishes, including a selection of Ã  la carte and set-menu pizzas like meat lovers and chicken BBQ.

Opting for something simple since it was just me and my first visit, I chose a small pepperoni pizza and ate there. Despite the crowd, I waited under five minutes to order and about 20 minutes for my pizza, which wasn't bad for a busy Friday evening.

The pizza was a jackpotâdeliciously satisfying. After three years, I finally found excellent pizza in Phoenix. They also offered beer and wine, which was a plus. Though they only had Merlot, Chardonnay, and another wine, I skipped the drink since I was alone, but it was still a nice option.

I loved the thick crust pizza; it was all so tasty! I've fallen for Barros and took leftovers home, planning many return visits to savor their delicious offerings again.

I've dined here several times; it's decent. This fast casual spot offers Greek-style cuisine. You order at the counter, receive a number, and they bring your food to the table when ready.

Initially, I took a Gyro to goâit was excellent: flavorful, hot, and satisfying. My second visit, I tried the bruschetta but didn't enjoy it much and probably won't reorder.

My dislike stemmed from: A) excessive, cold tomatoes on the bruschetta, B) overly soft, warm bread, C) it wasn't my preferred bruschetta style. I favor toasted French bread bruschetta that's uniformly warm, which this wasn't.

Next visit, I'll likely reorder the Gyro, given its deliciousness.

I visited the new LoLo's site with some fellow yelpers to explore it. I had previously visited the downtown branch and wasn't very impressed, so I decided to give it another try. This visit proved far more enjoyable.

Upon arrival, our group was already seated. I was pleased to find that my experience this time was significantly improved. The venue was clean, offered ample parking, and the service was markedly better than downtown. The menu and food quality remained the same, yet the overall experience was enhanced.

Expect a wait when you visit, as this place is extremely popular and delicious. Come ready to dine!

I enjoyed shopping at Dillards for its broad range of affordable products. Eventually, it transformed into a clearance center, where I occasionally shopped. The reasons for this change are unclear, but it resulted in numerous racks filled with significantly reduced Dillards apparel.

Items are organized by size and gender, with many clothes discounted by 50% or even 70%. Frequently, I noticed repetitive clothing styles in various sizes and a small selection of household goods that seemed frequently rummaged through. Despite the store's two-story structure, only one floor is accessible for shopping, featuring a few cash registers by the entrance. While the selection and prices are appealing, finding specific items requires diligent searching. The upper floor is closed, and access is likely only through the ground floor.

The deals are excellent, making it worthwhile to visit and hunt for quality clothes at low prices. Allocate ample time to navigate through the somewhat chaotically arranged racks. The setup isn't particularly attractive, but it's worth exploring while you're there. My success in finding items I like has been hit or miss; sometimes I discover several appealing items, other times I leave with nothing. Overall, it's a decent place.

I've been steering clear of this location due to its poor condition, yet today's necessity to wash two heavily soiled rugs forced my hand. Unfortunately, my usual laundromat has shut down, leaving this as the nearest option. My prior visits had set my expectations; it operates on a card system where funds are loaded onto a laundry card for machine use.

The sole redeeming feature is the affordable pricing. Beyond that, the environment is so dismal it makes me consider a bleach bath for myself. The facility is dilapidated and desperately requires comprehensive refurbishment. The machines are dated, with several consistently out of service. This morning, a burst pipe added to the chaos, requiring cleanup upon my arrival. The restroom is frightening, seemingly with unchanged trash linersâthough the trash is emptied, the liners appear perpetually reused.

Avoid this place if possible. It's unclean, and finding staff assistance is a frequent challenge. It would benefit from more attention to improve its standards, but that seems low on the priority list. This laundromat is a definite disappointment.

Located near Bass Pro Shops in the Mesa Riverview shopping area, this family-run cafe offers coffee, tea, and various treats typical of a coffee shop, including complimentary Wi-Fi. Its extended hours cater to both coffee lovers and internet users.

The reason I didn't rate it 5 stars is due to the seating options. While there are tables and a set of couches, only the couches are truly comfortable. The square tables don't allow for a relaxed, leisurely internet browsing experience, feeling more like sitting at a kitchen table.

Apart from that, it's an excellent spot, distinct from mainstream Starbucks cafes. It features local art, maintains cleanliness, has convenient parking, and consistently good service.

I've visited this spot several times and generally had positive experiences. It's near Fiesta Mall and visible from the street. I favor it over the Tempe Marketplace location due to easier access. The latter often suffers from heavy traffic, making this one a more convenient option.

Previously, I've picked up minor items here, but recently I bought a digital camera. Typically, the staff are proactive in offering assistance, though there are occasions when help is scarce, possibly due to busyness. At times, the attentiveness feels overwhelming, to the point where I find myself trying to dismiss persistent staff.

Nevertheless, I plan to continue shopping here, as my experiences with Best Buy have been satisfactory.

Visited this place last Friday evening with friends and it was decent. It's been ages since I last visited a traditional country buffetâtotally forgot about them.

Dinner for three, including drinks, cost us around $37. A bit more than the anticipated $30, but not a huge issue, though I hadn't planned on nearly $40. Still, it was okay.

The variety of food impressed us. Multiple buffets were active, offering a range of appealing dishes. There was even a grill section with a chef slicing up foodâpretty cool! I tried some steak, which was delicious.

Overall, not a bad spot. Likely to return sometime.

Alright, I confess, I'm not the biggest fan of organic products, yet it's tough to overlook the appeal of Whole Foods. They boast an impressive selection of fresh fish, particularly the smoked whitefish, which is my top pick. Their prepared foods section is also notable, and that's where I get latkes (those are potato pancakes).

Their food assortment is extensive, and it's not just for health enthusiasts or vegetarians. Everything appears fresh, and the store itself is spacious, tidy, and orderly.

My main gripe is the high cost. It's quite expensive.

I visited this spot today as I was nearby and craved a change. I'd known about this place but hadn't stepped inside until today.

It wasn't terrible, yet it didn't excite me much. I was expecting better. Upon entering, it was deserted except for one person dining alone in a corner. I'll attribute the emptiness to it being Christmas Eve, with most people busy with holiday preparations.

Upon entry, I approached the counter to place my order. Being new here, I had several questions, but the cashier was busy and asked me to wait. After what seemed an eternity, she finally took my order. I chose a Brisket sandwich combo with mac and cheese and a soda.

The meal was prepared swiftly, but it was a disappointment. The mac and cheese was overly liquid and peppery. I ate half and discarded the rest. Normally, I'd take leftovers home, but I didn't enjoy it enough to do so. The Brisket was passable, but the BBQ sauce lacked flavor and was scant, leaving parts of my sandwich dry.

Typically, BBQ joints offer a selection of sauces on the table or in a common area, ranging from tangy to spicy. Here, there was a vat near the napkins, unlabeled and uninviting, so I passed on it, unsure of its contents.

Additionally, the restaurant was extremely cold. Coming from Michigan, I'm used to the cold, but it's been unusually chilly here, even by Arizona's standards, with temperatures in the 30s at night. Despite the cold snap, this place had no heating, making me regret not wearing a coat.

While I was not fond of this location, I'm willing to try their other sites in the future, hoping for a better experience.

Today, after lunch, I joined a friend who needed to pick up some spices for upcoming meals, and I came along. I confess, my culinary skills could use a boost, and visiting this shop was inspiring.

This was my first encounter with the store, sparked by my friend's mention, which piqued my curiosity. A dedicated spice shop? The concept excited me. Entering with no expectations, I discovered a fascinating establishment. The aroma was distinctly spiced, yet pleasantly so, with a neat, well-stocked array of spices covering every imaginable type.

Each spice bottle includes not only ingredients but also suggestions for use. Some spices were new to me, and it was captivating to explore their potential culinary applications. The spices are available in various sizes and price points, from a few dollars for a small amount to over $40 for larger quantities. The containers are reusable; buying a spice means you can refill the same jar later, and empty bottles are available for purchase for those who might want to package their own blends from home-grown or uniquely crafted mixes.

I left the store thoroughly impressed by its organization, the welcoming staff, fair pricing, and the extensive selection on offer. If you're nearby, I recommend a visitâit's an engaging spot, and you donât need to be a culinary expert to enjoy it.

I've visited this particular Jason's multiple times. It's oddly located and quite inconvenient to access. Positioned just before the I-10, missing the entrance means a lengthy detour to circle back.
