I opted to dine here because I was too lazy to prepare dinner. Their servings are generous, with a single sandwich sufficient for two. Years ago, my mother and I shared one at their west side location.

I find their menu selection satisfactory. It's extensive enough for most tastes, though personally, I'm not overly impressed.

The layout at most Jason's Deli locations is consistent: a spacious area for self-seating featuring both booths and tables, plus sections for both carryout and dine-in.

After reviewing the menu, I placed my order. The service at the counter was fine, but the pickup process was irritating. While waiting, I took a call from my mom at a table, only to discover later that my order had been ready.

The pickup was confusing; despite having a number displayed on my table, I had to fetch my order myself. This was frustrating, especially since I was on a call and the staff member saw this but still signaled me to come over, forcing me to juggle a heavy tray while on my phone. I'm used to having my food brought to me.

Ultimately, I ate in, enjoying half my sandwich there with a delicious Caesar salad and packing the rest.

This venue is ideal for kids, families, friends, and dates. Note that the portion sizes here are enormous.

Last night, John C and I visited this restaurant he'd been raving about to have dinner. It's fairly new, and although I'd passed it several times, this was my first visit.

The menu is extensive, catering to all tastes with numerous vegetarian options as well as meat, fish, and chicken dishes. All ingredients are sourced locally and are predominantly organic. The interior is tastefully decorated, and patrons choose their own seating upon entry.

John handled most of the ordering. I opted for the falafel, which I found delightful. He chose vegan spinach dip, hummus, and a veggie pizza. Everything was satisfactory, though the veggie pizza was overloaded with broccoli, which I dislike and ended up removing from my portion.

The only drawback was the slow service, delaying our order placement, but this seems to stem from their recent opening. I'm inclined to return and explore some of their meat offerings. With such a diverse menu, I anticipate trying various dishes on future visits.

This restaurant has been on my radar for some time, and now that I'm nearby for a few days, I decided to give it a go. I opted for lunch over dinner, anticipating a smaller crowd, and indeed, it was moderately busyâa steady stream of patrons on a Saturday noon impressed me.

Upon arrival, I inquired about the ordering process from a staff member at the entrance. She explained the procedure of lining up, ordering at the counter, and waiting as the meal is prepared. Notably, there's an extensive array of chilled beers and cold sides available as you queue.

Ordering at the cash register was a relaxed affair; I took my time and asked numerous questions about their menu, which includes three varieties of brisket. I chose the Moist Brisket with creamed corn and a drink, totaling just over $9.

Seating is communal picnic-style, which I don't mind. Condiments are placed at the table ends, which could be inconvenient for those seated in the middle. The brisket was exceptionalâmoist, tender, and flavorful.

A large hand-washing station is available post-meal, which I appreciate given the messy nature of BBQ. It's equipped with multiple faucets and warm water, plus soap and towels are readily accessible.

I removed one star due to minor issues. The sandwich lacked BBQ sauce, which wasn't a dealbreaker as the meat was delicious on its own. However, the restaurant offers only two sauce options, and the dispensers were frustratingly difficult to operate, requiring excessive effort to extract sauce.

Despite these quirks, I highly recommend visiting. The quality of the food justifies the trip, and there's even a small shop at the front selling BBQ essentials for home use.

The light rail, which launched in December 2008, was something I eagerly awaited. Since relocating, I became a fan of the Rapid shuttle bus system, which significantly reduced my commute time and fuel expenses. The light rail offers similar benefits, providing a more convenient alternative to driving.

However, I often ponder what others expect from the light rail. I've outlined the advantages and disadvantages to help people set realistic expectations and understand what they're committing to.

Advantages:

A) It's quite affordable at $2.50 daily or $45 monthly, offering substantial savings compared to car fuel costs.

B) The trains are consistently clean and well air-conditioned.

C) While the train isn't faster than a car due to frequent stops, it's important to plan extra travel time for waiting, riding, and walking to your final destination.

D) Should you encounter any unusual situations on the train, it's crucial to contact 911 or Valley Metro immediately.

Disadvantages:

Currently, I see no downsides.

In conclusion, I use the light rail for my daily commutes to work, saving on both fuel and expensive downtown parking fees. I encourage you to try the light rail and enjoy the benefits it offers.

In December, my computer failed twice, necessitating a new purchase sooner than expected. I hadn't planned on this, hoping for another year of use. Life's unpredictability struck, and it was time to replace it.

I hadn't bought a major item from Fry's Electronics before, only minor ones occasionally. With the tech market evolving, I needed to update my knowledge of the current offerings, not just in computers but in the retail environment as well.

After comparing options at Costco and Best Buy, and visiting Fry's with a friend, I found Fry's offered the best selection and prices. I went there on a Wednesday night to take advantage of their expiring New Year's sale, deciding between two models.

The staff member assisting me was highly knowledgeable. He reviewed both models with me and advised that the performance difference didn't justify the $50 price gap, recommending the cheaper option.

After choosing, he fetched the laptop and processed my purchase. He mentioned a discount on Microsoft Office, which I declined as I don't often use Word.

His expertise greatly helped me understand more about my choices. My experience at Fry's was so positive that it has become my preferred retailer over Best Buy. Although Costco offers competitive prices and better warranties, their rapidly changing inventory makes it difficult to find the same product later.

Despite the advantages at Costco, Fry's consistent stock and helpful staff influenced my decision. I had a wonderful shopping experience and would return to Fry's for future tech purchases.

I visited this spot for breakfast on a Saturday morning and enjoyed a fairly good experience. Arriving early at 9 am, I was pleased to find no waiting time for seating. The establishment was bustling yet manageable.

The server seemed slightly overwhelmed, though I'll assume she was just busy with multiple tables, causing some delay in her service to me. It wasn't terrible, just slower than anticipated.

I chose a garden omelette with pancakes on the sideâdelicious! I appreciated the variety of syrup flavors availableâvery pleasing.

I'd definitely return and had a pleasant time. Cheers to IHOP!

After discovering this venue on Yelp, I was eager to visit. I made my way downtown and was delighted by my experience, including the chance to meet Thomas.

The website provided precise directions, which was helpful since Central was undergoing construction. It guided me effectively around the light rail work, making my journey to the restaurant convenient.

Upon entry, a friendly gentleman welcomed me and showed me to the bar area as I was dining solo. The Fez boasts stylish, modern decor with unique glass elements that create partitions in the bar and trendy light fixtures that add to the ambiance.

Choosing from the menu was tough due to the extensive selection of food and drinks, but I opted for simplicity. After consulting the attentive waiter, I settled on the American Burger, and it was a fantastic choice! The burger, served on ciabatta bread with delicious cheese and a slightly spicy mustard, was perfectly balanced in flavor and textureâa prime example of how burgers should be made.

The service continued to impress; my server replenished my drink without needing a reminder and kept my water cold, which was refreshing given the heat.

I would happily return to this spot. It's an excellent choice for a date, family outing, or a meal before an event downtown. Truly impressive!

While returning to the house where I'm pet sitting, I noticed a new Jersey Mikes. I've previously dined at other locations of this chain.

I was impressed with this branch. It offers extended operating hours and a diverse selection of subs available in various sizes, tailored to customer preferences. The staff member who assisted me was exceptionally welcoming and managed to chat as she took my order.

I chose the renowned mikes with turkey, roast beef, and all the extrasâvery delicious! I'm eager to revisit.

Having used Phoenix's Sky Harbor Airport for years, I can attest to its appeal. The airport features three terminalsâ2, 3, and 4âwith most traffic through Terminals 3 and 4, where I usually fly from. My experiences here, especially when picking up visiting family and friends, have been overwhelmingly positive.

During my latest trip from Terminal 3, I enjoyed a smooth process from drop-off to flight boarding, facilitated by a friend. The security check was swift, and the terminal offered ample dining options and free wifi, which is great for keeping my phone charged. Finding an outlet can be tricky when it's busy, but it's doable with some effort.

The availability of eateries both inside and outside the security zone is a plus, allowing for easy meals without re-entering security. I've often met friends for a quick meal before their departures and assisted my mom with navigating the airport. My dad, however, prefers finding his own way.

Rental car services are readily available, enhancing convenience upon arrival. The baggage claim process is notably fast, urging a quick move from plane to pickup. The airport also provides various ground transportation options, including taxis and shuttles.

Although I haven't used it, both on-site and more economical off-site parking are available, with regular shuttles to the terminals. The connection of the light rail to the airport is another feature I appreciate.

Sky Harbor, you're doing a fantastic job! Keep it up!

I knew about Cartel Coffee but didn't realize it had recently launched until a staff member distributed free coffee flyers at my office.

Situated conveniently by the 1st street light rail near the convention center stop (my usual exit), it operates from 7AM to 7PM. The new venue offers ample seating. The coffee menu is satisfactory, though curiously, they offer no food items like pastries or bagelsâlikely due to their recent opening. I hope they'll soon provide snacks as they settle in.

The coffee, freshly brewed per order, was outstandingâtruly impressive! The attendant was exceptionally friendly and helpful.

I'm definitely planning more visits. Great experience! Plus, there's complimentary wifi.

Before my first visit, the seed of Wildflower had already been sown. My wife, having brought home one of their Morning Glory muffins, piqued my interest. Delicious.

This experience compelled me to enter their doors, craving yet another Morning Glory muffin. During my visit, I indulged in a modest but delightful breakfast of eggs and ham, which was both tasty and affordable. Naturally, I departed with another Morning Glory muffin in hand, consuming only half at each sitting, convinced that a whole one would be quite satisfying.

Wildflower is gradually becoming a favorite of mine...

Moreover, adding another venue with free wifi to my roster is certainly a plus.

I frequent this place primarily for coffee, as I've never sampled a donut from here. They entertain me, however, since I spend a few moments completing the surveys on their receipts to receive a complimentary donut. If a donut isn't to your liking, the survey also offers a $1 discount. This was something I discovered at a different @DunkinDonuts location.

At this particular branch, though, when I order my large hot or iced coffee and present the coupon, the price drops to just .29 cents. Quite impressive.

On the other hand, this DD seems to struggle with management, based on the 6-7 times I've visited. Typically, there's an overwhelmed middle-aged man bustling about, attempting to expedite processes but only adding to the chaos, especially among the several young women working there who tend to operate at a more relaxed pace. It's somewhat entertaining, yet frustrating as the drink orders often end up incorrect.

Following my initial encounter with La Bocca during a recent Official Yelp Event, I was sufficiently impressed to warrant a return visit.

A colleague from the corporate office was in town. He, much like myself, often travels and enjoys exploring unique culinary options and discovering new locales. Consequently, I figured a trip to Mill Ave. and La Bocca would be an ideal choice.

We shared a bruschetta and a pizza, both of which were exceptional. The bruschetta offerings included: caprese with freshly pulled mozzarella - quite delightful; roasted tomato, pesto & parm - equally pleasing with its flavorful pesto; queen creek olives & ricotta - the olives were a hit!; and the highlight - prosciutto, fig & mascarpone - simply marvelous! I had previously enjoyed the fig and prosciutto pairing at a reception in Berkeley and found it delightful then as well.

We opted for the porco pizza, a fascinating mix featuring pulled pork, serrano chilies, and other delightful ingredients. The thin, roasted crust at La Bocca definitely won me over!

The service was adequate, though it seemed our server might have preferred to be elsewhere. Nonetheless, the overall experience was solid, and I plan to return.

During the Yelp event, there was a significant struggle to keep up with the demand for food, to the extent that I, along with others, found ourselves waiting by the kitchen door in hopes of securing some food before it all disappeared.

As an alternative to the typical fast food chain, NY NY is quite satisfactory. I have visited a few times, and each time, I relished my sandwich. Today's choice was a small meatball sub, priced at $4.99, accompanied by a delightful pickle spear. It's certainly worth the brief wait for food that's prepared fresh.

It surpasses Subway or Quiznos by a significant margin. The proprietor, along with the staff, appear to be very amiable and authentic.

Were it located nearer to my workplace, I would likely frequent it more.

While driving around in search of dinner options that were neither fast food nor part of a chain, my youngest daughter and I chanced upon Mimita's. We were immediately taken by the place.

Our server, Ty, provided excellent service, patiently addressing the numerous inquiries my daughter made, which helped her feel more at ease with the unfamiliar Cuban cuisine.

Our meal began with an order of papas rellenas: large, mashed potato balls stuffed with creole ground beef, lightly coated and fried to perfection. Essentially, they were delicious fried meat and potatoes.

Following that, we split a pan con lechon sandwich, consisting of pulled pork, sautÃ©ed onions, and mayo, all sandwiched in freshly baked bread. It was not only scrumptious but also sizable enough for sharing.

We concluded our meal with a shared serving of dulce de leche. Despite its modest size, the richness of the dessert made it a challenge for the two of us to finish. The flavors were a delightful blend of caramel, vanilla, and cinnamon, with a possible hint of rosewater or another subtle addition.

The total cost for our appetizer, sandwich, and dessert was quite reasonable, amounting to around $20.

Park Central Deli is passable. If you're anticipating the Kosher Style corned beef that you've enjoyed in eastern cities, you might find yourself let down. It's not that the corned beef isn't decent; it's just that it's more of a non-traditional, goyeshe varietyâa completely different type.

I tried the straw, which is akin to a Reuben. It featured an onion roll, with grilled sauerkraut and Swiss cheese atop the corned beef.

The ambiance at Park Central resembles a large cafeteria, though not in an unfavorable sense. The service is quick, and the food quality is solid. Should I find myself in the area again, I would certainly consider another lunch visit. The place boasts ample seating and a pleasant outdoor patio, complete with a Koi pond.

Ahh, @DunkinDonuts, you cunning rogue, you. Previously, my interactions with you were minimal, and I was indifferent, until my years spent around Boston. It was there that I became addicted to your so-called "crack in a cup."

My goodness, every quarter mile along route 1, your presence was unrelenting, constantly tempting with your caffeinated allure.

Thus, I grew accustomed to indulging in at least one daily "laahg regulah."

Now, having resided in the Phoenix area for three years, it's evident that you've followed me here, in a positive manner.

Therefore, it's genuinely pleasant to witness your expansion into the remote areas of the Phoenix region, @DunkinDonutsPHX.

Just remember, it all comes down to the coffee.

Behold the mighty deities of Cafetopolis, whom you observe,

Under whose command, figures like Paneracles and Chipotle have constructed realms from one ocean to another,

They yearn for offerings akin to those found beyond the Acropolis,

Where cafeterias offer dishes such as Gyro, among various others,



The meals were suitable for the aforementioned group,

Earning merely two stars, yet the service was as smooth as silk,

The dolomades were tough, yet the hummus proved flavorful,

Spanakopita arrived crispy, perhaps due to the chefs' rush,

Falafel was molded in the likeness of tater-tots,

Yet, internally, they were doughy and disappointing,



The salad was devoid of olives, save for a mere smear,

The feta cheese was scant and lacked any sharp taste,

Drachmas depleted swiftly as soon as the meal was requested,

A higher caliber of Greek cuisine could have justified the expense.

I might be inclined to rate this place at 3.25 stars. Last night marked my initial visit to this establishment, where I noticed a large banner announcing, "Any 12" Pizza $12."

When it comes to ordering pizza, my preferences are specific:

a. A delicious, NY-style pie. The best I've encountered in the valley are from Grimaldi's and Mama Mia, known for their thin crusts, sparse toppings, and delicious taste.
b. A "regular" pizza, heavily topped. Often, it's joked that my pizza resembles a salad bar, which can become quite costly. Hence, the deal advertised on the banner seemed appealing.

Consequently, I stopped by and opted for a takeaway pizza with three toppings. It was decent: the crust had a medium thickness, the sauce was gentle, neither too sour nor too sweet, and the toppings were generous, with the cheese perfectly browned. It was enjoyable.

However, my initial delight turned to slight disappointment upon discovering that they were part of a chain. This sparked an immediate concern of receiving a Peter Piper or Little Ceasar's style pizza, though, fortunately, it proved to be significantly superior.
Primate.

Make your way to Pop the Soda Shop, where it serves as your ultimate destination for all the soda you desire to drink.

At Pop the Soda Shop, the knowledgeable staff is well-versed in their inventory. Should there be a soda they do not carry, they will surely guide you to where it can be found.

Craving Capt. Eli's Root Beer? It's available. How about Fukola Cola? It's ready and cold. Olde Brooklyn Birch Beer? Indeed. Maine Root Sarsaparilla? Would you care to try it right away? Buderim Aussie Style Ginger Brew? Absolutely. Taylor's Tonic's Cola Azteca? Delicious. Pink Love Potion # 69? Try not to consume it too quickly...

Interested in Manhattan Special Espresso Soda? Certainly. Fentimans Mandarin and Seville Orange Jigger? It's said to be quite refreshing. Perhaps a White Rock Organic Red Peach? That sounds appealing. Zuberfizz Vanilla Cream Soda? We have it as well. In the mood for something herbal? Consider the Kombucha Wonder Drink. The Unknown Dread offers a unique take on energy drinks...

As is evident, their selection is diverse.

I'll start with the essentials: Sprouts guarantees that its products are free from antibiotics, hormones, and bovine by-products are not included in their cattle feedâand, it's more affordable than Whole Foods.

What a delightful establishment! The team there was exceptionally welcoming and accommodating. The first staff member we engaged in conversation with provided us with a wealth of information regarding the history of Sprouts, Whole Foods, and Wild Oats in the region. Additionally, there was a conversation about the mergers involving Wild Oats and Food Whole, as well as union busting efforts at a Food Whole location in San Francisco.

In any case, I'm fond of this neighborhood market. The prices for produce are quite reasonable, there's a wide selection, and the shopping atmosphere is calm and straightforward to navigate.

Should you decide to visit Sala Thai on a Sunday, and you're planning to meet others, it's wise to note that traffic tends to be lighter, allowing you to arrive earlier. Upon arriving early, you might discover a Big Lots nearby, where you can briefly immerse yourself in a distinctly gritty ambiance, or choose to skip it, as I would advise. Alternatively, you could follow the example set by our dining companions and stop by a local dive bar for a pre-dinner drink, especially since Sala Thai does not offer alcoholic beverages. I eagerly anticipate Christine's thoughts on this experience, no pressure intended.

My anticipation for dining at Sala Thai was high after reading several glowing reviews, and indeed, the restaurant lived up to expectations.

Our meal commenced with pork satay, an unusual offering that proved to be the least impressive dish of the evening. The pork was somewhat tough, and the accompanying yellow curry did not complement it well.

The four entrees we shared included a spicy basil fried rice, which I found particularly enjoyable and hope to revisit soon. Its perfect blend of spice and fresh basil offered a refreshing taste. The catfish with panang curry was also a standout, being the largest fillet I've encountered, lightly seared to achieve a crispy exterior while keeping the inside moist and tender. It came heavily seasoned, and we chose a four out of five on the spice scale, which nearly induced sneezes from us all at first taste. I'm curious about the level five spiciness, though four was already quite intense.

Additionally, we tried the pad thai, a dish I generally use as a standard for comparison. Sala Thai's version was notably unique and satisfying, not too sweet and subtly smoky, adding complexity to the dish. Completing our culinary journey was a duck curry, enriched with coconut milk, red chili paste, pineapple, basil, tomato, and onion. Despite not typically enjoying duck, I found this preparation to be very tasty, having several pieces along with a generous amount of sauce over my rice.

I endorse Sala Thai enthusiastically. The sauces were so rich in flavor that Myles M and I nearly shocked Christine O and Audrey W by almost licking every serving dish clean.

I've never really been a frequent shopper at Big Lots, not at any point. Recently, having a few spare minutes while in the area, I opted to explore this particular Big Lots. The store is quite large, featuring a diverse, somewhat eclectic mix of various items.

During my visit, I managed to purchase several items, which turned out to be quite the bargain. I would estimate that roughly 15-20% of their merchandise is offered at a great price, while the remainder tends to be of average cost, subpar quality, or both. It seems this is the typical outcome when purchasing large, assorted batches of merchandise.

We opted to stay here in November, which, as it turns out, is an excellent time to secure a favorable rate; naturally, the expenses were covered by my employer, yet it was still noteworthy.

The personnel were exceptional, and the lodging facilities quite appealing. The property boasts an array of attractive features: a pool, multiple hot tubs, a water slide, among others. Particularly remarkable is the hot tub positioned atop the cliff, adjacent to a smaller pool, offering a splendid experience. The resort's location, moderately distanced from nearby attractions, allows for serene late-night visits (there was an evening when my family enjoyed exclusive access to the pool and hot tub) to bask in the desert ambiance and gaze at the stars.

The morning meal provided here was superb. Regrettably, I'm unaware of its cost since it was provided at no charge. The location is conveniently close to the downtown area.

I've interacted with this team three times, and each experience has been outstanding.

During my visits to Lowe's, I encountered the following issues:

a. They lacked the necessary blanks for several keys I required,
b. The copies they made of the keys were ineffective.

Consequently, I turned to the local locksmith I trust, where each key was crafted to perfection, including those labeled as "manufacturer only" for which there wasn't an exact blank. Nevertheless, they managed to meticulously trim a similar blank and successfully create the keys.

Now, I exclusively rely on them. There's no point in looking elsewhere.

Yupha's has recently relocated to a new spot on Elliot, now situated directly adjacent to Tempe Cinemas. Who's up for dinner and a movie?

Our meal began with two starters: one was delightful, the other quite ordinary. The Chicken Satay stood out, featuring succulent, tender chicken infused with a delightful yellow curry scent and taste. Conversely, the Little Mermaid appetizer, consisting of shrimp and bacon encased in spring roll wrappers, failed to meet our flavor expectations.

For our main courses, we opted for Pad Thai and Panang Curry. The Pad Thai impressed us with its vibrant, fresh flavors. We chose a mild version of the Panang Curry, combining chicken and beef, to accommodate the children. Although it had a slight kick, it was mild enough not to induce sweatingâstill, it was predominantly rich in coconut milk flavor. The curry was pleasant, yet it lacked some complexity. It included plenty of string beans, which were undercooked and overly crisp, seemingly added at the last moment. The dish also contained a few slices of red pepper and a couple of lime leaves.

The service was commendable, with 4-5 staff members attending to us frequently, and my water glass was only empty onceâa notable feat given my high water consumption.

The ambiance of the restaurant was welcoming and airy, showcasing a clean, modern interpretation of Thai decor, which I found quite appealing.

I'll take the lead in adding to the heap of feedback for Casey Moore's, marking it as review number 72!

When it comes to enjoying drinks with pals, I'd rate it 4 stars. The ambiance is inviting, the crowd varied, and they offer an excellent selection of draughts, including my top pick, the Four Peaks Scottish Amber. Additionally, the outdoor seating is superb.

On the dining front, they earn 3 stars from me. It's been a few months since my departure from New England, and my first foray into seafood at Casey Moore's came with tempered hopes. Despite this, my Fish & Chips ($11.00, featuring Cod instead of the usual, more generous Haddock) turned out quite satisfying. The fish was delicately battered, perfectly moist, tender, and juicy. The accompanying chips were skin-on fries.

My wife opted for the Salmon Oscar. Unfortunately, the salmon was a tad overcooked, and both the crab and hollandaise sauce were somewhat overly fishy. She also had a double-cooked baked potato which bore an uncanny resemblance to the pre-made twice-baked potatoes included in a set of Omaha Steaks gifted by my boss last Christmas. Additionally, there were lightly seasoned, sautÃ©ed slices of zucchini and yellow squash.

The service was exceptional, with our waitress providing honest advice, such as steering clear of the Surf & Turf due to infrequent lobster sales and inconsistent preparation in the kitchen, leading to occasional returns. She helpfully suggested the Salt Cellar for top-notch Fish & Chips.

In summary, I'd award them 3 stars and wouldn't hesitate to revisit for some Fish & Chips and a round of drinks.

I appreciate and have confidence in Dr. Ganem, and plan to remain his patient as long as I reside in this vicinity, or at least while he remains covered by my insurance.

His approach to communication is both laid-back and straightforward, which I find extremely appealing. Throughout my numerous appointments with Dr. Ganem and his team, my experiences have generally been positive, and I would certainly suggest his services.

However, at this juncture, I am reducing the rating from 5 stars due to what seems to be a minor mishap in how prescriptions and samples are handled by the office's support staff. This led to me taking a medication that had unwanted side effects, a medication that evidently was not the optimal choice for my condition.

Are you joking? Seriously.

If subpar cuisine combined with explicit content being blatantly displayed appeals to you, this is your spot. Seriously.

We would have avoided this establishment had we known beforehand. Seriously.

Some corporate executives visiting the city decided to treat several of us from the office to a meal here. That's an hour of my existence I will never reclaim. Seriously.

This establishment makes Hooters appear highly sophisticated and elegant. Seriously.

Regarding the menu, enormous burgers and fries are your sole options. The burgers? Imagine Encore Frozen Salisbury Steaks served on a bun. Seriously.

Upon departure, we collectively concurred that we would never revisit this establishment. 

Seriously.

In my opinion, awarding 2 stars might even seem overly generous. The service was decent, and the televisions functioned properly.

I opted for the mushroom Swiss sliders. Had I not been pressed for time, I would have definitely returned them. They were tough, resembled leather, and were excessively overcooked, nearly reaching the point of being burnt. I managed to consume only one and a half of these sliders; my dog will enjoy the remainder.

Both my wife and daughter chose the standard burgers and agreed that a 2-star rating was appropriate for their meals as well.

Just because the establishment is a sports bar does not mean it's acceptable to offer subpar food, you know...

Jared: "Greetings at Subway! Did you catch my ad with Michael Strahan?"

Me: "Uh...yes?"

Jared: "Would you be interested in trying a sandwich on our new rosemary sea salt bread?"

Me: "Sure, that actually sounds quite appealing. What is Michael Strahan like?"

Jared: "He's pretty cool. We've been collaborating on Subway ads, not really hanging out or anything."

Me: "Understood. I'll take the meatball marinara with provolone, please."

"Perhaps you might consider pepper jack instead?"

"No, I prefer provolone with the meatball sandwich. Pepper jack suits the tuna better. They really should use less mayo in that tuna, though."

"I'll mention it to them. Would you like your sub toasted?"

"Yes. And you'll inform them? The...Subway team?"

"Yes, we've shared some challenging times. They'll listen to me."

"So, they won't listen to me? What kind of tough times are you referring to?"

"Well, you're a customer. I'm deeply committed here."

"A deep commitment? So, is working at Subway like a life sentence for you?"

"Not exactly, it's more about being dedicated long-term."

"So, you're essentially bonded to, uh, the Subway folks? What do you call them privately? Do you ever make inappropriate jokes about sandwiches? Because that would be inappropriate."

"No, nothing of the sort. What toppings would you like?"

"Black olives, tomatoes, onions, and spinach. Are you embarrassed by this relationship? Because it seems quite public now, especially with the ads and all. But let's return to the difficult periods. What were they?"

"No, I'm not embarrassed. You see, I lost weight, made a commercial, then another...you know the drill."

"Actually, no, I don't know the drill. I'm still waiting on my first endorsement deal...I suppose. How does it work? Is it addictive? Did you turn to subs heavily after a breakup? Was Subway a second choice for you? Have you heard the saying 'You can settle for second best, but it's hard to get enough'? Is that what happened here?"

"No! Look, do you want any mayo or other dressings on your sub?"

"My sub?"

"Apologies, I'm really sorry about that. Do you?"

"No. And about those hard times? Hmm?"

"Would you like to add a drink to make it a combo?"

"No. Wait, does the combo come with a brief tale about Jared and Subway's past difficulties?"

"No. You know, there was a time when we were quite sparing with our toppings. Just a single strand of onion or pepper, a thin slice of tomato. It wasn't a proud era for us."

"Yes, I recall those days. I'd order a veggie sub and the server would delicately place a single strand of green pepper and a thin slice of onion on my sandwich. I'd ask for 'more,' and he'd reluctantly add another strand. When I insisted on 'MORE,' he'd finally add a few more strands with a pained look. Yes, those were indeed tough times."

"Right. Thanks for visiting Subway!"

"Sure. Please let the, um, Subway team know that the improvements are noticeable, okay? The bread is better, the toppings are more plentiful and of higher quality, and you're still working on being less stingy, right?"

"Yes, I'll make sure to pass that along."

"Great. And could I have two napkins with my sandwich, please? Thanks."

Huauchinango!

Situated approximately 130 miles away from Mexico City, nestled in the Sierra Norte de Pueblo mountains, Huauchinango is not only a city but also a delightful, budget-friendly Mexican eatery that I frequent with ease.

It is said that the food served at Huauchinango closely mirrors the culinary style of Mexico City.

During my initial visit (my only one to date, though I plan to return), I indulged in three quesadillas. These were not the ordinary quesadillas we prepare at home; instead, they were exuberant, neatly folded enclosures filled with beef, chicken, and shrimp, complemented by cheese, mushrooms, onions, and other delectable ingredients.

The chips and salsa served at the beginning were impressive. Prepared on-site, the chips were notably non-greasy. Accompanying them were three types of salsa. The first was a green chili tomatillo salsa, vibrant and mildly spicy with a fresh taste. The second, a red chili salsa, was initially somewhat watery but had a robust red chili finish and contained very little tomato. The third salsa, smooth and orange-colored, was identified as habanero salsa, predominantly made from finely blended roasted habaneros. Quite fiery, indeed.

Special thanks to Donald S for his review that brought this gem to my attention, and for joining me along with Brian S for a memorable lunch. Exceptional!

During my initial visit to El Pollo Loco, I discovered that chicken is not considered meat. Consider this conversation:

"May I please have two hard tacos with only cheese, lettuce, tomato, and beans?"

"Two chicken crunchy tacos with cheese, lettuce, tomato, and beans only?"

"No, I'd like two crunchy tacos without meat, containing only cheese, lettuce, tomato, and beans."

"You're not wanting any meat on the tacos?"

"Correct, I'm looking for vegetarian tacos, just cheese, lettuce, tomato, and beans."

"So, just cheese, lettuce, tomato, and beans?"

"Yes, no meat, just cheese, lettuce, tomato, and beans, please."

*approaches window, completes payment, drives off.

*returns to window, returns bag to staff.

"Is there an issue?"

"Yes, these tacos contain chicken."

"Yes, we typically include chicken in them."

"But I specified no meat."

"Chicken is considered differently, though."

"May I get a refund?"

"You don't want them?"

"That's right, I would prefer a refund, please."

I absolutely adore this quaint bar! I must admit, my amazing wife played the role of designated driver tonight and effortlessly helped me out of the car after our outing.

We had a fantastic time at the delightful gathering organized by either Donald or Michael. It's always a pleasure to mingle with fellow Yelpers and relax a bit.

I acknowledge that my review might not meet my usual standards, as reviewing while tipsy offers a fresh perspective on critiques, doesn't it?

The service here is excellent, the drinks are potent, and I'm genuinely astonished by how affordable it is to get tipsy at Brackin's!

Tomorrow morning, I'll revisit this and decide whether it's suitable for posting.

Michael, what was that last drink I had, the one with the grape flavor?

*Morning* - What fun times.

Before reaching our designated seating, we had already begun to indulge in the roasted peanuts scattered abundantly throughout the establishment. These peanuts were perfectly roasted, achieving an ideal balance of saltiness.

Upon being seated, we were promptly served with steaming hot rolls, straight from the oven. Their heat and freshness were such that handling them was a challenge. Accompanying these rolls was butter, kept at room temperature and subtly enhanced with a hint of cinnamon-sugar, of which I partook in two.

For my side dish, I opted for a Caesar salad, a selection that proved to be quite pleasing. The dressing was tastefully seasoned, avoiding the excessive fishiness often associated with Caesar dressings.

I chose to order a Blue Moon ale, available on tap, and found it to be a satisfyingly full-bodied lager.

As the main course was served, I savored my second side, the baked beans, which, although a bit heavy on the BBQ sauce, were rich with hearty beans and ample, tasty pork chunks.

Additionally, a generous portion of ribs, totaling about 16 bones, was served. I managed to consume one of these.

It was both tender and scrumptious. The remainder of the ribs I plan to enjoy tomorrow.

I had been intending to pen this critique for quite some time. The initiation of a discussion thread concerning the scarcity of health care critiques on Yelp provided the impetus I required.

Since relocating to Arizona, Dr. Madder and his team have been my sole providers of dental health care. They are amiable, professional, and render the experience of visiting the dentist almost enjoyable.

I wouldn't claim that I eagerly anticipate dental visits, but they are definitely devoid of stress with this group.

Dr. Madder, Tish, and the remaining team members dedicate time to ensure your comfort, and they meticulously explain each step of the process, from procedures to billing.

This should be considered an endorsement from Jim W of Dr. Madder's dental office.

I consumed a shaggy dog at @mauidogs, or perhaps it was a fuzzy one. I believe it was shaggy. It was topped with slaw and a variety of other ingredients, and I thoroughly enjoyed it. I'm tempted to have another one immediately, and I certainly would, were I not currently penning this from a hotel in California.

I indulged in a spam slider as well, which was equally delightful. It's been ages since I last had spam, quite a long time indeed.

I'm fond of this establishmentâthe cuisine, the folks, the atmosphere...nunui!

'Oe pono he ekahi!

http://hawaiiandictionary.hisurf.com/

Created entirely from scratch, utilizing only fundamental components, without the inclusion of any pre-made elements.

Here, I encountered exceptional desserts and a delightful cappuccino. However, my desire is to come back for breakfast, lunch, dinner, and dessert once more. Yet, I suspect that merely breathing the air in this establishment might have added some calories to my count â such is the nature of bakery air.

The desserts, albeit costly, are irresistibly delicious, crafted with meticulous attention, gentleness, and love â and, of course, sugar.

I participated in a Yelp Elite gathering at this location, and the seafood left me utterly astonished. Having resided and spent considerable time in numerous coastal regions, my standards for seafood have inevitably lowered since moving to the desert.

Have no fear!

The oysters alone will certainly bring me back to this place! Not to mention the jumbo shrimp, fresh tuna, and crab cakes.

The previous occasion I found crab cakes this delightful, I could detect the scent of the Atlantic.

The last instance I enjoyed oysters of such quality, I could sense the aroma of the Pacific.

Occasionally, I find myself visiting Chick-Fil-A, one of the fast food establishments I prefer. Why, you might ask? It's because their nuggets, strips, and fries don't leave me feeling nauseous, greasy, or heavy, unlike what often happens after eating at BK, MCD, or many other similar places.

Moreover, I'm quite fond of their waffle fries. I do wish, however, that Chick-fil-A offered some cheese sauce to accompany those fries. That would be delicious.

The quality of their food has consistently been reliable. Thus, even though the offerings at Chick-fil-A might be somewhat bland, they are at least palatable and don't cause any discomfort.

Hooray for the diner! It earns four stars in its category, offering simple meals at reasonable costs, and the service includes a bit of friendly banter.

Additionally, the decor is quintessentially diner-style, albeit with a unique Indiana twist.

The prices are reasonable, aligning with typical diner fare. My experiences here have mostly involved breakfast options such as omelets and scrambled eggs, which might not seem varied, but they're always accompanied by bacon, potatoes, and toast. It's consistently reliable.

Cheer for the Hoosiers! And what exactly is a Hoosier? To my knowledge, it refers to a type of kitchen furniture, specifically a cabinet that includes a small counter space. Cheers to kitchen cabinetry!

Recently, some colleagues from the headquarters visited - one to conduct our yearly operational review, and another to evaluate the regional marketing strategies we are implementing. They expressed a desire to dine locally, thus...

We found ourselves at Trader Vic's. The ambiance was delightful, characterized by luxurious, island-inspired decor and a pleasing texture. The staff welcomed us warmly, and we enjoyed some cocktails and light fare at the bar before proceeding to our meal. The cocktails were delightful, and the appetizer, dubbed "tidbits for two," ranged from enjoyable to bland.

We then transitioned to the main dining area. On this particular Thursday evening, the restaurant was notably empty, lacking patrons. I opted for one of the evening's specials, a dish featuring Thai-style noodles with curry, assorted seafood, peanuts, and a hint of mild pepper â a concoction so forgettable that I can scarcely recall its intended flavor profile. It was overly complex, yet failed to leave a lasting impression.

Regarding the satisfaction of our group, it appeared that the meal was a hit for some but not for others. To clarify, among the four of us, I was disappointed, and only two out of the remaining three enjoyed their meals, which indicates that half of us were not impressed. This brings to mind a hypothetical scenario where if Trader Vic's were a train traveling at 75 mph over a distance of 160 miles...oh, that seems to be a digression into a childhood math problem.

In summary, Trader Vic's offers a somewhat intriguing ambiance with a touch of historical interest (I believe it was once owned by Merv Griffin), yet the culinary experience is merely average and comes at a high cost. Additionally, the restrooms were notably well-maintained.

La Condesa, my heart was captured by you. Indeed, a Gourmet Taco Shop. Your flavorful molÃ© was simply irresistible.

Your expertise in enhancing a relationship with an array of exquisite salsas is evident.

The warmth of your decor and the even warmer service were truly appreciated.

I am eager to return, eager to delve into more of your salsas, and eager to taste additional tacos.

It was only about a month ago that I first visited, gathering with friends during a trip to Phoenix, and more recently, I reunited with another friend there.

Gourmet street tacos for $3.99 each. Satisfying. Around 20 varieties of salsas. Utterly scrumptious.

Greetings, my cherished companion! How fares the delightful Buffy today? Well, well, it's heartening to learn she's on the mend from that ghastly abrasion she suffered on the tennis court's harsh surface. Horrible, indeed!

Could it be that Jim W is a member of a country club? The very idea! Could Jim W possibly dine at the club's eatery, Bolero's, utilizing a buy-one-get-one-free offer? Absolutely!

I perceived the interior dining space as somewhat oppressive, and dare I say, slightly ostentatious? Maybe. Why don't we enjoy our meal outdoors on the terrace? Yes, let's do that. The panorama of San Tan Mountain is particularly breathtaking at this time of year, wouldn't you agree?

The service was commendable, albeit in a somewhat ingratiating manner. If the notion of being overly pampered appeals to you because you might be considered important (a term worth looking up here: http://www.koshernosh.com/dictiona.htm), then the attention here might just suit your taste.

I chose a cheeseburger with fries. The fries were a bit of a letdown, being thin, lightly coated, and nothing special. The burger, however, was quite satisfying. The ambiance was quite appealing.

Alright, a lunch at the Country Club, experienced it, got the t-shirt.

Warning: Exceptional 5-star burger spot! Competitive prices, amiable staff!

Am I raising my voice?

Oh, apologies. It seems I often engage the "caps lock" when wearing headphones.

Recently, I enjoyed a meal here alongside my delightful wife, our youngest daughter, and my companion, Donald S (distinct from Don Sâa common mix-up).

I must express, the burger and fries I ordered were remarkable. The fries were smothered in cheese and topped with bacon, while the burger was both tender and succulently cooked to perfection.

The Italian beef sandwich that Donald had looked so tempting, I plan to order it myself on my next visit to Lobby's, which will likely be very soon, perhaps even for dinner tonight.

During our visit, we had the opportunity to converse with the proprietor, Lobby. He's a genuinely pleasant fellow running a fantastic local enterprise. Highly recommend visiting this place.

Until yesterday, I had never tried dim sum! My amazing wife, Audrey W, was there to enjoy this new experience with me, along with Dottsy Z, Donald S, Marian, and Kevin H. Dottsy even took some pictures! And, surprisingly, the cost was quite low!

It was the finest dim sum I've ever tasted, and truthfully, the only one I've ever tried! I'm thrilled that I was accompanied by other experienced yelpers who helped make my first time memorable.

Phoenix Palace offers exceptionally good dim sum. I savored almost everything I sampled, which featured a wide array and consistent high quality. I wasn't as bold as some of the seasoned diners at our table, opting to skip a dish that included tripe. Perhaps I wasn't quite prepared for that.

Lately, there's been a noticeable uptick in reviews. Rumor has it there's been a shift in ownership, management, or maybe they've brought in a new chef â or perhaps it's a combination of these changes. I'm not certain, but it was definitely enjoyable.

The bill for six people, with plenty of food, came to just under $70. Absolutely astonishing.

Phoenix Palace is a fantastic choice for a dim sum lunch, offering both great variety and value. Conveniently located in the same parking lot as Lee Lee Oriental Supermarket, it's perfect for a meal before shopping, which helps lessen spending. It's always wise to eat before shopping to avoid buying more than necessary.

This establishment presents an Island-inspired theme, similar to Tokyo Joe's and comparable venues.

I sampled a pulled pork sandwich accompanied by "rumbi fries," a blend of standard pencil fries and crinkle-cut sweet potato fries. The pork was fairly tasty, though a tad on the dry side, and it possessed a subtle smoky essence.

The fries were enjoyable, yet I would prefer them without the coating found on the sweet potato friesâor any fries, for that matter. The dish was complemented by a delightful BBQ sauce and, in true Salt Lake City fashion, fry sauce.

Dining outdoors, one can appreciate the local sparrows that boldly chirp for crumbs if you feed them once and then cease for a while. It was surprising to see a bird, scarcely larger than a ketchup packet, so eagerly plead for scraps of my meal.

Illuminating and invigorating! This past Saturday evening, we sampled Fresco (along with bingsoo) for our initial experience. Did I point out how airy and invigorating it was?

The team here truly values the quality of their offerings. They serve airy, invigorating (have I already highlighted this?) frozen yogurt, topped with meticulously cut fresh fruit, all resting on a bed of delicately shaved ice, finished with a mango glaze. It's both light and refreshing, and significantly healthier than DQ.

We plan to return soon to enjoy more and to sample the boba.

Last evening, we opted for Classic Italian Pizza for our meal. We began with an Aglio Olio appetizer and selected two pizzas. The starter was exceptionally tasty; it featured a base of pumpkin seed oil, incorporated freshly minced garlic, and included a touch of fresh jalapeno for some added zest.

Don't we all benefit from a little zest in our daily routines?

I chose a prosciutto pizza and asked for kalamata olives on top. It was so delicious that, after receiving the bill and having my leftovers packed, I couldn't resist opening the box to sneak another piece as I awaited the server's return.

Of the four slices that survived the journey home, none remained by morning.

Copper Star, an excellent, independent cafÃ©, deserves your financial support. Do it now, swiftly, as I remain here at Copper Star, utilizing their complimentary Wi-Fi and contemplating the purchase of one of their T-shirts.

The ambiance here appeals to me; it exudes a raw, masculine, straightforward vibe. The surrounding area is transitioning from somewhat questionable to fashionably chic.

My delightful iced coffee is nearly finished, and they have just removed the plate from the cupcake I just enjoyed.

I plan to return. Gabi is hosting Yelp office hours here, and I'm considering attending.

Critique Noir

On such evenings, every social gathering with drinks inevitably escalated into brawls. That night, a desert breeze swept through the avenues, a scorching zephyr that tugged relentlessly at your attire, causing the hairs on your nape to bristle. The roads lay more silent than a deceased feline nestled beside the guardrail on a moon-drenched mountain pass.

Adorned in my olive drab shorts and a black "Kill Your Television" tee, my sobriety was apparent, and I was indifferent to who noticed. I embodied the quintessential post-work regional manager, and my visit was to Best of Italy. She was precise, enchanting, yet merciless with her portion sizes. My mood resembled that of a child who delights in tormenting spiders, devoid of any more moral sense than an oppressed pup.

"She's a con artist," a voice in my head sharply declared. Perhaps she was, I pondered, but what was her angle with this five-dollar deal? Beneath the allure and the grin, could there be nothing but venom beneath that topping? I needed answers, even if it risked eternal rest by dawn.

Sampling her pizza slices, I found them delightful. Indeed, they transcended mere tastiness, embodying a profound veracity. It's that particular truth I refer toâthe one that heightens your consciousness, making you realize the world is at the disposal of men like us, men who believe they are entitled to exceptional pizza. Such pizza. It's a truth that convinces you the world would indeed be a more vibrant place, far from mundane, if only there were more pizzas like this one. Now, you're intertwined with itâ the crust, the sauce, the cheese, the toppingsâthey've become a part of you, and there's no turning back.

Today marked my first encounter with Bosa Donuts. By a stroke of luck, we timed our arrival perfectly, just as a batch of donuts was completing its enchanting transformation in the mystical realms of Oiliverse and Sugartopoliis. They emerged hot, fresh, and utterly scrumptious.

For those with a refined palate for donuts, allow me to draw some comparisons. The freshly made Bosa glazed donut is a formidable rival to Krispy Kreme's version. It boasts a thinner sugary layer, a larger size, and a slightly more doughy texture. Indeed, the doughiness of the Bosa donut bears a resemblance to the kind you might encounter at a state fair, albeit not as dense.

When compared to Dunkin' Donuts' glazed offering, the Bosa donut stands out significantly. It is noticeably fresher and has a more wholesome flavor than any glazed donut I've sampled from Dunkin'.

The physical premises of the store, however, do not project an aura of cleanliness or instill much confidence regarding the sanitation of the preparation areas. At times, one must rely solely on faith and the assurances of the local Health Department.

The level of service provided was comparable to that of any other establishment in the same industry.

Absolutely refrain. I repeat, refrain!

This critique pertains solely to the Chinese Fast Food section located at the store's entrance, which operates in a manner akin to Panda Express. We do appreciate the store itself.

Refrain, once more!

In search of a quick, effortless meal for dinner, we unfortunately decided to try this place. If my earlier warnings were not clear enough, refrain from dining here.

After bringing our meals home, we sampled and nibbled at the food. I even consumed a bit and found myself regretting it the following morning. The rice was parched, and the cubed vegetables mixed within were overly dry. The spicy chicken was indeed spicy but also greasy and not fresh. On the whole, both the freshness and the quality were subpar, with the freshness being notably deficient. Refrain!

Moreover, while the store's staff and the manager were amiable, and the manager kindly issued a refund this morning, I endorse the store but advise against the Chinese prepared meals.

To conclude, here's a summary: I advise against the Chinese cuisine offered here. You probably expected another refrain, didnât you?

This was my first time stepping into a Safeway since I moved away from New England, and overall, it was a fairly pleasant experience. The store was lively, celebrating a recent renovation on what turned out to be a bustling Saturday.

I approached a notably tall woman, reminiscent of a WNBA player, adorned with a lengthy, glittering rhinestone belt, and inquired about the location of the bakery. She thought it best to personally guide us there.

In my time, I've been escorted off various properties, led to restrooms, and even been "warned and sent, copy, over." However, being escorted to a bakery was a first for me.

We decided against purchasing the croissant we initially wanted, as they were only available in packs. Instead, we chose some doughnuts and made a stop at Starbucks before leaving. The doughnuts came at a reduced price, but only with a Safeway card. The cashier wouldn't scan a generic card or apply the discount without entering my details into their system. Ah yes, this reminded me of the reasons I stopped shopping at Safeway. Fortunately, the woman in line behind us kindly offered her number so we could avail of the discount.

In my view, Safeway continues to rank low among grocery store chains.

Rate this as 3.5 stars.

Here's the situation: The service excels, the ambiance is appealing both indoors and outdoors, and the dishes are tasty. The pricing? They're somewhat steep for the quality of the meals.

The accompanying sides outshone the main course, which is why it doesn't reach 4 stars, particularly given that main courses cost between $20 and $25.

My meal was a chicken breast, coated in panko, drenched in a tomatillo and cream sauce, and adorned with bacon, goat cheese, pico de gallo (comprising fresh onion, tomato, cilantro, etc.), and crispy tortilla strips. Honestly, the flavors of the chicken, bacon, and goat cheese, which I was most excited about, were overwhelmed. They got lost amidst the tomatillo, cream, salsa, and tortilla strips. This dish attempted too much and was the worse for it. The chicken ended up being a jack-of-all-trades, but a master of none.

The side dishesâa cornbread casserole and spicy mashed potatoesâwere quite delicious.

In conclusion, the meal was good but not exceptional, and when spending $21 on a chicken breast, I expect to be thoroughly impressed.

VSC has long been on my list of places to sample, but it was somewhat distant. Not as distant as Vermont, perhaps, but still, noticeably remote.

At VSC, the sandwiches are prepared similarly to how I make them at home: they're layered, feature a variety of intriguing flavors that blend well, and are made with high-quality components.

However, I don't have to prepare them myself; someone at VSC takes care of that for me.

This is the reason I wish VSC were nearer to my residence.

The interior design also strongly resembles that of Vermont. Indeed, if a Westfalia were parked outside, the effect would be utterly convincing. In fact, I've received directions in Vermont before that included a phrase like, "...take a right at the second Westfalia."

At Citizen Pub House, the esteemed Mixologist Richie Moe crafted some fiery beverages that left the entire bar in awe during a bustling Saturday evening. Upon learning that it was our anniversary, Richie expressed his desire to concoct a unique drink for us, mentioning his inclination to set something ablaze.

The final concoction resembled bananas foster served in a shot glass. The process included melting Mexican chocolate in a metal mixer, igniting 160 proof black strap rum, and Richie skillfully transferring a flaming blend of orange liquid with blue flames between cups in an arc, captivating all onlookers.

The drink was as spectacular as the performance that preceded it.

Having visited CPH on two occasions, we enjoyed both the exceptional food and the remarkable beverages each time. Whenever I crave a cocktail, this establishment is my preferred destination. Should you feel the urge for some drinks and a snack, consider this your go-to spot. Delight in it.

Before Jim W introduced him to Yelp, the proprietor of China King, Michael, was unaware of its existence. Michael is known for his warm, conversational nature, so expect a friendly chat if you engage him.

The service at this establishment was outstanding. A number of staff attended to us diligently, with Maggie, our main server, proving to be particularly delightful.

Opting for the American-style offerings, my wife and children chose dishes such as sweet and sour chicken, shrimp in white sauce, and garlic beef, all accompanied by soup, an egg roll, and rice. I tried the garlic beef, which was enhanced with a kung pao brown sauceâa choice made after a lengthy discussion between Maggie and my wife. It boasted a rich taste, and the vegetables were both fresh and tasty. The shrimp, too, were tender, and their white sauce was notably more unique than what is typically found at many Chinese eateries.

I selected a less adventurous item from the traditional menu, a sizzling plate with scallops and shrimp in black pepper sauce, which I found quite satisfying. The shrimp were again tender, and the scallops were flavorful. Having moved from Boston, where I had tempered my seafood expectations, I was pleasantly surprised to find the scallops in Phoenix to be some of the freshest and most carefully prepared I've encountered.

In summary, China King provided an exceptionally fresh and delicious meal. Their extensive traditional menu is something I am eager to delve into more in the future.

Christine Oâs glowing review was what led me to try China King, and I can confidently say it met my expectations.

Wow! The top French fries in the city! They're genuine, fresh-cut with the skin intact, and they have the ideal balance of crispness and greasiness! Their burgers are incredibly delicious, made from freshly cooked, pure beef. This establishment has existed for 57 years and has only changed hands four times during that period. The staff are really friendly and the service is excellent, too!

Okay, I seldom make trips to Old Town for dining. Very seldom. My usual spot is CenPho. However, when Chef Bec extends an invitation to sample some dishes, you simply have to accept. Immediately!

I chose to sit at the bar, as it was Friday and that seems to be the preferred spot for many. I was there with Kirti for happy hour, just to relax. The service was excellent (I hardly ever needed to request a refill), and the chef even made an appearance to introduce herself. The venue wasn't overly packed yet, which was fortunate, for it meant more attention for us. It kept the staff on their toes!

The first dish we sampled was the ribs appetizer. The ribs were tender, falling right off the bone, and they were coated in an exceptionally sticky-spicy-sweet sauce. We also enjoyed the crab dip, served with plantain chips â and I absolutely adore plantain chips. Truly adore them.

The pork tacos? Absolutely mind-blowing. I ended up taking a few home as leftovers, and found myself salivating all night long just thinking about them.

For dessert, we indulged in "crack pie." I'm not sure of the ingredients, but the pie had a nutty crust, was topped with whipped cream, and it clung to my teeth as I ate. It must have been made with actual crack! The red velvet cupcake was heavenly too, but that crack pie... just wow.

Finding parking in Old Town is always a hassle, but fortunately, there's a garage close to The Herb Box.

As someone who is deeply passionate about music, I find myself frequently attending concerts, often opting for local bands. I have also experienced performances by national bands in the area. However, the costs can add up with parking and ticket fees; for instance, I once shelled out $15 just to see local bandsâ$10 for the ticket and $5 in fees. Yet, I prefer spending my money on these smaller, more personal venues rather than larger ones like Cricket or US Airways. The audio quality is consistently excellent, and the sloped floor design is a bonus, especially since I'm only 5 feet tall and it allows me to see everything clearly. I was slightly annoyed when I had to remove my shoes at the entrance, particularly because it was just a local band night. What, am I supposed to threaten Steve from Signs of Betrayal with my shoes?

Having spent $100 at the nursery this morning for my new patio, I was in need of breakfast and a refreshing iced tea. My neighbors had recommended Luci's, a place I had passed several times. At Luci's, you can customize your omelet: Eeny (just egg), Meeny (egg and cheese), Miny (egg, cheese, and veggies), or Moe (all the previous ingredients plus a protein). I opted for a spinach quiche and ordered a large iced tea. While I enjoyed my tea, I waited for the quiche to be warmed up. And waited. Eventually, after running into my massage therapist (who is the absolute best!), I inquired about my order. It turned out they had overlooked me. :{ No worries, though, they compensated with a complimentary Danish while they prepared my quiche.

They offer a variety of teas and assorted foods, though it's a compact selection and the prices are somewhat higher than at Sprouts.

I'll definitely return countless times, given its proximity to my home.

Here's hoping they remember me on my next visit ;}

The Rhythm Room stands out because of the diverse crowd it attracts. Nearly every visit reveals a girl roller skating on the dance floor, and you'll also spot punk enthusiasts, rockabilly fans, and country music lovers of various ages. It's exactly the sort of venue I enjoy. Moreover, if hunger strikes, you can find a man behind the venue in a trailer, where he sells pork sandwiches. They may not be the best, but they are ideal following an evening of live tunes.
Peanut and Buster created a parfait, and then it was over.

I wasn't feeling like having a burger, so I opted for the fish and chips instead. Greetings to the chewy batter! *pfffffft* (that represents the noise of a fart). The fries tasted great, and the ordering system was well-structured. *ppffffffffffffttttttttttt* I enjoy the various types of tea available, but I prefer mine without sugar. The lunchtime crowd was decent, with plenty of men around. *ppppffffftttttt*

ALERT FOR THE HOTTEST WAITER IN CENPHO! Tonight, I finally made my first visit to St. Francis with Tony A. I originally learned about this place from Sunny B., but it took me a week to locate it after reading her review. Silly me! It turns out it's right beside my bank! When Tony proposed we check it out, I eagerly agreed!

We waited for about 15 minutes. The venue was crowded, but a 15-minute wait seemed reasonable. We chose to sit outside and spent some time chatting. We even fantasized about how amazing it would be to get a table upstairs. And guess what? WE GOT SEATED UPSTAIRS! What a miracle!

Our waiter, *sigh*, from now on I'll call him Dreamboat Brandon. (By the way, is "hereforth" actually a word? Spell check disagrees.) First off, handling both Tony and me is no small feat, as we tend to be quite the raunchy duo. Dreamboat Brandon managed beautifully, providing excellent service by keeping our drinks topped up and giving us space, although we wouldn't have minded a bit more attention!

I ordered the ahi sandwich based on recommendations, and it was delicious! It was served with avocado, tomatoes, and what I *think* was a horseradish mayo. On the side, there was a small cup of homemade potato chips. The sandwich featured a thick slice of ahi on a hearty Kasier-type roll.

The Arnold Palmer I had was crafted with mango iced tea, which perfectly complemented my meal.

I adore the decor! Tony insisted I check out the bathroom. Luckily, I needed to go. I struggled with the door to the WOMEN'S restroom until it was opened from the inside... by a man. He explained he couldn't wait. I lectured him on how we often have to wait in lines at concerts and football games. AND he had left the seat up. Nonetheless, the bathroom was quite funky. There was even a safe in the wall, which I attempted to open while peeing, but to no avail.

All the staff were friendly, and the atmosphere was truly inviting. This place is definitely a gem that CenPho needed. I've never seen it empty, even on weeknights. I'm thrilled it's so close to home and that it seems to be thriving. I'd hate for Dreamboat Brandon to be out of work. Of course, I could use an assistant...

Nine hours have passed since I left, and boy, are my arms aching! My fingertips, chest, and legs are sore too. I used a Deal Chicken coupon and brought a colleague from work. I was clueless about what to wear and how to style my hair, anticipating the need for a helmet, so I barely touched it after getting up.

I regret not making more of an effort because there were plenty of attractive men around! The staff is committed to ensuring your safety. You have to sign a waiver and provide an emergency contact. (Scary, right? Haha!) They make you watch a safety and instructional video. An instructor guides you initially and you must complete several climbs under their supervision. My instructor, a charming guy named Robert, was cracking jokes left and right, outdoing even me, which is rare. He introduced us to the basics (pun intended with the ropes!) and then took us to walls that were suitable for beginners.

The facility is quite large, with climbing routes marked by difficulty and color-coded. We attempted three different walls but had to switch locations because a couple of cute guys were chatting with us, and I didn't want to be in an awkward position, trying to focus while they watched. 

The outing was enjoyable, and we spent just over two hours there. I'm quite sore but smartly scheduled a massage for the next day.

Next time, I'll be sure to do my hair since I've learned that most of the single men show up on Tuesday and Thursday nights. If you spot me there, steer clear. You're not my rival, and I might just sabotage your safety rope!

In the East, numerous grocery stores feature a section for bulk purchases, but this is not the case in Phoenix. This is the reason I have such a fondness for Sprouts. The bulk section there offers an extensive array of items available for bulk purchase! I typically pick up a large bag of banana chips, pumpkin seeds, oatmeal (I prefer the type that is chewy and requires longer than a minute to cook :P), rice, and chocolate-covered pretzels. Their selection of ethnic foods is also quite satisfactory. The store is consistently clean, and the staff enjoys engaging in conversation as they process your purchases.

Dexter celebrated his graduation from puppy school today. We attended for eight weeks, and Lauren, our trainer, was fantastic! Even when Dexter had accidents, she remained calm. Naturally, he was the cutest puppy in the class... Well, most of the time he was the only puppy there, but still...

In the initial weeks, they provided us with bags of treats to take home and use as homework. Indeed, homework. Following each session, I received a summary of the week's lessons to practice with at home.

The course, costing $109 for the eight weeks, was absolutely worth it! Not only do I now have the cutest puppy in the whole universe, but he is also the brightest. He became a favorite at the store. All the staff memorized his name! Like his Mommy, he naturally approached everyone seeking affection. Er... *I* don't do that, but you get the idea.

I've listened to tales about other PetSmart's training sessions. Ours didn't match those frightening accounts!

He will enroll in intermediate classes come autumn, which I suppose is akin to Middle School for dogs.

Could anyone explain why this place is popular?

I had breakfast with Deb L, and she used a Living Social coupon, or something similar. The restaurant was crowded, likely due to the holiday week.

However, this does not justify the extremely poor service we experienced. We sat and waited, and waited some more. Servers passed by frequently, but none stopped to fill our water glasses or take our order. Eventually, we both addressed a passing waitress, who appeared confused about her responsibilities. With so many staff members, it shouldn't have taken 15 minutes to get a cup of coffee. Yes, a whole 15 minutes.

As for the food, it was barely mediocre. I ordered the traditional eggs benedict with home fries. The dish's only redeeming feature was the generous portion of ham. The English muffin seemed un-toasted, the eggs were just okay, and the home fries were so poorly prepared that my 9-year-old niece could have done better. Even my burps are not worth mentioning.

Had the service been better, I might not be feeling so miserable now. The meal left me unsatisfied, and I am resolved to never visit this place again. Ever. Leaving a tip felt foolish; it was that disappointing.

Complete failure. Ugh.

It's quite surprising that a modest cinema, primarily screening indie films, could attract such a large audience! Last Sunday, I, along with Julia and Ayesha, decided to catch "Milk." Coincidentally, I bumped into Harley's bartender while queuing up. And outside, we also spotted Amanda and her daughter!

The queue was lengthy, but lo and behold, there was an electronic ticket dispenser! I quickly used my debit card, and secured my ticket in under two minutes. The employees at the snack counter were exceptional! They were not only humorous but also clearly passionate about their work.

The cinema was quite pleasant. It lacked the stadium seating found in larger venues, but we managed to find seats near the screen, as it was extremely packed and we were three. Finding three adjacent seats on a Sunday afternoon is no small feat!

The seating was comfy. Despite its age, the theater had drink holders integrated into the armrests. Despite its location at Fashion Square, this venue will remain my top pick. I sometimes favor independent movies, and this cinema really stands out!

The food was awesome, and the service was equally impressive, thanks to Patty. The ambience? Also awesome. However, the temperature was terrible! I was shivering for half of my meal. When I brought it up with Patty, she mentioned that this issue occurs in that specific area during the rotation. Considering the cost is at least $80 per person, you would expect that they could manage such an issue!

I had a preference for visiting the Downtown spot, but, alas, I was involved with someone from Gilbert at the time. Our relationship endured for a mere 2 weeks. The relationship, that is, not the meal. It was satisfactory, I suppose. I consumed a sandwich, but it failed to leave an impression. It was served swiftly, even though it was nearly closing time, and I suspect it was heated in a microwave. I will certainly return, but to a different location.

I visited My Doll tonight and made my way on foot from The Sets. This venue is truly exceptional for experiencing live music, particularly for someone with punk inclinations like myself! The lighting is surprisingly good for a bar, and there's never an entrance fee, which is definitely a bonus.

The performances are consistently entertaining, and this evening, I nearly got knocked over in the mosh pit, earning a cool 500 points for the experience! Getting a drink at the bar can take some time, but this is both a positive and a negative aspect. On the positive side, a busy bar means a lively atmosphere, far better than a quiet spot with bands playing. On the downside, if you're really craving a drink, you'll find yourself waiting. Tough luck!

Ugh. Today, I had to be at the U of Phoenix Stadium for work, and my mom drove down from Payson to join me for lunch afterward. I'm not familiar with Westgate, except for the hockey arena. It's part of an outdoor shopping center, just like every other place there. We were famished, but the mall seemed deserted. It appeared that many shops were shut, so we opted for Margaritaville for our meal.

The main entrance was not well-signposted, and we ended up entering through the patio. Upon entering, we noticed no clear reception desk, so we inquired with the closest waitress whether we should seat ourselves. In a tone mimicking an airline stewardess, she directed us to the check-in area, which was both pretentious and irritating. Thus, we proceeded to check in. There was a 15-minute wait for a table for two, although we noticed several vacant tables as we walked in, which my mom remarked upon. "Our kitchen is quite overwhelmed at the moment, so not all tables can be occupied," we were informed. Remember, this was around 12:30 PM on a Saturdayâsurely a peak time that should have been anticipated by the restaurant management?

We wandered over to the bar, finding it nearly empty with just two patrons. We settled into a corner spot and, fortunately, discovered we could dine there. The bartender turned out to be the first amiable staff member we encountered, and I was pleased that she received our tip. The service here was prompt, with our meals served in about 10 minutes.

My mom chose the chicken quesadilla, and I opted for the taco salad. The menu was surprisingly limitedâI had expected a broader selection. The food was mediocre; nothing that would tempt me to return.

Throughout our meal, videos of Jimmy Buffet and his concertgoers played continuously. They seemed to be enjoying themselves far more than we were. No one yelled out for salt, which I might have done, but I refrained, considering my mom has endured nearly four decades of my antics.

Ugh.

I've visited this place with my mom on two occasions, and each time, the service was excellent. You should try the shrimp wrapped in pancetta; it's delicious! Additionally, I find myself yearning for, or rather, intensely desiring, their lobster bisque several times annually. It's luscious and creamy, yet it has a slight spicy kick. I invariably end up taking a container of it home. My sole complaint? Why can't they maintain consistent opening hours? So frustrating!

Indeed, it took quite some time for me to visit The Parlor, even though I can easily walk there. My friends, on the other hand, have been there countless times. But I've been too caught up with other things.

In front of us, there was a large group of eight, accompanied by a multitude of children, all waiting for others to join them. I informed the hostess that I was open to sitting anywhere, just not close to that noisy group. And she accommodated us by seating us on the patio.

I absolutely adore patio heaters; they're essential during the cold months here, and the patio felt exceptionally snug and warm, not too much, just perfect.

For my meal, I chose a pasta with seafood and a bold, spicy red sauce. I appreciate that the dishes are offered in two sizes because leftovers, especially shrimp, just don't hold up wellâthey turn rubbery and unappetizing. Otherwise, it ends up spoiling in my refrigerator, right next to the broccoli.

The service was impeccable; I didn't once need to ask for a drink refill. The server was not only efficient but also quite charming and attractive.

The prices were reasonable, and fortunately, I didn't have to cover the cost. I'm also a fan of valet services, which, luckily, I didn't have to pay for either.

This message is intended for Deb:
I traveled to the drive-thru speaker and placed an order for a Quarter Pounder with cheese meal, accompanied by a Diet Coke. Indeed, I opt for Diet Coke, not because I believe it counteracts the meal's unhealthiness, but because it is my preferred choice. 
I received my meal promptly, and I scarcely recall consuming it, but I did share the final bites of my burger and some fries with the dog. The fries were tasty.
Moreover, the ice in my drink was exceptionally cold.

This place, situated in the hippest section of CenPho and neighboring Stinkweeds, frances, and Halo, transported me into a time warp the moment I stepped inside. Tonight, I attended a writing workshop here, and the table was laden with countless varieties of candies. I found myself grabbing one candy, then another, either exclaiming or silently recalling their names in my head, amazed because I hadn't encountered them in so long.

As I perused the candy selection for our writing task, waves of nostalgia overwhelmed me. Fun Dip! Sure, it's available everywhere, but wait, there's more. When did you last come across an Aero bar? Or do you even recognize it? Or consider that awful violet-flavored gum, a favorite of one of my mother's former boyfriends.
