The store also boasts a range of novelty items. Are you in the market for a bacon wallet or perhaps a punching nun? These novelty items adorn one wall, while candies fill the opposite wall. In the center, both are intermingled.

I was also pleased to learn that the owner, Georgeanne, maintains an ongoing list of candies she aims to source for customers. I suggested one from my childhood: a mini record cover with a gum shaped like a record inside, and the lyrics to "Heart of Glass" printed inside the cover. I'm eager to see if she can locate it!

I'm uncertain why individuals repeatedly return to Yoshi's. I tried it just once, and that was enough. It's situated directly opposite our workplace at the Indian School & Central location, and it seemed like everyone frequented it daily. Thus, I decided to give it a shot.

However, when I ordered chicken, I couldn't really determine whether it was actually chicken or some other type of meat, nor could I tell which part of the chicken it might have been. The texture was notably stringy, fatty, and gristly. The teriyaki sauce was tasty, but the rice was merely passable, being somewhat too sticky for my taste.

Arrived well past 11:30 last night following our time at the Fez gathering, and I must admit, I am extremely grateful (or perhaps a bit frightened) to discover that it remains open until midnight! There's no guilt in visiting that place! We indulged in the peanut butter (indeed, yet another addition to my "Make Me Yelp" collection) and experienced a heavenly chocolate caramel brownie delight in a bowl. The service was exceptionally welcoming, and the establishment was notably tidy.

These folks are my crowd. I find myself here regularly, at least weekly, and often engage on Twitter Tuesdays. I hold the unofficial title of Mayor at this Mojo Yogurt spot. No, there wasn't any grand parade for me. On Twitter Tuesdays, they reveal a "word of the day" that entitles you to a 50% discount. HALF OFF. That, my friends, is what effective marketing looks like.

Although I experiment with various yogurt flavors, my favorites are coconut and acai. My go-to toppings? Always mochi and strawberries, without fail. If mochi is unfamiliar to you, it's time to broaden your cultural horizons. Mochi is not only part of the experience; its delightful chewiness is something I adore. (And yes, "chewiness" is indeed a legitimate word, and it didn't even trigger a spell-check alert!)

The customer service here is exceptional. I seldom use the term "stellar" as it's too commonly thrown around, but here, it's just the right word.

They recognize me by name at this location. Well, I make sure to remind them, given that I'm the MAYOR. (I probably wouldn't mention it so often if Amber didn't constantly boast about her Mayorship at Dunkin' Donuts! ;})

Sarah G, our resident food critic, joined me for lunch and presented me with a sprinkles cupcake encased in a charming little box. This is the point at which I become slightly annoyed. It even had its own box. Such extravagance! I get that they aim for cuteness, but I am someone who prefers to protect the environment. The cupcake tasted fine, but it wasn't exceptional. I anticipated it would be messy enough to ruin my "Make me Yelp" boyshorts, yet it wasn't. The flavor was vanilla milk chocolate. The chocolate icing was overly sweet, and it was adorned with sprinkles (obviously!). The cake itself was light and moist, but not as moist as I prefer. I thought it would be more impressive, but it reminded me of the cupcakes my sister baked for my niece's 5th birthday. And it had its own ridiculous box.

Visited the rooftop bar this evening. Upon entering the hotel, I was struck by the ultra-stylish lobby, adorned with vibrant hues, particularly the abundant reds! The elevator journey to the top was unique - a glass back wall allowed views of the brickwork as we ascended to the 4th floor, although it was quite warm inside.

Exiting the elevator, I observed that each room was marked with an Arizona license plate, a truly novel concept! Reaching the rooftop was breathtaking; despite being just four stories high, the cityscape view was impressive. Surprisingly, the place was deserted at 10pm on a Friday. Likely, because it was First Friday and a large crowd had gathered downtown for the art walk, people were still out and about.

I made my way to a comfortable couch and settled in, immediately soothed by the ambiance. It was clear to me that this spot would soon become a favorite retreat. My only complaint was that, even though we were the only guests, the tables were cluttered with used glasses and bottles. The bartender, Dallas, who is also a Yelper, was both approachable and quite charming!

Around 11pm, the crowds began to filter in, presenting a diverse array of individuals. Dottsy and I entertained ourselves by assigning nicknames to each group: the Tempe crowd (one girl flaunted a tattoo of the band Tool - quite the statement!); the Scottsdale crowd (the girls wanted a photo, yet one barely cracked a smile); the Phoenix crowd (down-to-earth folks, much like ourselves); and a few others who didn't fit any mold.

The soft background music was what I appreciated most. Frequenting clubs often, it was refreshing to hold a conversation without needing to raise my voice over loud music.

I'll definitely return. Dallas, you should remember my usual drink next time - a diet Coke with a slice of lime!

A group of six gathered for a birthday celebration. We enjoyed mac & cheese and, for dessert, indulged in homemade s'moresâyes, homemade, with a touch of peanut butter, fresh marshmallows, and chocolate-covered bacon. Seriously, I'm not joking. The service was excellent, until it came time to settle the bill and we requested separate checks. At that point, the server's demeanor turned somewhat unpleasant, but it wasn't so bad as to deter me from returning.

I must express my enthusiasm for this establishment! There was a business gathering planned, and our initial meeting spot was at the Merc. Unfortunately, their signage was misleading and their opening hours were not as advertised. Consequently, we ended up at Fuego Tacos just around the corner.

Previously, I had visited the Bistro once, so I was aware it was a reliable choice. We arrived shortly after 5 PM, and found the lower level to be moderately occupied, but the upper level was vacant. We requested to sit upstairs and were offered our pick of tables.

Our server was outstanding! Right away, he served us chips and salsa, and promptly took our drink orders. Surprisingly, he brought me two drinks, which I didn't mind at all, especially since I'm accustomed to servers who struggle to keep up with my drink needs (Diet Coke, just so you know).

The chips were freshly prepared, and the salsa was tasty. We decided to order a plate of nachos with pork on top to share. It turned out to be one of the most delightful nacho dishes I've experienced in quite some time, and we all thoroughly enjoyed it.

As we were preparing to leave, our server surprised me with a Diet Coke in a to-go cup without me having to request one â impressive!

I definitely plan to return. The prices were fair, and the atmosphere was lively. Oh, and they had 80s music playing, which certainly adds 500 cool points to the venue.

What is it that captivates me about Club Red/Red Owl? It combines two venues into a single location! Nearly every weekend, you can find me there. If one band doesn't catch my fancy, I simply stroll to the opposite side of the building. Moreover, the bathrooms are spotless and feature retro decor. The staff is friendly, and the guys working behind the bar are really attractive.

Dexter absolutely adored the place! He's a tiny 7-pound rat terrier and is incredibly friendly (I'm clueless about his origins!). He went along with Robert M and Brady. Upon our arrival, the park hosted just a few other canines, but by the time we were ready to leave, the count had surged to around 20. The park maintained cleanliness, offered ample seating for humans, and provided plenty of shade. Chuey, a toy silkie, along with a beagle, both had their fun with Dexter. Dexter sprinted as if he had never run before! It was his inaugural visit to a dog park. However, we had to stop by Wag N Wash afterwards because he ended up smeared with various canine secretions.

This location consistently astonishes me. I typically visit the branch on Camelback near the Biltmore, but now that I'm employed at the Scottsdale Airpark, I frequent the FLW store. Stepping into Trader Joe's always brings a sense of peace, happiness, and niceness. On my recent visit, I was in search of hummus and discovered two delicious varieties: roasted garlic and spicy. At work, a colleague had these irresistible cheese puffs, so I couldn't resist buying them; they're Buccaneer Joe's White Cheddar Corn Puffs, and they're scrumptious! I picked up some dunkers too, which are perfect for satisfying a sweet craving. The flowers were affordable, and I regret not being home more often to enjoy them. Unfortunately, I had to deduct a star due to a rather surly cashier â come on, you're at Trader Joe's, cheer up!

I absolutely cherish Trader Joe's. If it were possible, I'd take its hand, jump into an R32, and head off to Vegas with it!

I was invited to this place for Happy Hour and dinner. When they offer walleye as the fish n chips special, it's impossible to resist! The fish fry turned out to be fantastic! It's been a while since I last had walleye, not since my father passed away, and with his birthday approaching, it felt like a fitting homage. The meal included five ample pieces of fish accompanied by ultra-crispy fries, both tartar and cocktail sauces, a side of coleslaw, and... don't forget the malt vinegar among the condiments!

Four Peaks nailed it. Although the fish's exterior was slightly oily, the inside was delicious and fried to perfection. The batter wasn't overwhelming, allowing the true flavor of the fish to shine through. The addition of malt vinegar to splash on the fries was a brilliant touch â just add a sprinkle of salt and... absolutely delicious!

The coleslaw was mediocre, nothing special. The place was filled with a diverse mix of patrons, which surprisingly made the experience more enjoyable, considering I usually steer clear of the ASU crowd. It was somewhat noisy for having a good chat, but then again, it was a Friday night.

Oh, and I managed to snag a parking spot right in front. How great is that?

The weekend programs are so captivating! Car Talk was practically the sole interest my father and I shared. Ira Glass? He's my clandestine radio infatuation :} Splendid Table? Adore it! Fresh Air? It's terrific! I'm a huge fan of NPR, and I even get my friends from back East to listen online on Sunday evenings for the blues.

Upon entering The Lost Leaf, I immediately felt certain I would return! Live tunes in the rear, a vibrant crowd, and artistic decorations all screamed "Home" to me. I joined a group of fellow Yelpers (Happy Birthday, Jacqui!) and we had a fantastic time. The music was at a perfect volume, allowing conversations to flow easily. The beer options appeared extensive, although I didn't check out the wine selection.

I'm among the minority who actually prefer the high-top tables.

The patrons were predominantly young Phoenix locals relishing the urban offerings of downtown PHX. The place was crowded, yet on a Saturday night, I anticipated even more people. The local artwork displayed was less ostentatious than in many other venues. And the wood! So much wood around made me feel as if I were in the East again, with its hardwood floors and beamed ceilings, reminiscent of a cozy lodge ideal for post-skiing relaxation.

I found the kitchen charming, albeit slightly quaint. I'm pretty sure there was a non-commercial dishwasher in sight!

Naturally, the company was unbeatable! Jacqui, Dave B, Nathan, Kristin, Stevey P, and my favorite lads, Thomas and Ricky, truly made the evening exceptional.

For just five dollars, you get a burger, fries, and a soda. What could possibly go wrong? I opted for the Guac burger, and it was the sole reason I deducted a star. The burger was excellent, but the guacamole? Not so much. However, they do offer a wide variety of toppings to choose from. The fries were thin-cut and seasoned with spiced salt, and the portion size was generous. I absolutely adore a soda! They offer Shasta, which earns two thumbs up from me. It's free of NutraSweet in the diet version, using Splenda instead. Cheers! Exiting the venue can be tricky, so hereâs my tip: leave via the rear exit, passing through the car wash to reach 7th Street. The traffic at the Indian School intersection, especially at the 7th Street light, is horrendous.

I'm truly excited to bring my parents to this place!!! After the event, I phoned my mother and described the slide to herâthe one I struggled to slide down because my legs were sticky from walking up the driveway. I managed to get a ride, yet it was still sweltering outside. I know, it's unpleasant, but that's how it was.

The staff here is extremely welcoming! Everyone appeared genuinely kind and they were enjoying their work.

As for the food, it was decent. There was a good variety, though it lacked some originality. There were also options for vegetarians, which is a plus.

I am definitely planning to visit frequently. My stepdad is sure to adore this spot!!

I've consistently enjoyed Pita Jungle, yet this particular branch excels in service! I make a call from my office before heading out to place a takeout order. They promise it'll be ready in 15 minutes, and when I show up after 15 minutes, my order is indeed ready! The staff here is always welcoming, and they recognize me by name. The establishment is also spotless. Moreover, the rear patio is expansive, and they offer complimentary wifi. There's even a quaint bar outside, facing inward. I've never witnessed it being completely deserted. I'm so thrilled that we now have a Pita Jungle in CenPho!

SLUM! I ordered the chili con queso, and it turned out to be just VELVEETA mixed with salsa. I even inquired about it! I was truly let down by it, and it bothered me so much that I didn't bother ordering dinner. I visited the location at the Biltmore.

Undoubtedly the most beautiful Thai restaurant! Upon entering to rendezvous with one of my dearest friends, Ayesha S., I noticed her positioned at an enormous table. Truly enormous, and just for the two of us. It was a large, circular, marble spectacle, yet it was quite fashionable.

Our meal commenced with the spring rolls accompanied by shrimp, which arrived and were massive! It seems size is a recurring motif here. The ingredients were certainly fresh, and nothing was overly cooked.

Initially, the service was somewhat inconsistent, but it enhanced as our dinner progressed. Our beverages were replenished multiple times without any prompt.

I opted for the spicy mussels, served on a vast (HUGE) platter, accompanied by some sautÃ©ed vegetables and a spicy sauce. Aware that mussels do not fare well as leftovers, I consumed them entirely. I didnât end up feeling overstuffed like after a Thanksgiving meal, but rather nicely satisfied.

I am eager to return. I'm interested in sampling additional dishes from the menu. Like Ayesha, I'm curious to experience more spiciness. "If it donât make ya cry, why would ya eat it??"

I would also be interested in meeting the owner. I mean, given that everything is so large, perhaps it's indicative of something? ;}

Chaka Chaka, I adore you!!! I'm always thrilled to hear about other comedians who not only pursue comedy but also chase different dreams. Charles established this venue not long ago, and despite the adult entertainment establishment next door, it's fantastic! I also believe the neighborhood offers excellent opportunities for people-watching.

I had the jerk chicken sandwich and the garlic fries, and I consumed both. Indeed, I was accompanied by three other female comedians, and we all thoroughly enjoyed our meals.

The server was extremely friendly and efficient, and even though he took our orders, there were no mix-ups.

The menu might be limited, but I think it suits Chaka Chaka perfectly. I mean, with such a unique name, how could it not be a hit???

Oh, and don't forget to order the brownie. Seriously, order the brownie.

Here is the spot where I sometimes collect my Bountiful Basket. The co-op's food is pre-packaged for collection, but they offer additional items at attractive prices too! Ample parking is available, and the staff are extremely welcoming. I've also had folks assist me with my haul on occasion.

Alright, I previously penned a review about our Yelp birthday celebration, but I hadn't covered the museum itself. I just returned from the "Selected Shorts" exhibit, which featured a series of short films. Following a meal at Arcadia Farms, our group of 12 ventured to the film festival, aptly named No Festival Required. We watched seven distinct shorts, and, surprisingly, the exhibit was free of charge! We enjoyed this perk as we didn't have to pay the museum entry fee due to our lunch plans.

Entering the theater was an exciting experience! It offered stadium seating, which was unexpected but essential for someone of my height to avoid neck strain. The theater design included a stage with the screen positioned above, ensuring even those seated at the front could enjoy a clear view without discomfort. Although there was no popcorn, the seats were comfortable, and the staff was exceptionally welcoming. The event started and concluded precisely on time, which was impressive.

I am certainly planning to revisit the museum and am eager to attend more screenings in that theater.

Two possibilities here: either my starter has expanded, or I've gained a bit of weight! I can't remember the last time I managed to finish a whole pizza by myself â quite the feat! I even managed to clean my plate, much to my mother's delight. And yes, I was thoroughly enjoying it, as my expression clearly showed. The food was undoubtedly fantastic. The setting was charming, set in a house converted into dining rooms, complete with lovely hardwood floors. I was particularly struck by the artwork, which I think is sourced from local artists, and the fresh flowers on the tables added a nice touch. The patio felt like stepping onto a film set in Hollywood, with Christmas lights draped across the trees. The service was decent, and my server had a vibe reminiscent of that character from "The Devil's Reject" â intimidating yet intriguing. Looking for a spot for a date? This place should be on your list.

"My tea is good," my friend remarked. Besides that, I found the food to be passable. I frequently eat Thai cuisine, but the only standout was the intense heat from the spices...indeed, it was quite spicy! "The tea here is really good," my friend observed. The decor was pleasant and subdued, making me curious if there's a common interior designer for Thai eateries. "This is good tea," yes, I'm aware, my friend :). The service was satisfactory with no issues to report. My water glass remained full, and our server was very attentive. Regarding the tea? I believe you already know the answer - enjoy!

Have you ever used Yelp so frequently that you can't recall if you've reviewed a particular spot? Lucky for me, I had forgotten about this place, perhaps justifiably so. Despite its hype and stylish decor, the food was underwhelming. I had some curry and chicken; it was passable, likely because I was quite hungry. The presentation was appealing, which might just be their trick. And the cost? It's overly expensive for what you receive â I find more joy in filling up my car! The ambiance does have its charms, with enjoyable Polynesian-themed decorations. Regarding service, we were a large group, and I've never grasped why some waiters struggle with this. Having been an excellent waiter myself, I was always prepared, regardless of the group size. I'm not saying they performed well because, frankly, they didnât â just kidding! Enjoy!

I was born with a craving for Pho! My Vietnamese heritage constantly drives me to try out new Pho spots, while my Chinese roots instill in me a strong work ethic, humorously likened to laboring in a sweatshop. I enjoy the Pho at Blue Moon; it didn't impress me much a year ago, but I returned for their Pho Challenge. Indeed, there's a Pho challenge â the amount is unclear, but the size of the bowl might make you curl up like a baby. I admit I'm not brave enough to conquer this challenge as I need to maintain my slim figure. The quality of the Pho has certainly gotten better. The ambiance is simple yet stylish. The service is attentive and efficient. The price is astonishingly low at about $3.50 for a bowl of Pho â a real bargain for a satisfying meal. Enjoy!

I feel conflicted, much like the song by Natalie Imbruglia.

I enjoy visiting Sakana's. Their sushi rolls are tasty, and they occasionally use unique ingredients. I always make sure to order the fried shrimp heads and definitely the octopus with a bit of lemon zest, which is a nice touch. While I wouldn't describe the experience as extraordinary, it's a solid choice for satisfying a sushi craving. The sushi overall is decent, though the rolls could be a bit more compact. Their drink and appetizer deal is clever and appealing; you can get an appetizer for just $1 with a drink purchase â very cool!

The atmosphere is relaxed with a nightlife vibe. The decor is somewhat eclectic, and I'm unsure what to make of it. The service is commendable, and hearing the birthday song in Japanese is always a charming and enjoyable touch. I'm eager to grab the lucky cat! - Have fun!

I really enjoy the food here; it's excellent. It seems like all the dishes, from the soup to the sauce, are homemade because they're delicious. I occasionally visit for lunch and have noticed the restaurant gradually attracting more customers. It combines the ambiance of a deli and a sports bar, yet the quality of the food truly stands out. I value their commitment to sustainability, evident in their use of real plates over disposable ones, which is environmentally friendly. I highly recommend this spot for lunch, especially the half sandwich, their pastafagioli soup, and a drinkâdelicious!

Enjoy wine and bruschetta for just $20 on Mondays and Tuesdays! What else is there to say, except don't lament for me, Arizona! I plan to make the most of this deal whenever possible :) I really adore this spot. It surpasses the Arcadia location in many ways; it's more spacious and usually has ample parking available. The service is excellent and consistently entertaining. The atmosphere is relaxed and understated. I'm curious though, do they host live music, or have I just been coming on off nights? Hmm, take pleasure in it!

Apologies to Chino Bandido, or perhaps I should refer to it as Chino Bad-Dido. I do see the appeal of combining Chinese and Mexican cuisines, though I'm not entirely convinced. Perhaps I'm being overly critical. I generally like fusion cuisine, but mixing fried rice with refried beans under the guise of culinary innovation doesn't sit right with me. As for the ambiance, it resembles a storage facility outfitted with collapsible tables and chairs scattered throughout. What exactly was their product? They claim it's a fusion of Chinese and Mexican gastronomy, and it seems you're expected to savor it simply because it's there. I'm giving it a single star, primarily because I find their mascot, the Mexican Panda, quite charming.

Do you need rice urgently? This spot is perfect for a quick rice pickup, which was exactly my case. I went for the Spicy Lover because that matches my taste; it's essentially kung pao chicken but spicier, and I loved it. It was served with an eggroll, a side of egg drop soup, and fried rice. However, for those who prefer less heat, I'd suggest opting for the standard kung pao chicken. All of this cost just $6, which is quite a deal. It feels like you're getting street food without actually being on the street. They offer Boba drinks too, though I prefer the frozen yogurt boba shop next door.

The establishment is quite basic, resembling a typical fast-food Chinese place, but the service is commendable.

The reviews on Yelp rated this establishment as fairly good, and I found it to be quite enjoyable. It may not be the most authentic compared to other Indian eateries, yet it manages to stand out in its own right. Perhaps it's due to the level of spices used. It's important that the spiciness of the food is balanced. The spice level in my Masala CK was just right for my taste. I'm able to tolerate a bit of heat, but excessive spiciness is over the top; I'd need some milk then! The decor is appealing, especially with the vibrant green wall at the bar and the ceiling-high arrangement of wine bottles, which is a smart touch. The service was passable, and I'll leave it at that. Enjoy your visit!

Is it reasonable to expect an Asian boy to discuss rice? Throughout my life, I've consumed plenty of it :) I've enjoyed rice paired with kung pao chicken, sweet and sour pork, chicken parmesan, enchiladas, green curry, and even Thanksgiving turkey... the variety is endless. Rice is a fundamental food, especially for Asians. I really enjoy visiting this place for lunch or dinner, offering broken rice with a selection of toppings - choose freely! The staff here are exceptionally attentive - take a seat and you'll quickly decide what to order, given the menu features more than 100 options! The decor isn't much to speak of - it has a distinct, unrefined Vietnamese charm, which usually means the food is delicious. Since 22 is my favorite number, I recommend trying dish number 22 when you visit next. Enjoy!

I really like this spot. The food is surprisingly delicious. It's a great time to visit while the weather remains pleasant. Indeed, 90 degrees is quite nice in Phoenix. However, the service doesn't match up; with 50 customers and 20 waitstaff, you'd expect faster service. Can I please have my mimosas already? If you're okay with the slow service, then definitely go because the food is worth it. :)

I occasionally indulge in a cup of Boba. During my college days, it was gaining popularity rapidly. There was always a debate between choosing Starbucks or Boba. The place was called Boba Tea House - quite a straightforward name, right? My choice of boba usually stood out for its intense flavor. I consistently chose Thai Tea with Boba, which could easily be nicknamed "Bo's" Ba. The service was relaxed, and I received my tea just how I liked it. However, I wondered about the air conditioning situation. Fans were on everywhere. Is the preparation of Boba so energy-intensive that they need to turn off the A/C, or is it because the fish tank needs to maintain a specific temperature? They offered a leather couch for seating, but I preferred to avoid it to save my skin. It seemed like the staff was eagerly anticipating the cooler days of winter. Enjoy!

This place is truly for those who love the nightlife. The music is loud and the dance floor is always packed, with everyone enjoying themselves to the fullest. They host fantastic special events (shoutout to Phillip!) that really cater to fans of techno. The atmosphere is enhanced by glow sticks, blacklighting, and even my own glow-in-the-dark pimp cup. The presence of painted models and Go Go dancers adds to the excitement. I'd love another sweet shot, please! However, the venue has lost some of its original charm. I recall times when there were long lines of people, myself included, eagerly waiting just to get in. Here's hoping for a return to those days. Enjoy the experience!

Apologies for not choosing the Pho.

Given the heat, I opted against soup and went for the #3 Marinated Grilled Beef, Egg Rolls, and Noodles instead. Although it's not a dish I frequently indulge in, I was thoroughly pleased with it. The aroma of the marinade on the slightly charred flank beef was delightful. And the spicy fish sauce added just the right amount of zestâWa Cha! My companion chose the Pork Chops, and I must admit, her choice was spot on. I tried a little, and it was truly tasty.

The service was a mixed bag. The chef, whose identity I'm unsure of, appeared very friendly and made an effort to interact with the guests. Many regulars seemed to appreciate her presence, and I hope to join their ranks soon. The waiter, on the other hand, was rather rigid and perpetually seemed upset, which amusingly reminded me of my father (no offense intended to him!). The restaurant was quaint and small, a bit cluttered, yet I liked the intimacy it offered, allowing easy interaction with other guests. Enjoy!

Delicious! Absolutely delicious! Oh, and yes, delicious again! I adore Tottie's! I'm also a fan of Tottie :) I wish if I ever get married, my spouse could whip up dishes like Tottie, so funny! It goes without saying, the Thai cuisine is outstanding! However, I need to avoid too much spice as I'm not great with hot chili peppers. I prefer to keep it mild :) The fried fish and chicken basil are incredibly tasty! The interior design is lovely (shoutout to Gary!) Enjoying samurai art while dining on Tom Yum - more Tom Yum? Yes, please. Don't forget to try their variety of desserts; they're a great remedy for the spicy heat. The service is quick and impressive! I need more water over here, my tongue is starting to feel numb :) Have a great meal!

Explore the history of the Garcia family to enhance your appreciation of their cuisine! This location isn't the original Garcia's, but it suffices. On a spontaneous Sunday, my brother craved Mexican food. Garcia's, a personal favorite, is known for its complimentary bean and salsa dip at each table, with the bean dip being particularly outstanding. I opted for their beef tacos and tamales. Unfortunately, the taco was unremarkable, and the tamales were a letdown. I've experienced excellent tamales before, but these were too tough and lacked flavor in the beef. Our group ordered drinks, and initially, the bill seemed reasonable until we considered the quality of the food.

The service improved noticeably once they realized we were reviewing on Yelp. It's frustrating when my anonymity is revealed! The restaurant boasts charming old southwest decor and beautiful murals depicting traditional Mexican scenes, making it an aesthetically pleasing venue. - Enjoy your visit!

You really can't go wrong with Four Peaks, a local brewery that has long catered to ASU students and beer aficionados alike. The mixologist there has done an excellent job, as the food and beer complement each other perfectly. The venue is consistently lively. Securing a seat might require a wait, but it's definitely worth it. Alternatively, you could head straight to the bar where it's first come, first served. Even when busy, the service remains commendably efficient. With attractive bartenders and speedy service, there are no grounds for complaints. The atmosphere is comfortably casual and relaxed. Essentially, I value a bar that isn't fussy about dress code; just wear some form of clothing and you're good to go. Enjoy!

Mom is whipping up something delicious in the kitchen!

I really love the spacious kitchen layout. It brought back memories, making me feel as though I was in a traditional Italian kitchen but with contemporary seating options. We took seats at the bar and ordered "the Pig," essentially a pizza for meat lovers, without the typical chain restaurant vibe. Needless to say, it was impressive! My fondness for the pizza wasn't just because I was hungry; the sauce was bursting with flavor and the cheese was incredibly soft and stretchy! The meat on top was cooked to perfection, seasoned with just the right amount of salt to enhance its taste. Absolutely fantastic! I'll definitely return!

The service was outstanding, thanks to Bryan. He offered us a chance to sample some wine and provided great recommendations. Thanks, buddy, keep it up! Cheers!

Welcome to Christopher's Restaurant and Crush Lounge, a tribute to the legendary Macho Man Randy Savage! Nestled within the upscale Biltmore Fashion Park, this establishment is a world away from the flamboyance of WWE, offering a touch of sophistication and authenticity.

The venue is cleverly divided into two sections: a dining area and a lounge. The dining space boasts a modern, trendy ambiance with an open kitchen where the esteemed Chef Christopher Gross and his team skillfully prepare culinary masterpieces right before your eyes. It's truly captivating to watch these culinary artists in action, and I highly recommend experiencing this from the restaurant bar to interact directly with the chefs.

On the flip side, the Crush Lounge exudes a chic and seductive vibe. If you're feeling a tad adventurous, this spot might just be your haven. The artwork displayed here caters to a more adult audience, suggesting that it's not for the faint-hearted. For those preferring a milder atmosphere, the main restaurant area remains a safer, more family-friendly choice. The lounge offers a cozy setting to savor a drink and indulge in light fare, including cheese platters, pizzas, and popular snacks like burgers and calamari.

The culinary offerings from the restaurant are nothing short of exceptional. If your taste buds aren't impressed, it might be time for a check-up! Chef Christopher's menu ranges from simple delights like burgers and pizza to exquisite dishes such as Foie Gras and Duck Confit. You won't regret choosing to dine here; in fact, you'll likely find yourself returning to sample more of the menu. Enjoy your visit!

I wouldn't classify the cuisine as gourmet, especially considering my experiences in Hue, Vietnam, where I didn't indulge in any gourmet meals. Perhaps I'm not the best judge. However, I do recognize the authenticity of their dishes here, even though they're not exactly to my taste. The flavors don't quite excite me. The food was passable, but their excellent service deserves recognition. I find joy in attempting to speak Vietnamese, and I appreciate how the server helps and motivates me to learn more. Yes, I'm still on the learning curve. Being located in Mekong Plaza is definitely an advantage for this restaurant, although I'm unsure how it would fare in a different location. Enjoy!

This small sandwich shop is both expensive and lacks ambiance. It's aptly summarized by its abundance of bread filling my stomach. I found myself asking, "Where's the beef?" reminiscent of the 1980s. The sandwich I had was predominantly bread with some lettuce and tomatoes. The highlight of my meal was likely the clam chowder, which came with the sandwich and soup combo. The service was fast, which was a plus. The decor was very basic, but I did enjoy the unique helicopter ceiling fan, possibly more than the sandwich itself. Enjoy your visit!

Indeed, this individual made their way into the publicly accessible establishment! I opted for the Connelly's Grilled Cheese without much anticipation. Wow! The initial taste took me by surprise with its savory ham, melted cheddar, and sweetly pickled cherries adding a delightful twist. The toasted bread added a pleasing texture that delighted my palate. Excellently done, esteemed Citizen! We chose to sit at the bar and enjoyed some drinks (a refreshing Czech Pilsner!) The service was outstanding. The decor was quite contemporary, and with a name like Citizen Public House, it inevitably reminded me of the film Citizen Kane. "Still eating?" "I'm still hungry!" - Enjoy!

RA Sushi is exactly as you'd expect. In my opinion, this particular spot tops all other RA Sushi locations across the valley. It boasts a roomy interior and a pleasant outdoor seating area. While I'm not overly enthusiastic about their sushi, their happy hour offers are quite good. The bar layout is impressive; you can view the game from any seat! :)

Choosing pizza is a safe bet, and if that's not the case for you, perhaps running a pizzeria or working in one isn't the best idea. I adore pizza whether it's freshly baked or just pulled from the refrigerator. Cold pizza is delightful! CPK consistently delivers quality and is always exploring new pizza varieties like Bacon, BBQ, and Ham. I'd like another large one, please! It's usually busy, yet there's enough room to feel comfortable; I really value CPK's approach. Plus, nowadays everyone understands when you mention CPK. I guess I'm rambling a bit now, but anyway, enjoy your meal!

Downtown Chandler is truly an undiscovered gem! A key attraction is Latitude Eight, a compelling reason to visit. I'm a fan of Thai cuisine, and Lat 8 really satisfies my cravings with their delightful dishes. They expertly blend Thai zest with American presentation styles. The atmosphere is modern and chic, making it an ideal spot for a date. The service was exceptional; our server was humorous and attentive. My meal was served piping hot and disappeared just as quickly. I highly recommend their Pineapple Fried Rice, which elevates a simple dish to something extraordinary. Definitely worth trying!

Bo Bites! To start, imagine this: White Trash with Class. I'm all about Big Daddy's BBQ! What else can I say? Pulled Pork on Wonder Bread with a glass of PBR... delicious.

These folks truly master the art of Midwest BBQ. They boast a massive smoker in the back kitchen and a sizable pot for their beans, set up like an efficient assembly line to serve their dishes quickly.

The food is fantastic! I enjoy their Pulled Pork, Tri Tip, and Brisket. I'm not overly enthusiastic about the Beef Brisket, though. My friend tried the Chicken and was very impressed.

I really hope this place remains open and thrives. The only drawback is its location at Shea & 101, which isn't very lively. It's also difficult to spot from Shea, and the lack of signage allowed in Scottsdale doesn't help.

You become what you consume, and this particular cow was fed excellently. :) (I'm talking about the actual cow, by the way - haha!) Enjoy burgers and wine, along with some beer and fries; cheers with milkshakes and enjoy crispy breaded zucchini - delicious! Ever tried zucchini in the fryer? It's as tasty as yam fries. The atmosphere was relaxed, though I could do without the artwork on the walls. I prefer my farmers in simple overalls, or if she's attractive, in short denim shorts :) The service was satisfactory; I appreciate a server who can handle a joke and respond in kind :) - Have a great time!

I've dined out previously, but this evening was merely a social gathering. Starting with the clear point: the food was mediocre, reminiscent of a two-star rating suggesting "Meh. I've had better." It seems they attempt to impress with large servings and an unnecessary amount of garnish on what they claim is a burrito. Seriously, I'd prefer something that actually tastes good! As for the service, I have no grievances; Maria Maria consistently offers excellent hospitality. The ambiance is quite chic, featuring dim lighting and elegant displays of Santana's album covers. There's live music on Fridays and Saturdays, though I hope it isn't a rock band as the noise level can become overwhelming â yes, really loud!

Try saying "Sunshine Moon Peking Pub" quickly; it might almost seem like you're speaking Chinese! I wouldn't claim it's genuine, as my mom would definitely disapprove. Nonetheless, the food here is quite satisfying. I enjoyed their nightly special, a Seabass dish, which was delicious and well-prepared. The appetizers weren't outstanding, but they were acceptable. We also tried some typical Asian-American fusion dishes like Mongolian Beef and General Tso Chicken. Speaking of which, who is General Tso? The atmosphere here is very laid-back and soothing, with Chinese characters adorning the pillarsâthough it's possible they just took some random book pages and used them as decoration. The service was excellent; our waiter was energetic and playful. Enjoy your meal!

The endless fries are a big draw!

Do I need to elaborate? I'm a fan of a tasty burger, and strangely enough, Red Robins never fails to fill me up. My top choice is the Guacamole Burger with bacon â delicious and always perfectly made! The restaurant itself feels like a chaotic fair, complete with crying infants and children running wild. If that scene isn't for you, it might be best to avoid it. I prefer to relax at the bar where children are not permitted; a wise decision indeed! The beverages are quite standard, but each server offers a unique drink that you can try â nice touch! This particular location seems louder, probably because it's near the ASU crowd and seems to attract more families due to the nearby shopping area. Anyway, it's a great spot for a quick meal! - Enjoy!

Looking for a fast lunch option? Miracle Mile can quickly prepare your sandwich. I was impressed by the speed of service, resembling an efficient assembly line. The sandwich was decent, though not exceptional. You might find similar quality at any local deli. But if you're in a hurry, it's a viable choice.

I simply don't understand the hype!

This establishment had been on my radar due to numerous mentions, so I felt compelled to check it out. Initially, it struck me as somewhat dubious and rundown. Despite previous daring culinary adventures for a burrito, I decided to give it a go. I opted for the taco platter while my sister chose the enchiladas. Retrieving hot sauce from a not-so-pristine ketchup dispenser was a gamble, and the sauce turned out to be disappointingly mild. The tacos were merely edible, though my sister's enchiladas were decent. Having grown up in the barrios of LA, I've certainly experienced superior Mexican cuisine.

The decor was unremarkable, featuring only the essentials with tables and chairs that didn't impress or stand out. It's clear that wasn't their aim. To put it bluntly, I've enjoyed much better meals and doubt I'll return for another lackluster experience. - Cheers!

I don't often eat Filipino cuisine, yet a Filipino friend assures me of its authenticity. I trust his judgment on this matter. Honestly, I prefer the meals he prepares for me. While I tend to skip some dishes, there was a curry-like beef dish that I found enjoyable. It reminded me of home cooking. The seasoning was not excessive, though it seemed a bit mild for my taste. Red Horse beer really surprised me; I usually drink whiskey, but this beer was impactful. As for the service, it seems speaking Tagalog might enhance your experience there. The ambiance is quite basic and unremarkable. On Saturday nights, it transforms into a Salsa venue, which is a clever idea for the business, although they shut down too early. Enjoy!

It's not bad; I've visited various branches, yet this one stands out as my top pick for two main reasons. Firstly, it's the nearest to my home :), and secondly, their patio is situated on the second floor with a view of the streets below. Perhaps I enjoy observing people from above and it adds to the enjoyment, haha! Gordon Biersch is renowned for their garlic friesâavoid the gym the following day if you indulge in too many, trust me! They offer their unique Gordon Biersch selection of beers. I can't name them all, but they do provide a beer tasting flight which is quite enjoyable. You should definitely consider bringing your friends here!

Located in the center of South Scottsdale, this Denny's is ideally situated for those coming from nearby nightclubs. While Denny's may not offer the finest cuisine, its meals are particularly satisfying after an evening spent enjoying shots, cocktails, and beer. Eating late isn't something I generally endorse, but it's acceptable when you're having a good time with friends. The waitresses at this location are lively and adept at managing the inebriated patrons, which is something I really value. They likely handle such situations regularly and have adapted well. The interior design is typical of Denny's establishments, with its recognizable style.

The energy of Tuscany... and its grill...wow!

It was a relaxed Sunday, having skipped the cinema because I wasn't up for queuing. I chose this spot due to its rave reviews about their Happy HourâI was feeling listless and the idea of HH was appealing. Alas, no Happy Hour on Sundays! Still, I wasn't disappointed. We ordered drinks and starters. The Raspberry Mojito I had was incredibly refreshing! We tried the Calamari, but surprisingly, the highlight was the fried peppercini peppersâthey were a hit! We even made a special request for more, and they happily accommodated usâbig thumbs up! My friend had the Steak Bruschetta, and though I don't recall her eating it, the empty plate spoke volumes!

We enjoyed our time outside on the bar patio, cooled by misters and entertained by people-watching. The service was excellent, and the drinks were plentiful. I must say, I plan to return for Happy Hour next time. Cheers!

The terrace is spacious and can accommodate many people, adorned with Christmas lights and a water fountain that evoke the opening scene of Friends - I'll definitely be there for you!

I visited this place with my friends and we had a buffet. Despite this, I feel compelled to review it. We started with a fresh baby green salad dressed in balsamic vinaigrette, but unfortunately, the meal quality declined rapidly from there. Beginning with the pork; it was so tough and dry that I struggled to swallow it despite much chewing, and the chili flakes on top only exacerbated the issue. The stuffed chicken was served with a creamy sauce, though its flavor was overshadowed by the pork. The addition of mashed potatoes seemed to further dry out my mouth.

However, a friend pointed out that we ended up eating dishes we hadn't ordered. This was a fortunate twist! I plan to revisit and provide a comprehensive review, so keep an eye out for that.

It's a mixed feeling for me; I'm not a big fan of sushi, yet I often find myself dining at sushi places because that's where the group goes. As someone who doesn't usually eat sushi, I surprisingly liked Blue Wasabi. Perhaps it's the unique "blue wasabi" that sets it apart. The drinks are somewhat expensive, though I haven't visited during happy hour or on "Special Blue Days" when wearing a blue shirt might get you a discount. The service is decent, though I wonder why they don't wear blue uniforms, considering the theme. Maybe they should try Blue Sailor Moon uniforms! What a concept! Enjoy!

Is it okay to declare burgers as my comfort food? When everything else disappoints, thereâs truly nothing comparable to a great burger accompanied by sweet potato fries - delicious! I adore sweet potato fries; just chop up some yams and toss them into the fryer. Opt for the Deluxe Burger - itâs a sure bet. Why not include a beer flight? Indeed, beer flights, not beers that fly - you have the opportunity to sample three different beers! "Homer Simpson - Woo Hoo!" I also appreciate the atmosphere - BLUE - thatâs all I need to mention. Regarding the service, honestly, for a small establishment, thereâs room for improvement, though I canât point out anything specifically wrong - Enjoy!

This is one of my top picks for Irish pubs! I really enjoy the vibe and the live performances. Sitting out on the terrace when the weather is good is an ideal spot for some drinks. You have to try the fish and chips, and the Shepherd's Pie is both tasty and satisfying. Ever heard of a Snakebite? Yes, the cocktail, not the injury â definitely give it a go! It brings out the Irish in me... what exactly does that entail? It's curious to think if the Irish and Chinese cultures have ever intertwined historically... perhaps they have? (Interestingly, the film "The Departed" is a remake of a Chinese trilogy called "Infernal Affairs.") The service here is impressively swift, especially considering it can get quite busy, though my visits are usually earlier in the day. Every time I've been, it's been so packed I could barely move â and that's pretty much every time I've gone to Rula Bula! Enjoy your visit!

Sushi Ken is reputed for their Udon noodles, yet curiously, they're not called Udon Ken.

I visited this place with some friends following a short hike, feeling quite famished. I really appreciate their affordable lunch prices, but opted for the noodles on a friend's recommendation over sushi and sashimi.

The presentation of the Soba Noodles I chose was pleasing, though they were just okay overall. They didn't stand out as anything extraordinary from my recollection. The opinions from others at my table varied, but ultimately, my opinion is what matters most to me! I'm looking forward to another visit to Sushi Ken to try their renowned Udon Noodles. So, keep an eye out for updates.

While there, we tried to watch Jeremy Lin in action, but the small screen size made it difficult for anyone without perfect vision to follow along. A larger screen would definitely enhance the experience for guests and reflect better on the restaurant. Just something to consider. - Cheers!

I must admit, the design and atmosphere of the place caught my attention the moment I entered; it was cool, contemporary, and sleek. However, the cuisine didn't quite meet my expectations. I prefer my Thai food to be robust and spicy, needing more hydration to handle the heat â just like a knockout punch from Mama! Yet, this spot didn't quite deliver that impact; it was alright, but lacked that extra oomph. Kudos to the staff and their service, though, they were efficient and accommodating. They even offered me a taste of a beer I was unfamiliar with â much appreciated! I would certainly suggest giving this spot a try during Happy Hour. Enjoy your visit!

Our AA group convened here last Saturday evening under the guise of Affordable Alcohol. The ambiance truly catered to the mardi gras and college demographic, quite dive-like in its essence. The patrons, however, were quite amiable. I can't recall the specific tunes playing, yet they were notably loud and intense. I do remember being told about the bar's owner, an elderly gentleman appearing to be around 90, who was energetically dancing with a young woman on the dance floor. Impressive! Keep up the spirit! The venue featured pool tables which seemed out of place in the crowded space, but probably fit well on quieter nights. I'd recommend giving the punching strength game a goâit's a blast! The drinks were reasonably priced, and the attendees were distinctly different from the usual Scottsdale type. Cheers to a great night out!

Truly rapid departure indeed!

It wasn't exactly speedy, yet the food was notably salty. I prefer just a hint of salt, but it seemed as though they emptied an entire sack into it. The hot and sour soup I tried was exceptionally sour. Additionally, when I tried the House Special Chicken, the overwhelming saltiness really struck me hard. Incredible!

Visually, the establishment wasn't attractive. I was concerned about possibly falling ill from the meal, but fortunately, my immune system was robust enough to ward off any issues from the excess salt. Best wishes and have a great meal!

Odd Love, peculiar peaks and peculiar valleys,
Odd Love, that is the nature of my affection
(Depeche Mode)

Yet, you will not cause me suffering!

Curiously, this establishment was situated in a commercial plaza adjacent to a Starbucks and a cinema. I view this positively due to the bustling activity. Sushi, coffee, and a film make a great combination! Their website was visually appealing, though it often fails to capture the full experience.

Odd, the choices on the menu. Geoduck, giant clams, and round clams, these aren't usually what I crave for dinner, but I'm adventurous enough to give them a try. I may not have a PhD (Doctorate in Phood!) yet, but I was quite taken by the experience. My dining companions are well-versed in sushi and provided valuable insights. They praised the Round Clam prepared three ways - Nigiri, Sashimi, and Fried -- Cheers & Nod! I particularly enjoyed their Geoduck, a delicacy that's best served fresh and raw. Although I'm not an expert in sushi, my preferred dish was the salmon wrapped in avocado, as showcased in Yelp Photos.

Strange? Actually, it turns out to be not so strange. It's certainly worth a visit, and I highly recommend HMS - don't forget to greet Steve, he's a great guy :) - Enjoy!

The name might have been a giveaway â just a slight hint of Thai, not too overpowering, or it could be too much. I personally prefer a stronger Thai flavor. The food was quite good, although a bit on the expensive side. I did enjoy the Dragon Noodles, though. The service was friendly but somewhat slow, possibly because there were only a few other diners. I really liked the calm, relaxing atmosphere of the place. My main issue, however, was the excessive quietness. It was so silent that I felt the need to speak softly as if someone might overhear my conversations. (Yes, if I were a girl, I would definitely date him...strange thought!) - Enjoy!

This is one of the rare Chinese eateries I enjoy. Portions aren't the largest, yet they're made with attention to detail. While not the most visually appealing, it's tidy and spacious. It's ideal for sharing a substantial meal with many friends. Typically located in a strip mall, the food is excellent despite the mediocre setting.

A top Pho spot in the East Valley known for its ample servings and high-quality proteins. I typically choose vermicelli noodles topped with grilled beef or pork, and sometimes add fried egg rolls if I deserve a treat. The spring rolls have slightly too many bean sprouts, but that's a small complaint. I just wish it were closer.

Reliable Italian cuisine offered here. Bread is served with garlic butter alongside a superb spicy pepper and olive oil mixture. The meals are solid, albeit not extraordinary; I appreciate that they're not overly heavy or salty. They excel in catering services too. You'll find the portions ample and the proprietor exceptionally gracious. He often mingles, inviting guests to choose a number for a chance to win a free meal. The decor inside is quite attractive, though the clientele tends to be older, a trend I hope shifts. Ideal for a swift, subdued business lunch.

Quick lunch deals are good. Consistent, amiable service. More customization would be better; for instance, all diners receive the same starters like eggrolls and soup. However, for a quick meal, it's a solid choice, though not as upscale as Wile Thaiger or Thai Basil. It's an ideal informal lunch spot for colleagues. Not suitable for client meetings, as it retains an old diner's appearance with vinyl booths, but for lunch under $8, it's excellent.

The drink selection and happy hour offerings at this spot are top-notch. With downtown coming alive, it was time for a fresh hangout beyond the usual spots like the butcher and Hanny's. Blue Hound boasts an excellent general manager, a skilled mixologist, and attentive staff. Their menu features classic and innovative cocktails, including some with scotch. The lunch deals are so generous they might induce a food coma, and sharing during dinner might be tough if your companions prefer not to or desire more conventional dishes. (They might be a bit generous with the salt, in my opinion). I spend so much time here, I might as well set up a small office by the large communal table. Actually, thatâs a great idea.
Top eats: Flatbreads, caramel corn, falafel bites, anything from the lunch offerings.
Top drinks: The new Hemingway, the new Cuban, anything with bourbon or scotch.
The clientele is an eclectic blend of corporate types and trendy folks, though the vibe is more relaxed at the upstairs bar.

I enjoyed this venue during a soul night featuring an incredible band. They kicked off with lively songs, some unfamiliar, and concluded with an impressive Michael Jackson mashup that got everyone on their feet. The main issue is the venue's small size. With a tiny dance floor and popular bands, it becomes quite packed. A few tables are available (which you might need to reserve hours ahead), and there's a decently sized bar for drinks. This spot reminds me of bars in different cities; it doesn't feel like Phoenix. The atmosphere is welcoming, with everyone eager to enjoy and dance. It's heartwarming to see couples of various ages having fun togetherâthe sight of their affection is genuinely touching.

Charming eatery with delightful sandwiches, though on the expensive side, each served with a pickle. The place is adorned with numerous knick-knacks and foreign goods. Definitely worth checking out. The downtown branch lacks the same appeal. Opt for custom-ordered sandwiches over standard sandwich platters like roast beef and turkey.

I've only visited during lunchtime. They offer appealing dinner deals like a wine and pizza combo for $20, which I often overlook. The meals, especially the salads, are delightful. Their bruschetta selection is excellent, featuring three tasty varieties. They serve hummus and salads, perfect for a ladies' lunch. Men generally find it satisfactory, thanks to a decent selection of burgers and sandwiches, though it feels more like a women's wine bar. Parking can be challenging, so consider carpooling.

Meh, it's not as divey as DJ's, which I appreciate since they own their dive status. It's alright. The patrons vary, many visiting for spring training. Music can be inconsistent. The bartenders remain friendly despite the busy atmosphere. A stripper pole with a fan attached in one corner always provides entertainment.

Eh, it's alright. Enjoyed the salmon, found it tasty. Appetizers are decent, and the PBR served in a paper bag is somewhat kitschy. The issue seems to be that the venue is overly fashionable, making the rather ordinary food not worth navigating the packed scene for a meal. It's extremely noisy inside, and the bar area is packed. Everyone looks great. Not a complaint, just noting I'd prefer if the food matched the aesthetics. The menu combines comfort dishes with the latest popular ingredients from trendy eateries. Nonetheless, it's good to have an additional choice when puzzled about dining options near the mall.

Charming eatery. The guacamole is tasty and made fresh, though it lacks some zestâperhaps more lime or chili. All their dishes share this trait: decent but needing a bit more flair. The food isn't buried under cheese, which I appreciated. It's not the usual Mexican fare; it's lighter and pleasantly less salty. I'll return for another visit when in the mood for milder tastes. It's like the yin to Los Dos Molina's yang.

Undoubtedly, this place serves one of the finest Apple Pies locally. I haven't tried their sandwiches, which look tempting and fresh. I usually pop in for a quick sugar boost before heading back to work. Their large display features an array of cakes, cupcakes, and pies. They offer mini-cupcakes too, for those concerned about sugar and fat. Every baked item I've tried here has been exceptional. However, the pie is a mustâperfectly blended apples, cinnamon, and a crust that remains crisp without the greasy feel often found in other pies like those from Marie Callendar's. It's delicious, available by the slice, and truly a slice of heaven for around four dollars. It's a smarter way to spend my lottery winnings than usual.

Stumbled upon this charming spot and enjoyed it. The salsa doesn't compare to the red sauce enriched with garlic hints. Tried the three-way burro enchilada style, and my dining companion chose the chicken version. The servings are generous given the cost. Can I declare it the ultimate burro experience? Probably not. However, the horchata is tasty, service is solid, and nothing is overly spicy. At times, I crave spice, but occasionally, I prefer other tastes enhanced by a subtle kick. This place is a great option when you want to skip the long lines at Tortas del Rey or have visitors who aren't keen on spicy food.

Happy to note that replacements arrived as Oakville departed. All salads are tasty, pizza varies, yet their grilled cheese is excellent, especially with tomato soup. For Oakville's former patrons, a delightful bakery counter awaits, stocked with treats like Essence Macaroons and Julia Baker chocolates. Enjoy a healthy meal at Chloe's before visiting the bakery counter :)

I was eager to enjoy this establishment. The menu appeared appetizing, boasting healthful options under 500 calories and an attractive setting. Starting with the positives: the venue was bustling (usually a promising indicator for me, suggesting frequent food turnover), featured an inviting bar, and hosted a talented pianist reminiscent of the prime days at Old Eddie V's.

Upon ordering, I found the quail breasts and salads to be quite satisfying, though the flatbread was mediocre. The issue wasn't a lack of butter or cream, but rather a lack of culinary passion. It felt as though a culinary student was preparing meals for a final exam, restricted from expressing his creativity. My realization that it was managed by the same corporation that runs Olive Garden clarified a lot.

Adjacent to Lee Lee market, this spot is ideal for a quick stop before grocery shopping. Observe the chefs crafting amazing noodlesâit's the first venue in Phoenix offering genuine hand-pulled noodles, a true art form. The patience and skill required to transform basic elements like flour, water, and salt into beautiful noodles is astounding. They offer a variety of shapes, from wide and flat to slim and fine.

Each noodle type enhances different sauces and toppings, and the waitstaff excels at suggesting the best match for your chosen toppings. Tea incurs an additional charge, which is slightly irritating, but overall, there are few grounds for complaint. The place must be doing something right, as it's frequently filled with eager Asian diners.

Latest update: Carly's has become my favorite lunch spot outside the city center. I've grown tired of dining at the Butcher (yes, the pretentious one) and now prefer grabbing a panini or salad here. The orzo salad could use a bit more salt, but pairing it with their delicious balsamic vinaigrette (which enhances almost anything) solves that issue. Also, I consistently opt for the panini on focaccia over ciabatta, as the latter often becomes too tough or overly crispy for my liking. Brunch here remains lackluster.

Arrive with an appetite; the servings are large and delicious. Sharing with companions is my preference. The dishes have a kick, yet aren't overpowering. A touch of crema on most offerings brings joy. Unique options like duck enchiladas aren't common elsewhere. Additionally, their beverages are excellent and not overly sweet.

I had high expectations. The servings are adequate, and the food is tasty, though it could be more generous given the cost, especially since it's located on Mill Avenue. Oddly, it feels somewhat misplaced there. On the Sunday we visited, we enjoyed several sangrias, pizzas, and bruschetta boards. The bruschetta board stood out as the most delicious, yet it didn't leave me as full as Postino's doesâperhaps its tastiness made me crave more. The sangria was nice, but the pitcher seemed excessively filled with ice and orange slices for what it cost. The decor inside is quite attractive. It seems like a spot where upscale college students might date (a nice alternative to House of Tricks before a Gammage show!). On our visit, there was a large group of women celebrating a bridal shower, clearly enjoying themselves. It's worth noting the restaurant can handle big groups and events well.
Typical ice cream shop. Charming location, but the ice cream sandwiches were overly sweet, using Otis Spunkmeyer cookies. They do offer frozen bananas though!

Unsure if the rumor that Houston's changed its name to Hillstone to sidestep calorie disclosure laws due to its number of outlets is true, but it doesn't bother me. It remains Houston's, albeit now with an odd choice of sushi on the menu. I doubt sushi garners many orders; I'd prefer that space be converted into a dessert or additional bar. They still serve the excellent veggie burger, now slightly sweeter with beet inclusion, and the fried chicken salad. I'm not interested in knowing the calorie count, so their secrecy is fine by me. The new venue is spacious, featuring a piano and a vast patio, and is brighter than the former one, thanks to ample windows. I adore the massive double doors, reminiscent of a bank, and the charming little koi pond.

Delightful family-owned restaurant. Superb ceviche and the molcajete is a favoriteâit arrives sizzling, overflowing with seafood delights in a volcanic stone bowl. The chips might need improvement, yet the abundant Pacificos served usually distract from this minor detail.

A top-notch secluded resort. It's romantic and discreet, with highly accommodating staff. The casitas are well-separated, ensuring patio privacy. Room rates vary seasonally and can be quite reasonable. Although the pool area is smaller relative to newer resorts, it has been elegantly renovated.

This exceptional bakery is operated by a Taiwanese duo who've owned it for decades. They're renowned for their whipped cream-frosted cakes (possibly using a non-dairy alternative) which resemble a firmer cool-whip. Among their extensive cake selection, I favor the fresh mango, fresh fruit, and chocolate cakes. Note that their coconut cake uses young coconut meat instead of flakes. Additionally, they offer mini desserts and highly caffeinated coffee jellos at $2.50 each. They handle both large sheet and wedding cakes, offering prices more competitive than other local bakeries, though they skip the trendy fondant decorations. Their cakes are simple yet delightful, featuring various fruits or fillings beneath a whipped cream layer, always available fresh in the refrigerated section. For the best variety, it's advisable to order ahead or visit directly. Their menu also includes Asian desserts and meat buns, with special discounts on unsold baked goods in the evening to ensure freshness. Typically closing at six, they're almost always open. I endlessly admire this place as a major dessert enthusiast; their treats strike the perfect balance of sweetness and moisture. I always choose their cakes for my birthday, and they never disappoint.

This spot remains bustling as it feeds famished jurors confined in the grand jury room's basement. The carpet, likely untouched since the Nixon years, matches the quite ordinary food. Nevertheless, everyone should visit at least once to claim they've a) endured it, b) experienced it, and c) unexpectedly yearned for it. While most choose a, a few opt for c. It's a classic Phoenix tradition that deserves support!

Opt for the unusual offerings, such as random Japanese soda, fruit, and pudding cups on the conveyor. This venue is popular, so make a reservation if you anticipate hunger. I prefer simple sushi and openly admit to eating around the rice when full. The rolls often become monotonous, typically containing crab mix, mayo, and cream cheese. Securing a table near the kitchen offers a prime view of hot dishes, allowing you to pick them up fresh. Sake bombs cost only $5âa real bargain. The amount you can eat for the price will astonish you.

Ideal for a swift coffee or snack, and excellent for breakfast too. The oatmeal rivals that of Taylor's Cafe, while the omelettes, accompanied by a delightful sweet potato hash, are quite deliciousâI wish it were more common elsewhere. If you're here primarily for coffee, you'll find the pastries surpass those at Starbucks. Feel free to browse and pick up some groceries while you're at it (prices are akin to Whole Foods), adding to its local charm. However, parking can be tricky; consider carpooling.

Absolutely adore this spot! I admit I'm somewhat lazy and avoid driving to their North Scottsdale location. Instead, I visit the mobile food truck run by the very friendly and kind owner. The flavors are exceptional. You can tell there's a lot of care and effort put into infusing high-quality ingredients into the custard base. Unlike Cold Stone's overly rich ice creams that feel like eating frozen lard, here the cream and milk are perfectly balanced. I've tried various tea-flavored ice creamsâChai is unforgettable, Jasmine a bit too mild, and green tea is simply sublimeâas well as the heavenly salted caramel. The Madagascar Vanilla might just change your mind about the clichÃ© of calling mundane things "vanilla." The Lavender Honey is a bit too strong for my taste, perhaps just an off day, with not enough honey and too much lavender. Definitely worth trying, though it's not the cheapest, you're supporting a genuine artisan.

Breakfast clearly outshines the rest. I usually skip their lunch offerings. However, be aware that the breakfast options aren't healthy, except perhaps for the oatmeal. They prepare a good eggs benedict, served with heaps of potatoes. The pancakes resemble a dessert more than a morning meal. A minor complaint? No diet coke available!

A new option for downtown dining has emerged. It's a middle ground, situated between the lawyer and politically frequented Arrogant Butcher, and what's jokingly referred to as "Celtic-Hooters," actually the Tilted Kilt above. The menu presents an intriguing array of starters, though it's lacking in salad options for my liking. When compared to Arrogant Butcher and probably Tilted Kilt, it offers fewer salads and fried items, making it challenging to opt for something healthy. The offerings lean towards comfort foods, featuring dishes like chili paired with cornbread souffle, and flatbreads accompanied by burrata fondue. The menu includes several flatbread varieties, their take on pizza. On my visit, the lunch crowd was bustling. (Entry is via a lobby shared with Stand Up Live). I missed the opportunity to sample their impressive beer collection, but I plan to next time I attend a show. The staff and management are exceedingly welcoming. (Not overly so, but in a manner that enhances your experience). This contrasts starkly with the often unpleasant service at Lucky Strike nearby. I'm hopeful they maintain their success.

The cuisine and drinks are exceptional. Entry is via a side entrance. It resembles an underground cellar in appearance and ambiance. Choosing the cheese fondue or various small dishes is a safe bet. I generally steer clear of evenings when a jazz band performs, as it becomes overly noisy for me. Many couples frequent the place, making it a hit or miss depending on your preference. Bigger parties often struggle to find seating, and there might be a wait for the bathrooms.

This spot is straightforward, featuring massive, tasty-filled tortas, though the bread doesn't fit the bill. Street taco seekers won't find them superior to Gallo's. It's decent for a fast bite but not a major hotspot. Seating is scarce, clearly more of a takeout joint. It's stylish and charming with efficient service and a concise menu. A highlight is the self-serve salsa bar offering fresh salsas and crema.

The Caesar salad is incredibly addictive. The meals are expensive, yet dining beneath the stars on the patio erases all worries. I prefer dinner here over lunch. It's ideal for celebrating special events.

It's challenging to squeeze in a quick lunch here. If you're not rushed or visiting during happy hour, expect creatively updated comfort dishes (think hotel version of Tuck Shop). Offerings include Mac and Cheese with Schreiner's Sausage, Pulled Pork sliders, and mini corn-dogs. The crab cake salad is tasty, and the dark wood paneling sets a corporate vibe. The staff, though inexperienced, are welcoming. Pricing is typical for hotel dining spots, yet this place feels more spacious and bright. I haven't focused much on the food; it's decent but not the type to spark lengthy discussions. It's safe and satisfying, ideal for visitors.

Finally got to check out Windsor after much buzz. It's the trendy new hotspot right across from Arcadia Central. Regulars from there likely hop over to Windsor too. The architecture is stunning with exceptional dining ambiance lightingâa definite highlight for me (helps me appear younger and fresher). The cocktails are delightful, inventive, yet a tad small for my liking, served in almost full martini glasses. Beers are available in "shorty" sizes, an adorable idea reminiscent of complimentary tasting flights at some breweries. The food is delicious. Similar to Chelsea's kitchen and Arcadia, they offer excellent bread and sides. The kale salad and roasted veggies were great, though the latter was a bit too rich in olive oil. The mac and cheese and salmon chowder were hits, but the crab cake sandwich lacked flavor despite containing crab. The Chicago dog was well-received. Having pistachios to snack on at each table was a thoughtful gesture. I'll return, preferably during quieter times.
Avoid this spot if you're concerned about cholesterol. It's tasty and straightforward. Carry cash and come hungry. The fried chicken and waffles here are unmatched in the city.

Fez offers tasty, garlicky dishes. Service could improve as they often appear short-staffed, despite their efforts. They feature appealing happy hour deals, though parking may be difficult. The atmosphere is enhanced by good music and ambiance. Their hummus, vegetarian burger, and fez saladâeither with shrimp or gyroâare excellent. Definitely worth visiting, especially since it's accessible via light rail. Also, the sweet potato fries are incredibly delicious, almost like candy!

Visited for afternoon tea with pals. Opt to indulge in the tea and consider adding 15 dollars for endless sparkling wine. Geoffrey, the tea expert, will keep your glass as full as your teacup. His coconut jasmine blend was my top pickâtruly divine. Initially concerned about the quantity of food, I found the dessert course satisfyingly filling. The scones, served with clotted cream, raspberry jam, and lemon curd, are outstanding. Utterly luxurious and divine. The live piano music enhances the experience, offering a refreshing break from our usual outings. Note the additional "tea service" fee atop gratuity and tax, but it's definitely worth it.

Switch resembles the younger kin of the Fez/Ticoz conglomerate. I'm aware of its presence and often pass by, yet seldom consider dining there. The offerings are dependable for lunch, featuring sandwiches and saladsânothing overly spiced or extravagant. It often gets packed during lunch hours, and the service can be inconsistent. At times, I'm seated immediately, other times, there's a delay; it's really just the luck of the draw, not the waitstaff's fault. I typically opt for a salad, which is filling, or a sandwich. For those feeling indulgent, there's mac and cheese or their gallettes, essentially phyllo dough pockets. I haven't tried brunch there, though I've heard positive reviews. Additionally, they tempt with cookies near the entrance, perfect for a quick sugar fix on your way out.

Mac and Cheese tastes great, while the burger is okay; however, the standout is their drinks, making it a worthwhile visit. They offer a creative cocktail menu. The music tends to be loud, and the crowd is often trendy, which can be intimidating, but it's the perfect spot for a post-work drink or a relaxing brunch. The venue boasts a beautiful interior with attractive patrons.
I believe I'm alone in my dislike for these. Sprinkles seems overly sweet and occasionally dry. While the flavors seem appealing, their delivery falls short. They're also costly.
